<FIRST>u i AM-SriLanka     04-12 0530</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka,0547</SECOND>
<HEAD>26 Sinhalese Militants Surrender</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government on Wednesday declared a
week-long cease-fire with Sinhalese and Tamil rebels, and an
official said 26 Sinhalese militants surrendered under President
Ranasinghe Premadasa's peace plan.
   The militants, belonging to the Marxist People's Liberation
Front, gave themselves up at temples and government offices
Wednesday, said the military official, who cannot be identified
under briefing rules. He did not give details.
   Premadasa, seeking to end six years of ethnic violence that has
claimed 12,500 lives, announced a general amnesty and unilateral
cease-fire to Sinhalese and Tamil rebels.
   The offer was part of a peace package that included seats in
Parliament and jobs for the militants. The cease-fire began a day
before Sinhalese and Tamils celebrate a common new year.
   The government also set up 228 centers at schools, temples and
government offices across the country where the rebels could give
themselves up.
   The front has not yet responded to the truce offer but the
largest Tamil militant group, campaigning to set up an independent
state in Northern and Northeastern Provinces, rejected it outright
Tuesday.
   However, ``the militants have a week to surrender and it is too
early to make a decision about the response to the surrender
call,'' the military official said.
   No militants surrendered in the capital. The chief priest of
Buddhist temples in Colombo said ``nobody turned up'' at the
shrines where reception centers were set up for receiving the
rebels.
   An official at a reception center in Weligama, 85 miles south of
Colombo, said on the telephone: ``We have a whole lot of armed
police here but nobody to surrender.''
   The south is the Sinhalese heartland where the Marxist rebels
are most active. The extremists have been blamed for more than
2,500 political killings since January and most of the victims have
been government officials and security men.
   The militants have been trying to topple the government since
July 1987 when it signed a peace accord aimed at ending the Tamil
separatist campaign.
   The left-wing extremists say the accord gave the minority Tamils
too many concessions. They also say the presence of Indian troops,
deployed to disarm the Tamil rebels and enforce the 1987 accord,
compromises the country's independence.
   An Indian High Commission or embassy offical said Indian troops
will continue to carry out operations against the Tamil rebels.
   But the troops will not hinder the ``process of surrendering,''
said the offical who cannot be identified under briefing rules.
   The dominant Tamil rebel group, Liberation Tigers of Tamil
Eelam, said Tuesday: ``We will not agree to any cease-fire so long
as the Indian army remains in Sri Lanka.''
   India became involved in the conflict because of the sympathies
of its own 60 million Tamils to the rebel cause.
   Tamil militants launched a campaign in 1983 for an independent
homeland, citing discrimination by the majority Sinhalese in
employment and education.
   Tamils comprise 18 percent of Sri Lanka's 16 million people.
Most live in the Northern and Northeastern Provinces, where they
want their homeland. Sinhalese make up 75 percent of the island's
population and control the government and military.
</TEXT>
