<FIRST>r a PM-Spill-Defenders     04-12 0670</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Spill-Defenders,0691</SECOND>
<HEAD>Battle Against Oil Slick: Lonely And Frustrating</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Wednesday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FRED BAYLES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP National Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ABOARD THE COMMITMENT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For 11 days, Guido Casciano has
fought the battle of Sawmill Bay, riding herd on wave after wave of
oil with his nimble 27-foot fishing boat.
   For 11 nights, he has slept in the boat's tiny cabin so he'd be
ready at first light to continue the deadening routine of coralling
oil away from the salmon hatchery up the bay.
   ``It's fairly boring, but hopefully we're doing some good
here,'' he said.
   Casciano and his fellow fishermen have done some good. But their
rescue of the hatchery is a brief skirmish in a losing fight to
limit the damage of 10 million gallons of crude oil spilled from
the tanker Exxon Valdez.
   ``It's really frustrating when you consider what little you're
accomplishing with all the effort here,'' said Gary Raymond, who
had his 48-foot Sound Adventure working with Casciano's Commitment
on Monday. ``When you think about what little oil you've picked up,
it blows your mind.''
   The view from above Prince William Sound speaks to the seeming
futility of the cleanup effort.
   The lower end of the sound is a checkerboard of oil. Rainbow
swirls of oil nudge the shore in the hundreds of lonely bays and
inlets. Mud-colored oil streamers stripe the deep green water of
the open sound.
   The powerful forces of nature have taken man's mistake and
scattered it hundreds of miles.
   No one knows this better than fishermen like Casciano and
Raymond, neighbors from Cordova who have looked to the sound for
their living.
   While officials dusted off contingency plans and held assessment
meetings, the fishermen of the sound streamed out of towns like
Cordova and Seward to do what they could.
   Most went without knowing they would be compensated for their
efforts. Casciano and Raymond were at Sawmill Bay for five days
before they received contracts from Exxon, the only contact they
have had with the company responsible for the spill.
   ``All of us figured that if nothing else, at least we're out
here doing something,'' said Casciano.
   The independent fishermen organized their own battle plan. Booms
were floated across the inner bay. The fishing boats took what
materials they could get and began collecting the oil, using the
same techniques they have used for years for fishing.
   A yellow, oil-smeared boom was attached at one end to
Commitment, the other to Sound Adventure. Using hand signals and
radio calls, the two boats moved in graceful ballet until clumps of
oil, resembling greasy brown oatmeal, were snared in the boom.
   The strategy is similar to the way two boats can use seining
nets to trap schools of salmon and herring.
   The oil was then floated to a ``sucker boat,'' a Navy skimmer
that sluices the oil from the water and into a small barge.
   But often, over the past two weeks, there has been no skimmer to
feed. The special boats can only swallow 32 barrels of oil before
their tanks are filled and they have to go unload.
   Whatever the fishermen are paid for the effort will fall short
of the cost of what the spill may do their way of life.
   Raymond lost at least $40,000 when the spill canceled the
herring harvest. In normal times, his wife and daughter would be on
the boat with him for weeks, helping catch fish.
   Carolyn Raymond was aboard Sound Adventure on Monday after
flying out to be with her husband. ``Everybody back at town is
worried that our way of life may be over,'' she said.
   Both the Raymonds and Casciano are pessimistic about what their
efforts mean against the massive amount of oil and unrelenting
forces of nature. But they say it is better to be on the water,
doing something, then sitting ashore.
   ``Maybe what you do is not going to make a dent, but you've got
to try to do something to help,'' said Raymond.

</TEXT>
</DOC>
