<FIRST>r i PM-BRF--AiredBedding     04-12 0141</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Aired Bedding,0142</SECOND>
<HEAD>Swiss Housewife Appeals Fine For Airing Duvet</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A housewife is appealing a $25 fine for airing her
bedding after 10 a.m., saying the 30-year-old law that prohibits
the practice is outdated.
   The woman has enlisted the help of a biochemist to back her
claim that heavy pollution during morning rush hour makes it
impossible to air her bedding ``legally,'' Geneva's La Suisse
newspaper reported.
   Under 1955 public hygiene regulations in Geneva, anyone living
in an urban area who hangs duvets or carpets out of windows or over
balconies in public view after 10 a.m. can be fined.
   The clause, which remained in obscurity, made headlines in Swiss
newspapers Tuesday when the housewife, identified only as Claudine,
appealed the fine she received after a zealous policeman spotted
her offending duvet 30 minutes after the deadline.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
