<FIRST>r i PM-BRF--Koran     04-12 0171</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Koran,0176</SECOND>
<HEAD>Record Price For A Koran</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A miniature Koran by an unknown 10th century
scribe was bought at auction for a record $297,000 for a European
collection, Christie's said.
   The auction house said the price paid Tuesday for the little
book of 332 vellum pages, less than three inches tall and written
in Eastern kufic script, was the highest ever paid for a Koran or
part of one.
   ``Finely written small Korans are much prized and very
saleable,'' said Caroline Blyth, the firm's head of Islamic
manuscripts.
   ``This one was very old and had the status of coming from the
estate of Crown Prince Muhammad Hasan Mirza Qajar, the sole
pretender to the throne of the Qajar dynasty in Persia which ended
in the 1920s,'' she said.
   The buyer was only identified as representing a European
collection. Christie's had put a top estimate on the Koran of
$169,000.
   A single decorated leaf from a large Koran made the previous
record of $268,000 in London in October.
</TEXT>
