<FIRST>r a PM-Nielsens     04-12 0505</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nielsens,0516</SECOND>
<HEAD>CBS Drives for Hoop, but NBC Slam-Dunks Another Week</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Last year, the NCAA championship basketball game
gave CBS a rare first place for the week in the A.C. Nielsen Co.
television ratings.
   This year's game, in which Michigan defeated Seton Hall by one
point in overtime, was in the top 10. But it wasn't enough to knock
NBC out of first place, where it has been for 42 straight weeks.
   NBC won the week that ended Sunday with a 15.4 rating. CBS had a
13.0 and ABC 12.5. For the season, NBC has a 16.0 rating, ABC 12.9
and CBS 12.6.
   The week was fairly typical, except that the onset of daylight
saving time seemed to affect the earlier shows since viewers tend
to be less eager to plop in front of the tube when it's still light
outside.
   Therefore, ``The Cosby Show,'' which starts off the night for
NBC on Thursday, found itself in second place behind ABC's
``Roseanne,'' which is broadcast an hour later on Tuesday night,
even though ``Cosby'' had a bigger share of the audience.
   ``Roseanne'' had the highest rating _ 23.3, but a 35 share.
``Cosby'' had a 22.4 rating, but a 38 share. The rating is a
percentage of the nation's 9.4 million homes with television. The
share is a percentage of sets actually in use.
   Daylight saving time also affected the news ratings, all were
down somewhat. ``ABC World News Tonight'' was first with a 10.1
rating and a 20 share, slightly ahead of the ``CBS Evening News''
with a 9.9 and 20 share. ``NBC Nightly News'' had an 8.9 and 18
share.
   The top 10 prime-time shows last week were: ``Roseanne'' ABC,
``The Cosby Show'' NBC, ``Cheers'' NBC, ``A Different World'' NBC,
``60 Minutes'' CBS, ``NCAA Championship _ Michigan vs. Seton Hall''
CBS, ``Golden Girls'' NBC, ``Empty Nest'' NBC, ``L.A. Law'' NBC and
``Murder, She Wrote'' CBS.
   ABC's ``Columbo'' came in 12th for the week, a good showing. The
bad news for ABC is ``Moonlighting,'' which was in the bottom 10.
``Moonlighting'' went on hiatus earlier this year, then moved to
Sunday night where it had a 6.2 and 10 share last week. Only two
other prime-time shows, both on ABC, rank lower: ``HeartBeat'' and
``Men.'' Even Fox had three shows with higher ratings than
``Moonlighting.''
   CBS got a so-so performance out of the premiere of ``The Robert
Guillaume Show'' which finished 46th.
   ABC won the Sunday movie battle with a repeat of ``Romancing the
Stone.'' It was 15th, out-rating NBC's Perry Mason movie, at 18th.
CBS' ``Bridge to Silence,'' starring Marlee Matlin in her first
speaking role, ranked 35th. CBS' Sunday schedule was pushed back
because of an overrun of the Masters golf tournament.
   The lowest-rated shows of the week were: ``Hard Time on Planet
Earth,'' ``Mission Impossible,'' ``Rock 'n' Roll Mom,'' ``Quantum
Leap,'' ``Sesame Street: 20 and Still Counting,'' ``Great Circuses
of the World,'' ``A Man Called Hawk,'' ``Moonlighting,
``HeartBeat'' and ``Men.''
</TEXT>
