<FILEID>AP-NR-04-12-89 0021EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u p AM-LAMayor 1stLd-Writethru a0670 04-12 0674</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-LA Mayor, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0670,0694</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bradley Seeks Fifth Term as Mayor, Low Voter Turnout Reported</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE with Bradley early leader, UPDATE
turnout; picks up 3rd graf, ``Although virtually ...''</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA10</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JUDY FARAH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tom Bradley was the early leader in his
campaign for a historic fifth term as mayor of the nation's
second-largest city, capturing 54 percent of the absentee vote in a
race characterized by low voter turnout.
   Bradley, 71, the city's first black mayor, needed at least 50
percent of the vote to avoid a June 6 runoff.
   Forty-five minutes after the polls closed at 8 p.m., Bradley was
in the lead with 13,146 absentee ballots, or 54 percent, according
to the City Clerk's Office.
   The next-closest contender was freshman City Councilman Nate
Holden, who received 5,014 absentee votes, or 20.66 percent. Former
Los Angeles County Supervisor and television commentator Baxter
Ward had 4,800 votes, or 19.7 percent.
   Although virtually no observers believed the mayor could lose,
one newspaper reported that a secret poll conducted by Bradley's
campaign last week showed the mayor with just 53 percent of the
vote.
   Bradley pollster Richard Maullin told the Los Angeles Herald
Examiner that the polls conducted April 2 and 3 contained questions
checking the impact of a city attorney's office ethics
investigation of Bradley.
   But, Maullin said, ``None of the results showed Tom Bradley not
winning outright.''
   City Clerk Lee Martinez had predicted a 25 percent to 30 percent
turnout _ ``a historical low for a mayoral election.'' Voters faced
morning low clouds and drizzle, and the turnout by 4 p.m. was only
11.6 percent of the city's 1.9 million registered voters.
   A poll taken recently by The Los Angeles Times showed 78 percent
of Hispanics, 70 percent of whites and 68 percent of blacks had a
favorable impression of the Democratic mayor.
   That led Bradley to be dubbed the ``Teflon mayor,'' because he
is apparently not blamed for the city's mounting urban problems.
   The only currently elected official challenging Bradley,
freshman City Councilman Nate Holden, was considered his only
serious opponent in the non-partisan race, but hardly a threat to
the 16-year mayor.
   Other candidates included a former county supervisor, a
socialist oil field worker and a singer-dancer who used to cavort
in a green bikini across the street from City Hall every day.
   The winner of Tuesday's mayor's race will oversee Los Angeles at
least into the early 1990s, leading a city with a population that
is swelling past 3 million people.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Pollsters and would-be opponents such as City Councilman Zev
Yaroslavsky agree that Bradley's low-key image has kept him from
being linked in voters' minds with Los Angeles' growing problems,
including criminal gangs, illegal drug trade, traffic congestion
and a failing sewage system.
   Yaroslavsky had widely been considered Bradley's leading
challenger, but backed out of the race after apparently deciding
that he couldn't win.
   Bradley's image even appeared untarnished by an ethics
investigation by the city attorney's office, which learned that the
mayor had performed consulting work with Far East National Bank,
which did business with the city.
   Bradley returned the $18,000 in fees he was paid by the bank and
called the charges politically motivated.
   Bradley, the son of a Texas sharecropper and the grandson of
slaves, was first elected mayor of Los Angeles in 1973.
   A track star at the University of California at Los Angeles, he
first entered public service as a Los Angeles police lieutenant,
and later was elected to the Los Angeles City Council.
   He was defeated in his first run at mayor in a bitter 1969 race
against incumbent Sam Yorty that critics said was tinged with
racism, but came back to beat Yorty the next time around.
   At the end of his current term, Bradley will become the first
mayor in Los Angeles history to have served four full terms.
   He has run twice for governor, but was defeated in 1982 and 1986
by Republican George Deukmejian.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
