<FIRST>r i PM-BRF--AussieEarl     04-12 0181</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Aussie Earl,0185</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Australian Sheep Sheaper Given Tour of Family Seat as New
Earl</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LINCOLN, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The new Earl of Lincoln _ a retired
Australian sheep shearer _ received a guided tour of his family
seat in northeast England and called it a nice place.
   Edward Fiennes-Clinton, 75, visiting Lincoln for the first time
Tuesday and Britain for the second time, said he hopes to take
advantage of the only real perk offered by his title _ a seat in
the House of Lords, the unelected upper chamber of Parliament.
   When the Duke of Newcastle, who was also the Earl of Lincoln,
died last Christmas, historians began a frantic search for the new
earl.
   It led to Fiennes-Clinton's shack in Bunbury, Western Australia,
l00 miles south of Perth.
   ``My wife thought it was a joke,'' said Fiennes-Clinton, who
before retiring worked as a sheep shearer, gold miner and milkman.
   ``It hasn't changed my life. My mates take me for what I am. One
said `You're a big man now,' but I haven't grown any taller,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
