<FILEID>AP-NR-04-12-89 0308EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-TourGuideBush     04-12 0615</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tour Guide Bush,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON TODAY: Bush Giving Visitors the Grand Tour</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new sightseeing business has arrived on the
scene in the nation's capital: guided tours conducted by President
Bush.
   Bush has been taking his guests to see the sights, something
predecessor Ronald Reagan rarely did.
   For Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak, it was a trip by
helicopter to nearby Baltimore for a baseball game. There, the two
presidents sat in a box and ate hot dogs and hamburgers and debated
Bush's high-and-outside season-opening pitch.
   For Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir, it was a trip past
the Tidal Basin for a glimpse of the city's famed cherry blossoms
and then to the Air and Space Museum, one of Washington's
most-visited attractions.
   The two joined springtime tourists in the museum's wide-screened
theater to watch the movie ``To Fly.'' Excited conversation rippled
through the audience as people realized who was in their midst, and
those who had cameras used them for snapshots.
   Next week, Jordan's King Hussein will be in town. And it's
anyone's guess where the president might take him.
   ``Washington is a city of 1,000 monuments,'' said White House
press secretary Marlin Fitzwater. ``We may end up visiting them
all.''
   Bush plans to take French President Francois Mitterrand to his
vacation home in Kennebunkport, Maine, next month.
   And he threw open the doors of the presidential retreat at Camp
David, Md., to House speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas.
   Bush set the theme early in his presidency, when he opened the
White House to the public the Saturday after his inauguration. And,
at one reception for members of Congress, Bush used a Polaroid
camera to take instant photos of lawmakers in the Lincoln Bedroom.
   On the way to the Air and Space museum, the Bush-Shamir
motorcade passed a line of life-sized standup photographs that have
proliferated in Washington over the past few years.
   For instance, for a $5 fee you can have your picture taken with
a cutout of President Bush, the first lady or both. In the final
photograph, it looks like you were standing next to the first
family in front of a Washington landmark.
   At the White House, there have been such cutouts for several
years: first the Reagans, and now the Bushes. For a while, a cutout
of Oliver North also appeared, but popular demand trailed off and
it has been removed.
   But outside the Air and Space museum, George and Barbara Bush
now share sidewalk space with other celebrities, including cutouts
of wrestling star Hulk Hogan and actor Tom Selleck, and a new
addition: Soviet President Mikhail Gorbachev.
   It would have been hard for Bush to miss the life-sized likeness
of the Soviet leader. Gorbachev was right on the corner, just feet
from the official motorcade.
   But if the president had any reaction, it went unreported.
   The president is often out and about town, frequently taking
guests with him in his limousine.
   And, since he has a habit of stopping at red lights when he's on
a social or recreational call, his motorcade often produces
expressions of surprise and delight from other motorists and
passersby as they realize the man in the stopped car alongside them
is none other than the president.
   Those on the street might have done a double take one day last
week.
   Bush, wearing exercise clothes, took his motorcade to the
Rayburn House Office Building, where he played racquetball in the
House gym.
   Running late for a formal dinner at the White House, Bush
emerged from the gym two hours later wearing a tuxedo.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Tom Raum covers the White House for The
Associated Press.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
