<FILEID>AP-NR-04-12-89 0301EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-TerrorismReport     04-12 0606</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Terrorism Report,570</SECOND>
<HEAD>1988 Set Record For Incidents, State Department Tells Congress</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Terrorism rose to record heights in 1988, as
the United States suffered a substantial increase and Israel
remained the favorite target, the State Department reported to
Congress.
   The bombing of a Pan Am jetliner in December over Scotland,
which the department's office of counter terrorism said probably
was a terrorist incident, and the Palestinian uprising on the West
Bank and in Gaza helped push the total of incidents to a new high
of 856, up 3 percent from 1987.
   In all, 658 people were killed and 1,131 wounded, an increase in
fatalities from 633 in 1987 but a decrease in injuries from 2,272.
   The casualty figures include terrorists themselves who were
killed or wounded during attacks as well as attacks by Afghanistan
against Pakistan, a U.S. ally which funneled American weapons to
Afghan guerrillas.
   In all, the citizens and property of 79 nations were attacked in
60 countries. Businessmen and tourists accounted for 77 percent of
the victims. The weapon used most often by terrorists was the bomb.
It was used in 48 percent of the attacks, said the report released
Tuesday.
   The Army's top uniformed lawyer contends that the U.S. military
can legally attack terrorists without violating a 1976 presidential
order that bans assassinations of individuals abroad,
   Maj. Gen. Hugh Overholt, the service's judge advocate general,
argued in an eight-page draft memorandum that because of changes in
``the nature of the threat,'' action against terrorists can be
justified on grounds of national self-defense.
   Overholt's memorandum was disclosed Monday by the newsletter
Defense Week and confirmed by Army officials.
   The State Department report said the United States remained a
primary target for international terrorism last year, as the number
of anti-U.S. incidents rose from 149 in 1987 to 185. They resulted
in 192 persons killed and 40 wounded, compared with seven Americans
killed and 47 wounded in 1987.
   The increase in deaths was due largely to the attack on
U.S.-bound Pan Am 103 in which 259 people aboard the jumbo jet and
11 on the ground perished. Of the victims 189 were Americans.
   Latin America was the area showing the largest percentage of
incidents against U.S. citizens and property _ 60 percent.
   On the whole, the Middle East again had the highest incidence of
international terrorism, with 313 attacks. Israel, including the
West Bank and Gaza, again was the main target, accounting for 29
percent of the attacks.
   The State Department credited Syria and Iraq with a substantial
reduction in direct involvement in terrorism last year, but said
both countries continued to provide safe haven and training to
terrorist organizations.
   Iran's decision to end its war with Iraq and expand ties to the
West lessened Iranian involvement in terrorism, but Iran continued
to include terrorism among its foreign-policy tools, the report
said.
   At year's end, 20 foreigners were listed as political hostages
being held in Lebanon, two others possibly were dead, while 13 were
released during the year.
   Ranked behind Israel, in order, as sites for the most terrorist
incidents were Pakistan, Colombia, Spain, Lebanon, West Germany,
Zimbabwe, South Korea, Peru and France.
   The 10 countries accounted for 75 percent of the incidents
during the year, the report said.
   The Palestinian uprising, which began in December 1987 and
continued through last year in the Israeli-held West Bank and Gaza
Strip, should be viewed overall as a ``civil insurrection,'' the
State Department said.
   But the report said since it contained ``elements of terrorism''
in some instances, all civilian casualties were included in the
1988 statistics.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890412-0022 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-12-89 0309EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Drugs-Housing     04-12 0673</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Drugs-Housing,680</SECOND>
<HEAD>Housing Officials Say Money Needed More than Policy Changes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Public housing officials say HUD Secretary
Jack Kemp's anti-drug proposals may help in some housing projects
but what they really need is more federal money to beef up security
and help tenants find jobs.
   ``He's not suggesting anything that has not been thought of in
the past _ they just haven't had the resources,'' said Richard
Nelson, executive director of the National Association of Housing
and Redevelopment Officials.
   ``We've got a lot of hand-wringing going on but no help,'' said
Gordon Cavanaugh, counsel for the Council of Large Public Housing
Authorities. ``I haven't seen any money yet.''
   The secretary of Housing and Urban Development proposed this
week a series of steps for fighting drugs in federally supported
housing projects in Washington. He said they ``are applicable to
every public housing authority in the United States'' and will be
issued in ``action memos'' to all locally run public housing
authorities.
   Kemp's package includes only one direct HUD action: dropping
government hearing procedures that may delay eviction of tenants
who use or sell drugs, so long as the tenants receive due process
in the courts.
   His other proposals were suggestions, including more police
patrols, installing security fences around projects, establishing
guarded entrances, renovating the projects and requiring photo
identification cards for residents.
   He provided no cost estimate but said he would go to Congress to
ask for more money if needed.
   District of Columbia officials on Tuesday formally asked HUD to
drop its requirement for hearings before evicting tenants for drug
use or firearm violations.
   But some housing officials said the move might not be possible
in some states, and that it might not speed up the eviction process
very much in others.
   In Baltimore, housing authority spokesman Bill Toohey said, the
hearing process works well and keeps most cases from ever going to
court. ``We are not about to change our ... grievance procedures,''
he said.
   Cavanaugh said many of the nation's 3,000 public housing
authorities might want to drop the hearing procedures, but that the
more serious delays in evictions are in the court system and would
not be changed.
   Jane Lang of the Housing and Development Law Institute said laws
in some states do not appear to provide enough protection for
tenants in eviction cases to meet HUD guidelines for waiving the
formal hearing procedures.
   The proposal to fence in housing projects will be controversial
and likely will be rejected in most cases, according to Nelson,
whose organization represents 90 percent of the local public
housing agencies that operate federally subsidized housing.
   He said a main concern of public housing agencies is making
projects blend in with the surrounding neighborhoods, and fencing
would only make them stand out and be even more attractive to drug
activity by outsiders.
   Kemp acknowledged on Monday that fences may not work in all
cases and said they should be considered on a case-by-case basis.
   ``A security fence may be different from barbed wire,'' Kemp
said. ``We're not trying to keep people in. We're trying to get
drug users from getting in.''
   In New York City, housing authorities have no plans to require
residents to have photo identification cards or to surround
projects with fences, said Val Coleman, spokesman for the city
housing authority. He called the steps ``draconian.''
   ``We're not that demoralized,'' Coleman said.
   Coleman said New York's need is for more money _ to increase its
public housing authority police force and to provide job training
for tenants.
   But some other cities, including Washington, have already begun
issuing photo identification cards in certain cases, such as for
tenants of high-rise and senior-citizen projects.
   Mayor Arthur Holland of Trenton, N.J., president of the U.S.
Conference of Mayors, praised Kemp's enthusiasm and said most of
his suggestions could be useful. But he cautioned that increasing
security in projects may only move drug problems into surrounding
areas unless broader programs are provided to poor urban residents.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
