<FILEID>AP-NR-04-12-89 0236EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-FairnessDoctrine     04-12 0493</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fairness Doctrine,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Committee Clears Bill Restoring Fairness Doctrine</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A House committee's vote to impose a new
fairness doctrine on broadcasters sets the stage for a
confrontation with the White House and a probable Supreme Court
challenge.
   The House Energy and Commerce Committee issued the challenge
Tuesday when on a voice vote it approved a fairness doctrine bill
introduced by committee chairman Rep. John Dingell, D-Mich.
   The bill goes to the full House, where it is expected to pass
easily.
   The Justice Department has told Dingell that it will urge
President Bush to veto any fairness doctrine law that passes
Congress.
   President Reagan vetoed an identical bill in 1987, the same year
the Federal Communications Commission repealed its doctrine on the
grounds it violated the First Amendment and no longer served the
public interest in an era of diverse media outlets.
   The 50-year-old rules required broadcasters to air opposing
views of controversial issues.
   If the bill should pass both houses of Congress and become law,
a Supreme Court test also would seem likely because of what
opponents say is the doctrine's unconstitutional infringement on
broadcasters' rights.
   A federal appeals court earlier this year ruled that the FCC had
the authority to scrap the doctrine, but the court sidestepped the
issue of the doctrine's constitutionality.
   Rep. Edward Markey, D-Mass., chairman of the Energy and Commerce
subcommittee on telecommunications and finance, said the fairness
doctrine is not a great burden on broadcasters and only assures
``more speech'' on public issues.
   The bill would not impose criminal sanctions on broadcasters who
violate the doctrine, Markey said, adding that a station never has
lost its license for fairness doctrine infractions.
   The committee's ranking Republican, Rep. Norman Lent of New
York, said the bill is designed to provide ``a minimal assurance of
fair play.''
   Opponents included Rep. Tom Tauke, R-Iowa, who said, ``This is a
clear violation of the First Amendment.'' He also disputed the view
that broadcasters must be required to be fair because they are
licensed to exploit a ``scarce'' medium _ the airwaves.
   ``Our founding fathers had the question before them: `Do we want
a fair press or do we want a free press?' And they made the choice
that we ought to have a free press,'' Tauke said.
   ``There were at that time very few media outlets in the
nation,'' he said. ``And of course then as today it was abundantly
clear that some of those media outlets sometimes engaged in
activities which were perceived, may actually have been, unfair.
But the founding fathers said there was a greater risk in
attempting to control the media by imposing fairness than there is
in permitting a free media to perhaps occasionally be unfair.''
   The fairness doctrine has been opposed by many broadcasters,
particularly smaller station owners who say the threat of lawsuits
is enough to make them just play music instead of discussing
controversial issues.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890412-0027 </DOCNO>
