<FIRST>u a AM-AuburnFire     04-12 0338</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Auburn Fire,0352</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fire Injures Two, Causes Evacuations and Power Outage</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AUBURN, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A spectacular five-alarm fire Tuesday
destroyed a roofing materials warehouse, forced the evacuation of
nearby buildings and injured two warehouse workers slightly,
firefighters said.
   The blaze sent a towering column of smoke over the suburban area
between Seattle and Tacoma, knocked out electricity to downtown
Auburn and snarled traffic as stoplights went dark and motorists
slowed for a glimpse of the flames.
   Four other buildings in an area of more than 100,000 square feet
also were engulfed in flames.
   An undetermined number of people were evacuated from four nearby
businesses, and firefighters hosed down a house across the street
that was threatened by the flames.
   No firefighters were hurt, although shifting winds blew sparks
and flaming tarpaper around the Leatherback Industries Inc.
warehouse.
   Mike DeHart of the Kent Fire Department said the smoke could
pose a threat to area residents with respiratory problems. Most of
the smoke was blown to the south, but some stayed in the area.
   The fire apparently started around 2:30 p.m. near an electrical
panel, but the cause remained undetermined, authorities said.
Damage initially was estimated at about $1 million.
   Fire officials estimated it would take the 75 firefighters from
five jurisdictions at least 12 hours to extinguish.
   The building contained large amounts of felt paper and tar to
make tarpaper for roofing, said an Auburn Fire Department spokesman
who refused to give his name.
   ``It's hot and it's nasty,'' he said.
   Asphalt stored at 300 to 400 degrees in the warehouse had only
to get a bit too hot to burst into flames, he said.
   Two Leatherback workers were treated for minor burns after
trying to extinguish the fire earlier in the day, officials said.
   The blaze spread despite a sprinkler system, and the two workers
and nine other employees fled, workers said.
   Several tanks of industrial chemicals exploded. Firefighters
tried to prevent flames from reaching a 61,000-gallon tank of
liquid asphalt and a large propane tank.
</TEXT>
