<HEAD>LaserPhoto PE1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENNIS CONRAD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PEORIA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fire swept through an apartment house early
Tuesday, killing seven children and two young mothers, and police
later arrested a homeless man but did not link him to the blaze.
   The three other occupants of the building were injured, two of
them seriously.
   Fire Chief G. John Parker said the cause remained under
investigation and authorities were focusing on a gas heater near
where the fire started. Parker said that based on an initial
investigation, authorities did not suspect arson.
   The blaze started about 2 a.m. on the first floor and had
engulfed the two-story, wood-frame structure by the time
firefighters responded.
   ``The fire was just blazing all of a sudden. ... I can't
remember hearing (noise) or anything,'' said Rhonda Tracy, a
relative of several of the victims who lived across the street and
was first to call the fire department, at 2:20 a.m.
   ``I had never seen people come out burned like that,'' she
continued. ``I was just hysterical.''
   Police and fire authorities, aided by arson investigators from
the federal Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms, were examining
the rubble in a working-class neighborhood in this central Illinois
city of about 130,000.
   Smoke detectors were found upstairs and down, Parker said, but
the downstairs detector was connected directly to the building's
wiring and electricity service had been cut April 4 by Central
Illinois Light Co. He was uncertain about the upstairs detector.
   Parker said the fire originated in a room off the foyer near the
entrance of the building. He said a folding bed was in the room,
but it was not being used at the time of the fire.
   Three families, consisting of four adults and eight children,
lived in the house, and had moved there last year, officials said.
   Police Capt. Mary Dunlavy said Carl Wells, who was treated at
St. Frances Medical Center and released, was the only survivor to
have been interviewed.
   ``He woke up, went down the stairs and it was hot and he had to
go, of course, back upstairs and try to wake the others,'' she
said. ``And then he went out the window onto the roof and was
rescued by the fire department with a ladder.''
   Later Tuesday, police arrested Joe Pickens, 34, and charged him
with criminal trespass for living in the first floor of the
building without permission, Parker said. An apartment on the first
floor was vacant.
   ``He's somewhat of a homeless person,'' the fire chief said.
``He stayed there sometimes.''
   Pickens was at the building Monday night, and left at 11:30
p.m., said Parker. Pickens was being held at the Peoria County Jail.
   Parker said rescuers found ``people standing on the porch and
some people on the roof. There were people already injured when we
got there.
   ``As soon as we knocked the fire down, it would come back up
again. This happened two or three times,'' he said.
   Several neighbors said they watched helplessly as the fire swept
the house.
   ``The kid was up there waving her hands like she was yelling for
help and the flames were all around her,'' said Charles Harris, 34,
who was visiting his sister in the apartment building next door.
   Three people died at the scene and six were pronounced dead at
two hospitals, said Peoria County Coroner Herbert Buzbee. The
children ranged in age from 2 months to 10 years, he said.
   ``As far as we know this is the worst fire we've ever had in
Peoria in terms of deaths,'' the coroner said.
   Assistant Fire Chief Sam Sisk said he believed the cause of
death was smoke inhalation.
   Joyce Barnes, 30, and Eric Davis, 14, were in serious condition
at Franciscan Medical Center in Rock Island, said spokeswoman Neva
Aldene.
   The coroner identified the dead as Wanda Hobbs, 20, and her
children, Ashly Hobbs, 1, and Felicia Hobbs, 3; Terry Davis, 27,
and her children, Carlyssa Davis, 2, Arnisha Davis, 7, and Tenora
Davis, 10.
   Also pronounced dead were Jacolby Thomas, the 2{-year-old
daughter of Ms. Barnes; and Eugene Roberts Jr., 2 months, believed
to be the son of either Ms. Hobbs or Ms. Davis, Buzbee said.
</TEXT>
