<FIRST>u i AM-DamagedConcorde 1stLd-Writethru a0461 04-12 0281</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Damaged Concorde, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0461,0285</SECOND>
<HEAD>Concorde Loses Piece Of Its Tail, Makes Emergency Landing</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 5 grafs to drop attribution in lead, UPDATES with
passenger comment. Pickup 5th graf `Austrialian Associated...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SYDNEY, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A British Airways Concorde jet on a
world-circling journey lost a piece of its tail in flight but
landed safely at Sydney international airport on Wednesday.
   There were no reports of injuries.
   The Concorde, making the first all-supersonic flight around the
world, was trying to set more than one dozen speed records as it
circles the globe and had been scheduled to land in Sydney,
organizers said.
   ``About 25 minutes after takeoff from New Zealand there was a
large thump,'' passenger Sheila Cole Nilva, a freelance journalist,
said in a telephone interview.
   ``Everybody looked at everybody else and lunch was served. The
stewardesses looked terrified,'' she said. ``The pilot came on and
said there was nothing to worry about and that there was a piece
loose on the airplane.''
   Australian Associated Press, quoting Australian Civil Aviation
Authority spokesman John Death, said it appeared that part of the
stabilizer at the back of the plane was missing when it landed at
12:42 p.m. (10:42 p.m. EDT Tuesday) on the flight from
Christchurch, New Zealand.
   The airport control tower was warned by the pilot there was a
problem with the plane and all emergency vehicles were placed on
standby, the radio network said.
   The three-week trip, covering 38,343 miles, involves 35 hours of
flight. It started April 1 in London and was to end there April 23.
   The 100-seat plane was filled to capacity with American
passengers who each paid $39,000 for the flight.
</TEXT>
