<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     04-12 0280</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0289</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Up Against Yen, Stocks Barely Rise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar rose against the Japanese yen in
Tokyo Wednesday, while stocks gained marginally.
   The dollar closed at 132.85 yen, up 0.23 yen from Tuesday's
closing. It opened at 132.68 yen and ranged from 132.60 yen to
132.88 yen during the day.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues, which gained 250.56 points on Tuesday, edged up
another 6.87 points, or 0.02 percent, to finish at 33,256.45.
   ``The index rose since participants were somewhat reassured
because Prime Minister (Noboru) Takeshita said nothing shocking
yesterday, but still they are reluctant to purchase actively,''
said Manji Ueda with Nomura Securities in Tokyo.
   On Tuesday, Takeshita said before parliament that he had
received about $1 million in donations from Recruit Co., the firm
at the center of a major stock-profiteering and bribery scandal.
   But he denied taking bribes and continued to reject oposition
calls for his resignation.
   Opposition leaders criticized Takeshita, saying the prime
minister had proved nothing, but investors were more or less
reassured as he said nothing that might cause a drastic change in
Japanese politics, dealers said.
   ``Some feeling of political uncertainty lingering in the market
made trading directionless,'' Ueda said.
   In currency dealings, traders said the dollar-yen rate moved
little as market players stepped to the sidelines in the absence of
market-affecting incentives.
   Market sentiment toward a stronger dollar dominated, but the
rate is unlikely to move much before Friday, when U.S. trade
figures for February and wholesale figures for March are to be
released in Washington, said a dealer at Bank of Tokyo, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
</TEXT>
