<FILEID>AP-NR-04-12-89 0503EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Nicaragua     04-12 0408</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nicaragua,0421</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report: Opposition, Rebel Leaders to Meet in Attempt to Unify</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FILADELFO ALEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Contra rebel leaders will meet
opposition politicians in Managua next month in a bid to field a
unity coalition against the ruling Sandinistas in the 1990
elections, La Prensa reported.
   The opposition newspaper said in its Tuesday editions that
directors of the Nicaraguan Resistance, the Contra umbrella
organization, will meet with leaders of 14 opposition parties in
the capital ``if the Sandinistas don't stop them.''
   It would be the rebel leaders' first trip to Managua since June,
when talks between the Sandinistas and rebels broke down.
   Resistance leaders and domestic opposition leaders signed an
agreement Monday after meeting in Guatemala City and pledging to
unite to run against the leftist Sandinistas in February 1990
elections.
   The document, quoted by La Prensa, said the domestic opposition
and Contra leaders had accepted ``the political electoral path in
order to defeat the FSLN (Sandinista party), which will lead to
democratization, stable and durable peace, reconciliation and
reconstruction of the nation.''
   The Resistance, it said, ``reaffirms its disposition to maintain
the halt to offensive military operations during the development of
a completely free election process in our country.''
   The opposition party leaders were to return Managua today to
hold a news conference on the accord, party spokesmen said.
   The Sandinista party newspaper Barricada on Tuesday condemned
the attempts at Contra-opposition unification.
   Barricada displayed a photo of Resistance director Enrique
Bermudez embracing Eli Altamirano, leader of the opposition
Nicaraguan Communist Party.
   An accompanying editorial said the accord represented ``a
tragedy for all these parties that call themselves the internal
opposition who have shown themselves to be incapable of
administering what little legitimacy they have and risk converting
themselves into what they weren't before, an opposition hired by
Washington.''
   Bermudez was a colonel in the National Guard of dictator
Anastasio Somoza, who was toppled in 1979 in the revolution the
Sandinistas rode to power. Bermudez later served as a military
chief of the Contras, who have been backed by the United States
since 1981.
   U.S. military aid to the rebels ran out early last year. Contra
forces that sought refuge in Honduras after the aid ran out are
receiving humanitarian aid.
   Seven opposition parties hold 35 seats in the 96-member
legislature, including the Communist Party and the Marxist-Leninist
Popular Action Movement. The ruling Sandinistas have 61 seats in
the National Assembly.
</TEXT>
