<FIRST>r i PM-Honduras-Attack     04-12 0368</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Honduras-Attack,0384</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Troop Supply Convoy Attacked, One Jeep Damaged</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDDY CUEVAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Unidentified assailants ambushed a
U.S. military convoy, raking it with gunfire and disabling a jeep
with an explosive, but no casualties were reported, a U.S. Embassy
spokesman said.
   The attack Tuesday in northern Honduras was the third this year
on U.S. troops in the country.
   The caravan of 11 jeeps was hit as it carried supplies to troops
taking part in military exercises, said the spokesman, Charles V.
Barclay. He said 14 U.S. and six Honduran soldiers were in the
vehicles.
   ``We don't know how many people were involved in the attack, but
an investigation is in progress,'' said Barclay.
   There was no immediate claim of responsibility, but leftist
groups including the Cinchonero People's Liberation Movement have
attacked U.S. troops in the past.
   Barclay said the incident occurred on a road near Olanchito,
about 125 miles north of Tegucigalpa, the capital.
   ``There were several gunshots and an explosive device that blew
up beneath one of the vehicles,'' said Barclay. He said the nature
of the device was unknown.
   U.S. and Honduran troops are taking part in a joint exercise to
build roads in northern Honduras. The exercise started in December
and will end in July, with 600 U.S. troops rotating in every two
weeks.
   The Honduran armed forces, in a statement, called it a
``criminal attack on members of both armies who are working jointly
to create an adequate highway infrastructure to improve living
conditions for Hondurans.''
   U.S. and Honduran forces are investigating the Tuesday morning
attack, a Honduran armed forces statement said.
   The troops were scheduled to return today to Enrique Soto Cano
Air Base, 50 miles north of Tegucigalpa, Barclay said.
   At least two soldiers have been killed and six injured in
attacks on U.S. forces in Honduras in the last four years.
   On Feb. 1, a U.S. troop convoy was hit by gunfire but no one was
injured. The last attack occurred on Feb. 18, when an unidentified
assailant hurled a bomb at a passing bus carrying 25 U.S. troops.
   The explosive destroyed the bus and injured three U.S. soldiers
and two Honduran passers-by.
</TEXT>
