<FILEID>AP-NR-04-12-89 0447EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Mexico-Debt     04-12 0601</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mexico-Debt,0624</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mexico Signs $3.6 Billion Debt Assistance Agreement With IMF</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ANDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mexico has signed a $3.65 billion three-year
loan agreement with the International Monetary Fund to bolster the
country's foreign exchange reserves and help spur domestic economic
growth.
   The accord breaks from previous IMF practice by mandating no new
austerity measures, said Treasury Secretary Pedro Aspe.
   Mexico, struggling to overcome the burden of payments to
commercial banks and governments on its $107 billion foreign debt,
is the developing world's second-largest debtor. Only Brazil owes
more _ $121 billion.
   Tuesday's agreement is the first from the international lending
community since U.S. Treasury Secretary Nicholas Brady outlined a
debt-reduction plan on March 10 that he hoped would help ease
payment terms on the developing world's $1.32 trillion foreign debt.
   As interest rates have risen worldwide since last year, the
higher rates have created additional problems for countries
struggling to meet the terms of payments to foreign creditors. Some
debtor nations threaten default unless they can arrive at more
favorable terms with lenders.
   Austerity measures imposed by the Venezuelan government at the
behest of international lending organizations prompted riots last
month in Caracas that led to the deaths of more than 300 people.
   Aspe said Tuesday that his country's agreement intends to
reverse Mexico's net outflow of funds and provide investment money
to spur economic growth, which was nil last year.
   By stipulating that the IMF recognizes Mexico's need to set its
growth priorities first and schedule debt servicing accordingly,
Aspe said the agreement ``is a fundamental change from the past.''
   ``The agreement reached with the IMF constitutes a plain
endorsement of the economic strategy of Mexico,'' he said.
   That means the IMF will not require further devaluations of the
Mexican peso, as has been called for in previous agreements in an
effort to stimulate exports, said one government official on
condition of anonymity.
   President Carlos Salinas de Gortarihas pressed efforts to cut
the outflow of capital needed to revitalize Mexico's stagnant
economy.
   Mexico has been expected to be among the first beneficiaries of
the U.S. plan, which seeks to entice banks to forgive part of the
debt in return for assurances from the IMF and World Bank that the
remaining debt will be paid.
   Aspe also announced that Mexico will conclude an agreement this
week with the World Bank for $1.5 billion in credits to support the
government's restructuring programs.
   In addition, Mexico shortly expects to obtain $500 million in
compensatory financing from the fund, Aspe said. The combined
credits ``will be devoted to operations that reduce the debt and
its servicing,'' he said.
   On April 19, Mexico will formally present creditor banks its
proposals to reduce the foreign debt's value, cut servicing and
obtain additional lending over several years, the treasury chief
said.
   Mexico will offer banks the option of exchanging old debt for
Mexican bonds that discount debt principal and reduce interest
rates, Aspe told the private ``24 Hours'' newscast late Tuesday.
   Mexico netted a $1.1 billion reduction of debt principal in a
bond auction backed by the U.S. Treasury last year.
   Aspe said the IMF agreement also will promote Mexico's efforts
to reach restructuring agreements with the Paris Club of creditor
government banks.
   He stressed that Tuesday's pact ``is a new type of agreement
that bolsters a strategy of sustained economic growth with price
stability,'' a clear reference to Salinas' anti-inflation program.
   That program has reduced inflation from a record 159.2 percent
in 1987 to 52.7 percent in 1988. The government predicts inflation
will reach 18 percent this year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890412-0050 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-12-89 0555EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-WVaGovernor     04-12 0602</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-WVa Governor,0623</SECOND>
<HEAD>New W.Va. Governor Defends Tax Increases</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK PAXTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Many voters are angry that Gov. Gaston
Caperton broke his no-tax campaign pledge, but Caperton defends the
record tax hike and says he couldn't be more satisfied with his
first three months in office.
   ``We inherited a state which was in real crisis,'' the
Democratic governor said Tuesday. ``I think we well-defined that
crisis and with a cooperative effort with the Legislature ... have
set forth a legislative program to turn this state around, and we
batted about 1,000 percent.''
   The $392 million tax package is just one of the accomplishments
Caperton pointed to with pride after the regular legislative
session ended last week.
   Lawmakers on both sides of the aisle passed virtually all his
major bills, including one calling for a sweeping reorganization of
state government, and generally gave him rave reviews for his
leadership. It was a dramatic change from the previous four years,
in which a Legislature dominated by Democrats fought almost
constantly with combative Republican Gov. Arch Moore, who lost to
Caperton in November.
   ``He's been honest,'' said Republican state Sen. Buffy Warner.
``He's been very actively and personally involved. And I think both
on the surface and the deeper you look, the man is trying his
absolute best to do what has to be done in this state.''
   Caperton inherited a treasury that was millions of dollars in
debt because of severe slumps in the coal and steel industries in
recent years, which drove up unemployment, and cuts in federal
assistance.
   Despite his campaign pledge, Caperton asked the Legislature for
the largest tax increase in its history, including a new 6 percent
sales tax on food and a 5-cent-a-gallon gasoline tax.
   ``I also said I'd never be a governor who couldn't pay his
bills,'' Caperton said. ``We had the courage and the guts to stand
up and ... raise taxes. No one likes to raise taxes and no one
likes to pay additional taxes. But it was necessary.''
   Many voters apparently didn't appreciate that courage. Some tax
protesters who showed up at the Capitol last month carried signs
calling for Caperton's impeachment.
   A statewide poll conducted in mid-March showed 73 percent of
respondents thought Caperton broke his campaign promise by pushing
for a tax hike within a week of taking office, and two-thirds rated
his job performance as just fair or poor.
   The poll showed Caperton would trail Moore by 43 percent to 36
percent if an election were held today.
   Lawmakers approved Caperton's plan to consolidate more than 155
state agencies and departments under seven gubernatorially
appointed, cabinet-level secretaries.
   They also approved Caperton's request to put proposed
constitutional amendments before voters in September. One amendment
would abolish the elected posts of secretary of state, treasurer
and agriculture commissioner and put the jobs under the governor's
control. Another would place the Board of Education under the
governor's control.
   Agriculture Commissioner Cleve Benedict, the only Republican
holding statewide office, said Caperton was making a grab for power.
   ``It's the honeymoon express,'' he said. ``Every governor enjoys
a period of good will with the Legislature. This time it is
amplified by the governor's party's overwhelming control of both
chambers of the Legislature.''
   Caperton says he isn't concerned about the polls or the
protests. And Warner, one of only four Republicans in the 34-seat
Senate, says there's plenty of time for anger to ease before
Caperton's term ends in 1992.
   ``Four years will be enough time to see that he's done the
things that needed to be done,'' he said.
</TEXT>
