<FIRST>r a PM-EmbattledEducator     04-12 0531</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Embattled Educator,0547</SECOND>
<HEAD>Embattled Superintendent's Contract Renewed Amid Controversy</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto BX13 of April 11</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE DREYFOUS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The city's first black school chief hung on to his
job by one vote, but opponents of Laval S. Wilson vowed to continue
working to oust him.
   Bitterness from the 7-6 vote Tuesday night by the Boston School
Committee spilled over to the announcement that Wilson's contract
would be renewed.
   As committee President Tom O'Reilly tried to move on to other
agenda items after the announcement, committee member Robert
Cappucci suddenly took command of the microphone.
   ``We're going to do everything in our power to see to it that we
get a new superintendent,'' Cappucci said.
   Wilson said he was delighted with the renewal but acknowledged
there had been problems during his tenure.
   ``I don't think anyone was expecting a real endorsement,'' the
53-year-old Chicago native said after the announcement. ``The issue
was whether or not we could continue the progress we've made.''
   Wilson's arrival in Boston four years ago to operate the
country's oldest public school system was heralded as the healing
of racial wounds that had festered since the first days of
federally ordered desegregation in the mid-1970s.
   But the honeymoon has come to an end in recent months, with
critics increasingly denouncing what they call Wilson's
``autocratic'' style.
   Committee member John Nucci, who supports Wilson, said it was
everyone's duty to try to make the uneasy union work.
   ``I hope they realize that personal vendetta have to be put
aside in the interest of the school system,'' he said. ``We have to
think of the kids first.''
   But Cappucci said he and other dissenters would show their
displeasure by voting down Wilson's program proposals and making an
intense effort to lobby the swing vote necessary to oust the
superintendent.
   ``There's going to be some troublemaking,'' said Peggy
Davis-Mullen, a committee member and one of Wilson's fiercest
detractors.
   The committee, which announced its decision after deliberating
about two hours behind closed doors, offered Wilson a contract
without an increase to his $95,000 salary and with performance
reviews every six months.
   ``It's not a working situation,'' Cappucci said. ``I don't see
how Dr. Wilson thinks he'll be able to get anything done.
   ``If I were him, I'd see the handwriting on the wall ... and bow
out,'' he said. ``He is not the man for the Boston job.''
   Mrs. Mullen said some people who oppose Wilson ``are afraid
they're going to be attacked for being racist. But black leaders
have come out against this man. It's his approach. He's not a
communicator, not a motivator.''
   The system has become increasingly black since the early 1970s,
when white students began moving in droves from public to private
schools. There are 59,000 students, 24 percent of them white,
enrolled in Boston's public schools today as compared with 96,000
in 1972, when 60 percent of students were white.
   Supporters have said Wilson is a tireless worker who regularly
puts in 12-hour days and deserves a fair shot at turning the
troubled system around, but detractors claim he hasn't dealt
effectively with high dropout rates and low test scores.
</TEXT>
