<FIRST>r a PM-DeNiro-Bandit     04-12 0269</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-DeNiro-Bandit,0276</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fugitive Bank Robber Tries Plastic Surgery, But Recaptured</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PENSACOLA BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bandit with a penchant for
robbing banks and a knack for escape is back behind bars because
plastic surgery designed to make him look like actor Robert DeNiro
failed to fool the feds.
   Deputy U.S. marshals arrested Robert Litchfield, 41, on Tuesday
in this Florida Panhandle resort community.
   Litchfield was the first man to escape from the federal
penetentiary at Leavenworth, Kan., in 12 years, said W.L. McLendon,
U.S. marshal for northern Florida. He escaped March 10.
   ``Robert DeNiro is his idol,'' said Ken Pekarek, the U.S.
marshal for Kansas said from Kansas City, Kan. ``He said he altered
his appearance so he would look like Robert DeNiro.''
   Litchfield's nickname, ``Blockhouse Bandit,'' stemmed from his
specialty of robbing bank drive-in windows separate from main banks
in the Miami area, McLendon said.
   Litchfield had been serving 140 years for numerous armed bank
robberies in Florida and a 1986 escape. He used a disguise to
escape from Leavenworth, passing himself off as an employee and
walked out the front door of the prison to a waiting cab.
   In February 1986, he escaped from a federal prison in Talladega,
Ala. In that escape, he dyed his prison uniform blue and convinced
a prison dentist he was a visitor. He was arrested May 20, 1987, in
Lake Tahoe, Nev.
   Pekarek said Litchfield is a suspect in the March 24 holdup of
Georgia Federal Bank in Tucker, Ga., where a man posing as a
utility worker investigating a natural gas leak fled with about
$38,000 in cash.
</TEXT>
