<FIRST>r i PM-SatanicSlayings-Matamoros     04-12 0413</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Satanic Slayings-Matamoros,0423</SECOND>
<HEAD>Matamoros Residents Worry About Cult Stigma</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Satanic Slayings, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID SEDENO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MATAMOROS, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Residents of this border city said
today they hope they can ward off a stigma that could be attached
to their community after the cult mutilations of at least 12 people.
   ``It is not fair if people in the United States try to judge all
of us just because a few people committed these atrocities,''
Ignacio Garcia, a supervisor at Pancho Villa's restaurant, said
this morning. ``Those people may not even be from Matamoros.
   ``We don't really know what the reaction of the American people
will be, but we are very concerned and we will tell the tourists
that 99.9 percent of the people here are good and that it only
takes one or two to give the others the bad name.''
   Five men have been arrested in connection with the slayings,
Mexican authorities said. Authorities on Tuesday announced the
arrests after discovering several graves at the Santa Elena Ranch,
outside of Matamoros.
   The graves contained remains of 12 bodies, including that of
Mark Kilroy, a 21-year-old University of Texas premedical student
who disappeared from the streets of Matamoros during spring break
on March 14.
   Authorities said the victims, most of them still unidentified,
were sacrificed in a voodoo ritual intended to ward off harm to the
suspects during drug-smuggling activities.
   The streets of Matamoros were quiet early this morning, a day
after the revelations hit the newspapers and television airwaves.
   Resident Beatrice Cistkovit said many residents worried about
Kilroy after his parents, James and Helen Kilroy, offered a $15,000
reward seeking information about his disappearance.
   ``We put ourselves in the parents' position. We really felt for
them,'' she said. ``They should give those guys the death penalty
because it's horrible what they did. They should hang. They don't
deserve to live.''
   However, she worried that publicity about the case could cast a
dark shadow on the city.
   With a month before summer vacationers begin their annual summer
descent on Matamoros, some residents said the revelations will not
greatly affect tourism.
   ``This town is a tranquil place. There are some fights every
once in a while and there are some faith healers here, too, but
nothing like this has ever happened and it's new to us,'' said
Manuel Sandoval, a restaurant manager. ``This may take a little
time to pass, but we think it won't hurt us too much.''
</TEXT>
