<FILEID>AP-NR-04-12-89 0718EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r p PM-BradleyProfile     04-12 0607</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bradley Profile,0625</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tom Bradley: `Teflon Mayor' Wins Fifth Term</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-LA Mayor, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD DE ATLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For Mayor Tom Bradley, called the ``Teflon
mayor'' because the blame for the city's problems hasn't stuck to
him in the past, the timing for a re-election bid couldn't have
been much worse.
   Gang-related murders are on the rise, traffic congestion is
horrendous, the sewage system is failing and there's problems with
smog, housing and homelessness.
   The 71-year-old Bradley, Los Angeles' first black mayor, won
election to an unprecedented fifth term Tuesday but by a far less
of a margin than published polls had predicted.
   Early today, he held more than 52 percent of the vote with 98.4
percent of the city's precincts reporting. He needed at least 50
percent to avoid a June 6 runoff. His nine rivals were not well
known and voter turnout was less than 20 percent.
   A recent poll by the Los Angeles Times showed 78 percent of
Hispanics, 70 percent of whites and 68 percent of blacks had a
favorable impression of the Democratic mayor.
   Pollsters had said that Bradley's low-key image helped him.
   Bradley, mayor for 16 years, a city councilman and a policeman
before that, may be one of the most private public persons in
America.
   ``There's a mystery about him that I don't know if anyone will
ever crack,'' former press deputy Tom Sullivan once said.``I've
spent more time with him than anyone, including his wife, during
the campaigns. I still don't understand him.''
   His political powers as mayor include an ability to heal his
wounds almost overnight and a quick recovery when he slips.
   He's slipped twice in runs for governor. In his first try, he
lost to George Deukmejian in 1982 by just 1.2 percent.
   Some said voter racism shaved the ballots Bradley needed to win,
but he refused to blame prejudice for losing the campaign, except
in oblique references years later.
   With a monotonal speech delivery and a decided dislike for
public feuding, Bradley is a far cry from such contemporaries as
New York's Edward Koch.
   But at 6-foot-4 and still bearing an athletic trim in his eighth
decade, Bradley can afford to dispense with histrionics and
arm-waving to get things done.
   His political power, observers say, lies in his attention to
detail _ he takes notes on potholes while riding through the city _
and his refusal to delegate authoity to staffers. Their role is to
do his bidding, and do it quickly.
   Wanda Moore, Bradley's executive assistant, has said Bradley
sees 99.9 percent of the paperwork that passes through his office,
down to gripe letters from constituents.
   His 1987 appointment calendar, opened to the Los Angeles Times,
shows him in unrelenting motion, working 16 to 18 hours a day,
seven days a week.
   He went to 512 social engagements that year, including birthday
parties, bar mitzvahs, weddings, pancake breakfasts and the opening
of a fast-food chicken restaurant.
   Those appearances are another key for Bradley _ his ability in a
city of more than 3 million to appear to be everywhere at once. He
doesn't even have to be in some spots to have his presence felt.
   Busts of Bradley stare at visitors at the Los Angeles
International Airport's Tom Bradley Terminal, the Los Angeles
Convention Center and the Los Angeles Produce Mart, all tributes to
the revitalization and building of the city for which Bradley has
taken credit without the usual hoopla.
   He also brought the profitable 1984 Summer Olympics to the city,
and has encouraged Los Angeles' role as an important center of
Pacific Rim trading.
</TEXT>
