<FIRST>r a PM-BusinessWeek-Dillon     04-12 0304</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Week-Dillon,0312</SECOND>
<HEAD>6 Months in Prison for Ex-Broker in Business Week Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former Merrill Lynch &amp; Co. stockbroker was
sentenced to six months in prison and ordered to make full
restitution for insider-trading based on advance knowledge of
market sensitive Business Week articles.
   U.S. District Judge John Walker sentenced William Dillon to two
years in prison Tuesday but suspended all but six months because
Dillon was cooperating with federal investigators.
   The judge turned down a defense lawyer's request that Dillon not
be sent to jail, saying the former broker was ``motivated by greed,
pure and simple.''
   Dillon, 34, of Old Lyme, Conn., pleaded guilty last year to a
single count of wire fraud. He could have been sentenced to a
maximum five years in prison and fined $250,000.
   Dillon began working at Merrill Lynch's New London, Conn.,
office in 1986. He was fired last July after the firm discovered he
had been obtaining advance copies of Business Week from workers at
a printing plant.
   The printer, R.R. Donnelley &amp; Sons Co., has fired several
employees for allegedly selling copies of the magazine before its
official publication date.
   ``I am truly sorry for what I did,'' Dillon said.
   Dillon also was placed on three years' probation and ordered to
perform 200 hours of community service. The judge also ordered
Dillon to make full restitution of an amount to be determined by
the Securities and Exchange Commission.
   The government contends that Dillon, who now works as a
carpenter, made some $118,000 in profits from more than 120 trades
between May 1986 and July 1988, said Assistant U.S. Attorney Carl
Loewenson Jr.
   Dillon also pleaded guilty to a fraud count in Connecticut and
is due to be sentenced there on Thursday, said Loewenson.
</TEXT>
