<SECOND>PM-Vietnam-MIAs, 1st Ld-Writethru,,a0477,0556</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Experts Fly To Vietnam For MIA Investigation</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with arrival in Hanoi, Cambodia comment,
details. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. military team arrived in Vietnam
today for the fifth joint field investigation to account for
American servicemen missing from the Vietnam War, a U.S. spokesman
said.
   The 10 specialists flew from Bangkok to Vietnam's capital of
Hanoi for the 18-day mission, which is expected to be the longest
of its type since the war ended, said Ross Petzing, the spokesman
of the U.S. Embassy in Bangkok.
   Previous investigations were limited to about 10 days each.
   The U.S. investigators, including forensic scientists, are from
the U.S. Joint Casualty Resolution Center and the Army Central
Identification Laboratory, both based in Honolulu. They will work
with officials of Vietnam's Office For Seeking Missing Personnel.
   U.S. Defense Department officials said earlier that most of the
investigative work this month would focus on the area of Danang, a
major port 400 miles southeast of Hanoi.
   Danang is in what was South Vietnam, which the United States
supported in the war the against Communist north. The Marines who
splashed ashore there in March 1965 were the first American combat
troops to set foot on the Asian mainland since the end of the
Korean conflict.
   U.S. forces withdrew in 1973 and South Vietnam fell to Communist
forces in April 1975.
   In the joint field missions, American and Vietnamese
investigators interview villagers and inspect U.S. warplane crash
sites to try to resolve ``discrepancy cases'' that the U.S.
considers top priority.
   These are cases that U.S. officials say Vietnamese authorities
should have information on, including cases of airmen who survived
crashes but failed to emerge from prisoner of war camps.
   The U.S. Defense Department previously announced that Vietnam on
April 27 would return 21 sets of remains that may be those of
missing Americans.
   Vietnam has returned large numbers of remains since August 1987,
when it agreed to accelerate cooperation on the issue in return for
Washington's help in encouraging private humanitarian aid to
Vietnam.
   More than 1,700 Americans are listed as missing in action in
Vietnam and others are unaccounted for in Laos, Cambodia and China.
   The pro-Vietnamese government in Cambodia claims to have found
the remains of some of the 83 U.S. servicemen missing there, but a
senior Cambodian official last week there was ``no progress'' in
arranging their repatriation.
   Uch Kiman, director of the Foreign Ministry's Political
Department, repeated his government's demand that the U.S.
government receive the remains directly and not through
intermediaries.
   Washington has refused to do that and instead has requested
assistance from an international organization because it does not
recognize the government, which Vietnam installed after invading
the country in late 1978.
   ``There should be negotiations between governments, not between
this government and private groups,'' Uch Kiman said in an
interview in Phnom Penh with two Western journalists.
   ``We don't seem to have a positive signal from the American
government ... regarding the return of the remains of the MIAs,''
he said.
   In February, Cambodia's Prime Minister Hun Sen told a former
American aid official that about 10 percent of the 83 Americans
listed as MIA have been found.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
