<DOCNO> AP890412-0063 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-12-89 0754EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Soviet-Submarine     04-12 0298</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Submarine,0306</SECOND>
<HEAD>Commander Says Soviet Sub Crew Gave Up Too Late</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More sailors might have survived the sinking of a
Soviet submarine off Norway if they had realized sooner that the
vessel could not be saved, the Soviet Northern Fleet commander said
in an interview published today.
   ``People didn't think about retreat, they were sure they would
be able to save the ship, and so part of the submarine's crew
didn't get a chance to use the life-saving equipment on board,''
Adm. Felix N. Gromov told the Defense Ministry newspaper Red Star.
   The nuclear-powered submarine, carrying two nuclear-tipped
missiles, caught fire and sank Friday, killing 42 of its crew of 69.
   The Soviet navy plans to raise the ship from its resting place
4,950 feet deep to determine the exact cause of the disaster,
Soviet television reported. Gromov was quoted as telling the
newspaper that the ship's logbook has been recovered along with
many other documents.
   He said it was clear the construction of ``certain life-saving
devices'' on board must be improved, but final conclusions about
what caused the accident and its high death toll will be made by a
government commission.
   Soviet officials say there is no danger of radiation leakage
from the submarine because the crew shut down its reactors and
neither of its torpedoes was armed for combat.
   The submarine's captain, Yevgeny Vanin, pulled a sailor through
a smoke-filled hatch and then died as he struggled to reach his
crew, according to Soviet media reports.
   Some survivors waited for rescue in freezing waters for an hour
and a half. Only 19 of the 42 bodies have been recovered.
   The government newspaper Izvestia said a short circuit probably
caused the fire as the submarine was heading to port after a long
voyage.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
