<FIRST>r i PM-Israel     04-12 0535</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel,0552</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jewish Settler Leader Charged With Manslaughter</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police today charged a Jewish leader with
manslaughter in the death of an Arab shop owner. Soldiers in the
occupied Gaza Strip reportedly shot and wounded at least six
Palestinians.
   Rabbi Moshe Levinger of the occupied West Bank city of Hebron
was charged with manslaughter, causing bodily harm in aggravated
circumstances and intentionally damaging property, said Justice
Ministry spokeswoman Etty Eshed. If convicted, he faces 20 years in
prison.
   Levinger is accused of killing Kayed Hassan Salah, 42, after a
rock-throwing incident Sept. 30, 1988 in Hebron. According to
prosecutors, Levinger got out of his car, fired in the air with his
pistol, and then shot the shoe shop owner as he stood outside his
store with a customer. The customer was wounded.
   Levinger also allegedly overturned vegetable and fruit carts and
damaged goods inside Hebron stores.
   Levinger, reached by telephone at Beit Romano, a Jewish enclave
in Hebron, said he had not been officially informed of the charges
and had no immediate response.
   The Jerusalem-born Levinger, 54, is known as an extremist leader
of a religious Jewish movement to settle the West Bank and Gaza
Strip.
   About 70,000 Jewish settlers live in the occupied lands along
with 1.7 million Palestinians. An uprising against Israeli rule,
which began in December 1987, has killed at least 423 Palestinians
and 18 Israelis.
   In Hebron, merchants closed their stores today to protest an
incident Monday in Jerusalem in which a Jewish man fired an Uzi
submachine gun on a group of Arabs. One Arab was killed and three
were wounded, and the killer escaped.
   An anonymous caller claimed responsibility for the attack in the
name of the extremist Sicarites group, named after ancient Jewish
assassins active nearly 2,000 years ago.
   Police today released three Jewish men it detained Tuesday on
suspicion of being linked to the attack, Jerusalem police spokesman
Uzi Sandouri said. He said police distributed a composit drawing of
the main suspect.
   A total of five men, four Jews and one Arab, have been detained
for questioning in connection with the shootings, Jerusalem Police
Chief Yossi Yehudai said. All five have all been freed, he said.
   In the West Bank town of Bethlehem, about 100 Palestinian youths
built barricades and burned tires in narrow streets leading to the
Church of Nativity.
   The masked youths clashed with troops who fired tear gas and
rubber bullets, an Arab reporter said. One woman was injured by a
rubber bullet.
   In the Gaza Strip, soldiers shot and wounded six Palestinians,
five of them teen-agers, Arab hospital officials said. The army
said it was checking the report.
   Also in the occupied territory, the army issued about 200 green
identity cards to Arab activists and former detainees, barring
their entry into Israel, Arab and Israeli reports said.
   Muin Shadid, a 25 year-old Tulkarem journalist who was served
with the new card April 3, said he saw at least 100 such cards at
the military administration headquarters.
   Shadid said an administration officer refused to explain the
move, saying it ``was the decision of senior security officials.''
Shadid said he would complain to the Supreme Court.
</TEXT>
