<SECOND>PM-Democratic Chairman,0227</SECOND>
<HEAD>Houston Democrats Select Replacement For LaRouche Follower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Harris County's Democratic Party has elected a
new chairman to replace a follower of jailed political extremist
Lyndon LaRouche.
   Jack Carter was named Tuesday to succeed Claude Jones, who was
elected in the 1988 primary but removed by Texas Democratic
chairman Bob Slagle earlier this year for allegedly campaigning
against presidential nominee Michael Dukakis.
   Nearly 300 members of the county Democratic Executive Committee
shouted their votes for Carter, the party secretary. Only a few
people shouted in favor of Jones.
   ``This is totally undemocratic what they are doing here, and
they know it,'' said Jones. ``They are hurting themselves _ not me.
They are hurting the party.''
   He said he will challenge his ouster in court and will recruit
``as many candidates as we can to run in the next election.''
   Jones' election to the post shocked the party leadership. He was
stripped of most of his powers shortly after the election. Slagle
and others wanted him out of office before it was time to raise
money and organize for 1990.
   LaRouche, a frequent presidential candidate, is serving a
15-year sentence for conspiracy and mail fraud in his
organization's solicitation of $34 million in loans. He also was
convicted of conspiring to hide his personal income since 1979.
 
