<HEAD>Empress Dowager Nagako Visits Hirohito's Tomb</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Empress Dowager Nagako, Emperor Hirohito's widow,
visited her husband's tomb for the first time today in her first
trip outside the Imperial Palace in nearly seven months, a palace
official said.
   The 86-year-old empress dowager rode in a passenger car from the
Imperial Palace in Tokyo to Hirohito's hillside mausoleum in
Hachioji about 30 miles away. She walked several yards to the tomb
with the help of an aide.
   Emperor Hirohito died of cancer Jan. 7 at age 87. His state
funeral, held Feb. 24 in Tokyo's Shinjuku Gyoen Imperial Gardens,
was attended by more than 10,000 people, including envoys from 164
foreign countries.
   His widow did not attend the ceremonies due to ill health. A hip
problem makes it difficult for her to walk, and she has generally
moved around in a wheelchair for some time.
   Her last trip outside the palace was to an imperial villa in
Tochigi prefecture, northern Japan, last July.
   The imperial family is observing a year of mourning for
Hirohito. In four days, Emperor Akihito, Empress Michiko and other
family members will conduct a ceremony marking the 100th day since
Hirohito's entombment, the palace official said.
