<FIRST>r a PM-RiverboatGambling     04-12 0236</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Riverboat Gambling,0243</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iowa Lawmakers Reject Legalized Riverboat Gambling</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE GLOVER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Riverboat gambling fell three votes
short of approval in the state House, but the measure's backers
aren't ready to fold.
   ``We'll take a look at it overnight and talk again,'' said House
Majority Leader Bob Arnould.
   After hours of debate Tuesday, a bill to allow floating casinos
ply the Mississippi River drew 48 votes, less than a majority. The
Senate has narrowly approved the proposal, and Gov. Terry Branstad
has indicated he would sign it.
   Critics worried about organized crime and about compulsive
gamblers losing their grocery money.
   ``I may be able to gamble intelligently, but I have no right to
do that if it's going to cause the people who are weaker to get
caught up in this thing,'' said Rep. Betty Jean Clark.
   Backers said riverboat gambling would be tightly controlled and
would pump $100 million into the state's tourist economy.
Developers have offered to launch floating casinos and build
historical theme parks along the river.
   ``All we are asking is that those of us from my area be given an
opportunity to help ourselves,'' said Rep. Phil Wise of Keokuk.
``Please allow the citizens of the former home of Mark Twain to
capitalize on that.''
   The bill would limit stakes to $5 per bet and impose a $200 loss
limit per excursion.
</TEXT>
