<FILEID>AP-NR-04-12-89 0921EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-RapeOrdeal     04-12 0362</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Rape Ordeal,0373</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Overturns Dismissal Of Policeman in Rape Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CALUMET CITY, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge has overturned the firing of a
police officer who failed to break into an apartment where a girl
was being raped.
   Judge Thomas Rakowski ruled Tuesday that Patrolman James Horka,
who waited nearly 30 minutes to go inside during the 1987 attack,
``could reasonably have made the judgment call to not crash the
door based on the information he had.''
   ``We don't want policemen to believe that they have to take a
position of: `Don't wait, draw your guns and crash the door, or
your job's on the line,''' the judge said.
   Police Chief Steven Rhoads said Horka, 40, will be back on the
job Monday.
   Though the 12-year-old victim's mother begged police to go
inside, Horka and two other officers waited nearly a half hour
before rescuing the girl.
   Horka, the senior officer at the scene, said he waited for the
landlord to arrive with a key because he feared the girl and her
10-year-old brother might be killed if police forced their way in.
   ``I couldn't have lived with that,'' Horka said. ``No matter
what judgment call you make, the department can say you were wrong.
They weren't there, and I have to live with it.''
   A fourth officer later arrived, entered the apartment through an
unlocked back door and arrested a suspect, who is awaiting trial.
   Horka was dismissed a year ago by the city Fire and Police
Commission. The two other officers were suspended for up to three
weeks.
   ``I think the judge is going to get a lot of heat and rightly
so,'' said Edward T. Stein, a lawyer for the girl's family. ``The
message, that is very dangerous for the public, is: `Who do you
call when you can't call the police?'''
   The girl's family declined comment. The family is suing Horka
and three other officers.
   The judge upheld one charge against Horka _ late filing of a
report _ but noted that the officer could not be fired for such an
infraction. He sent the case back to the commission for
consideration of a lesser penalty.
</TEXT>
