<FIRST>r i PM-USBases-Strike     04-12 0255</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US Bases-Strike,0265</SECOND>
<HEAD>Greek Workers at U.S. Bases Go on Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Greek employees at U.S. military bases
today began a two-day strike to demand higher pay and improved
fringe benefits.
   Giorgos Alexandrou, U.S. Forces Employees Union president, said
shortly after the strike began that ``it is 100 percent
successful.''
   A spokeswoman for the four U.S. bases, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, said no information was immediately available on how
many Greek employees joined the walkout. The union represents about
1,750 workers.
   The union president said employees have not received any
substantial pay increases since 1982 and that the average monthly
salary is $500.
   ``We want increases at the level of other collective wage
agreements in Greece,'' Alexandrou said.
   He gave no percentage increase sought by the union. However,
other collective wage agreements this year have provided for
increases ranging from 4 percent to 15 percent.
   There are two military bases near the Greek capital and two
others on the southern Aegean island of Crete.
   About 500 of 900 Greeks who work at the Hellenikon Air Base next
to Athens International Airport, mounted a protest outside that
base holding banners that read ``No Firings, Permanent Employment,
Higher Wages.''
   The base, which was built in 1947, is the center for U.S.
reconnaissance aircraft monitoring Soviet fleet movements in the
eastern Mediterranean.
   U.S. and Greek officials are discussing renewing the pact on use
of the bases. Premier Andreas Papandreou has said Hellenikon Air
Base will close even if the others remain open.
</TEXT>
