<FIRST>r i PM-Soviet-Space     04-12 0211</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Space,0220</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mir to be Unmanned For The First Time in Two Years</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet space station Mir will be unmanned for
the first time in more than two years after three cosmonaunts who
are aboard return home this month, an official report said.
   Tuesday's report by Tass, the official news agency, made no
mention of a previously scheduled launch of two other cosmonauts
April 19. Since Tass said the craft will be unmanned, the new
launch has apparently been called off.
   Tass said the return of Alexander Volkov, Sergei Krikalev and
Valery Polyakov is scheduled for April 27.
   The Mir has been permanently manned since February 1987 when
Yuri Romanenko and Alexander Laveikin boarded the spacecraft.
   Mir was launched into orbit in February 1986. Soviets have said
it is the first part of a permanently manned space station.
   Cosmonauts Vladimir Titov and Musa Manarov last Dec. 20 set a
world record for space endurance, living aboard the space station
for 365 days and 22 hours.
   Volkov and Krikalev arrived at the Mir station on Nov. 26 as a
replacement crew for Titov and Manarov. Polyakov, a physician, had
joined the record-breakers in October to monitor their health in
the final months of their year in space.
</TEXT>
