<FIRST>u a PM-HospitalAirlift 1stLd-Writethru a0488 04-12 0419</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hospital Airlift, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0488,0424</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hospital's Request For Spoons Leads To Airlift</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to UPDATE with plane's departure. Picks up
4th graf, `Tomaszewski's wife...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEAN McNAIR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWPORT NEWS, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A plane loaded with medical supplies
and toys took off for the Dominican Republic today in a charity
drive that began with an appeal for spoons.
   ``It started with 100 spoons and now we're well over 130
boxes,'' John Tomaszewski said Tuesday.
   The Coast Guard C-130 cargo plane left Patrick Henry
International Airport with almost 3,000 pounds of supplies for the
Children's Colony Hospital in Santiago.
   Tomaszewski's wife, Chris, visited the Caribbean nation in
December to return a 3-year-old boy the couple had housed while he
was in the United States for surgery. The Tomaszewskis are foster
parents for Heal The Children, an organization based in Spokane,
Wash., that arranges for Third World children to receive medical
care in this country.
   During her visit, Mrs. Tomaszewski went to the children's
hospital, which was so ill-equipped that patients with severe cuts
had to bring their own thread for stitches.
   ``Instead of my eyes just filling with tears, my heart filled
with `I have to do something,''' Mrs. Tomaszewski said. ``When you
see children hurting or hungry or so sad, it's a human instinct.''
   A nun at the hospital said the children needed metal spoons that
could be sterilized so they wouldn't get sick from eating with
their hands.
   Mrs. Tomaszewski went home with pictures of the hospital and
started asking for help. Individuals and community groups
responded, and the couple's home quickly began filling up with
spoons, baby cribs, linens, an examination table, a microscope,
bandages, stethoscopes, toys, clothes and vitamins.
   ``Everybody was more than eager to help with the spoons. I think
we ended up with 500 spoons along with medical supplies,'' Ms.
Tomaszewski said.
   The supplies eventually were moved to a warehouse at the Coast
Guard Reserve Training Center at Yorktown, where Tomaszewski works
as a quartermaster.
   The Tomaszewskis will travel with the supplies and return a
10-year-old burn victim who has been getting treatment in the
United States. Mrs. Tomaszewski said she has sent a message about
the shipment to the nun, who had been pessimistic that any supplies
would reach the hospital.
   ``We've arranged for the chamber of commerce over there to bring
her to the airport,'' Mrs. Tomaszewski said. ``I know that her eyes
are going to fall out of her head.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
