<FIRST>r i PM-Germany-Firebombs     04-12 0256</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Germany-Firebombs,0265</SECOND>
<HEAD>Frankfurt Stock Exchange, Muenster Electronics Firm Attacked</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Masked youths hurled firebombs
into the main trading hall of the Frankfurt Stock Exchange today,
and a similar attack was made against an electronics firm in
Muenster, police said.
   Law enforcement officials said both attacks were apparently
carried out by sympathizers of jailed Red Army Faction terrorists.
   Two employees were slightly injured in the stock exchange
firebombing, which occurred more than an hour before trading was to
begin. Employees grabbed three suspects, Frankfurt police spokesman
Horst Neitzel said.
   Neitzel said two security employees at the stock exchange were
slightly injured when they grabbed two women and a man who
allegedly participated in the 10 a.m. attack, which damaged a
computer and slightly delayed trading. At least three other
attackers escaped, he said.
   In Muenster, police found a note near the scene saying the
attack on the four-story offices of the AEG electronics firm was to
support hunger-striking jailed Red Army members, Neitzel said.
   The 3:30 a.m. firebombing of AEG, a subsidiary of the
Daimler-Benz automotive and high-technology conglomerate, caused
millions of dollars in damage but no injuries, Neitzel said. No
arrests were made immediately, he said.
   At least 34 imprisoned terrorists have joined the fast to demand
a separate cell block for jailed members of the Red Army, a radical
organization that seeks to undermine the West German government
with assassinations, bank robberies and other attacks.
   Government officials have said they are concerned the fasts will
spur further attacks by sympathizers.
</TEXT>
