<FIRST>r w PM-DefenseInvestigation 1stLd-Writethru a0441 04-12 0318</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Defense Investigation, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0441,310</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jury Still Out in Pentagon Fraud Case</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: New lead with jury resuming deliberations; picks up 2nd graf
pvs, The four women.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury considering the bribery case
against three California executives charged in the Pentagon
corruption case resumed deliberations today after failing to reach
a verdict in two days.
   The four women and eight men informed U.S. District Judge
Richard Williams late Tuesday that they had not come to a decision
after a total of 20 hours of deliberations.
   Williams said he would give the jury new instructions today if
they were having problems with the charges.
   Dale Schnittjer, Eugene Sullivan and George Kaub, three former
vice presidents of Teledyne Electronics of Newbury Park, Calif.,
are charged with bribery, conspiracy and wire fraud in the first
case brought to trial since the government ``Ill Wind''
investigation into fraud and kickbacks at the Pentagon began nearly
three years ago.
   Kaub is also charged with two counts of filing false statements.
   The case involves what prosecutors say was a conspiracy to bribe
a Navy official for information about a $24 million contract that
Teledyne obtained in July 1987 to build hand-held radar test sets.
   The government claims the defendants knew that William Parkin, a
private consultant hired by Teledyne Electronics, was paying bribes
to Stuart Berlin, the Navy official.
   Both Parkin and Berlin, as well as Teledyne Industries, the
parent of Teledyne Electronics, have pleaded guilty in the case and
are cooperating with government.
   But the defendants said they didn't know Parkin had done
anything illegal.
   Kaub, Schnittjer and Sullivan testified Parkin was hired for
$10,000 for his expertise in November 1985.
   He was promised $150,000 if Teledyne won the radar contract,
which it did. Parkin was paid about $18,000 before the payments
stopped when the Ill Wind case was made public.
</TEXT>
