<FILEID>AP-NR-04-12-89 1027EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-HospitalKillings     04-12 0518</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hospital Killings,0531</SECOND>
<HEAD>Doctor Suspended At Austrian Hospital Where Patients Killed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   City authorities today suspended the
director of the hospital department where four assistant nurses
have confessed to killing at least 49 patients in the past six
years.
   The suspension followed mounting criticism of the chief doctor's
conduct during a police investigation last year at Vienna's Lainz
hospital, where elderly patients reportedly were killed by
overdoses of medicine or by forcing water into their lungs. Senior
police investigator Max Edelbacher said Monday that police met ``a
wall of silence'' at the hospital during the probe.
   A police report says the department head, Dr. Franz Pesendorfer
had declined to give police the name of a second doctor, who
alerted Pesendorfer to suspicions about the killings after talking
with a Chilean-born nurse's assistant.
   The four assistant nurses claim they engaged in ``mercy
killings,'' but police said the methods they used made that motive
unlikely.
   The Neue Kronen Zeitung, Austria's largest circulation tabloid,
said today that if Pesendorfer and the second doctor ``had not kept
quiet, it would fairly certainly have been possible to stop the
series of murders a year ago.
   ``As it was, however, the sadistic nurses could kill another 22
people,'' the newspaper added. Police have not confirmed media
reports that 22 of the 49 people killed were slain in the last year
alone.
   Mayor Helmut Zilk said he was suspending Pesendorfer, head of
the first medical department at Lainz hospital, ``on the grounds of
the results to date of the police investigations.'' He declined
further comment.
   Alois Stacher, chief of the city's health department, said
Pesendorfer was suspended because of ``lingering lack of clarity''
over the investigation.
   Pesendorfer consistently has defended his role in the
investigation and the conduct of officials in his department at the
Lainz hospital, Vienna's fourth largest, since the first word of
the killings on Friday.
   The doctor and other hospital officials declined comment today.
   The Chilean-born nurse's assistant, Dorah Eugenie
Ferrada-Avendano, was questioned by police Tuesday and arrested
after she admitted to witnessing one of the killings, Edelbacher
said. But he told The Associated Press he would try to free the
woman because ``she has really helped the police.''
   Ms. Ferrada-Avendano knew of killings at the hospital two or
three years before she told the unidentified doctor of her
suspicions last year, Edelbacher said on television Tuesday.
   He described her as a single parent who as a foreigner was
afraid of losing her job if she went to police. A former patient at
the hospital who knows the woman, now an Austrian citizen, told The
Associated Press she feared political persecution if forced to
return to Chile.
   Assistant nurses Maria Gruber, 25, Irene Leidorf, 27, and
Waltraud Wagner, 30, have been in custody since Friday. Stephanie
Mayer was detained Sunday. None of the women has been charged.
Police said the four women confessed they killed at least 49
patients and that Ms. Wagner admitted killing 39 of them.
   Pesendorfer is the first doctor or official suspended because of
the mass killings.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
