<FIRST>u a PM-WeatherpageWeather 1stLd-Writethru a0526 04-12 0528</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0526,0536</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cold Front Freezes Southeast</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with record lows, DELETE outdated
references to freeze warnings; PICKS UP 9th graf pvs, ``Elsewhere, a ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Temperatures plunged to record lows across the Southeast today
for the second day in a row, dropping below freezing as far south
as the central Gulf states and damaging fruit crops in Tennessee
and Alabama.
   Low temperature records were tied or broken at more than 20
cities from Texas to Virginia, including 15 degrees at Elkins,
W.Va.; 32 at Augusta, Ga.; 34 at Huntsville, Ala.; 41 at
Jacksonville, Fla.; 40 at New Orleans; 55 at Galveston, Texas, and
24 at Roanoke, Va.
   In Tennessee, peaches, plums and strawberries were the hardest
hit as the cold snap that sent temperatures below freezing Monday
night showed few signs of letting up. Lows in the state this
morning included 25 at Chattanooga, 25 at Bristol and 26 at
Knoxville, all records.
   ``I feel like probably 90 percent of what I looked at were
gone,'' said Tom Oswalt, an assistant agent with the Agricultural
Extension Service in Shelby County, after inspecting a plum orchard
Tuesday.
   ``These plums were anywhere from a quarter inch to a half inch
and they were ice all the way to the middle. You could mush them up
and they were just like crushed ice.''
   In northern and central Alabama, damage was reported to
blueberries, strawberries and peaches.
   Elsewhere, a cold front extending from the upper Great Lakes
across the central Plains and southern Colorado produced widely
scattered showers, mainly in Texas and Oklahoma. A few showers also
dampened parts of Florida.
   Today's forecast called for snow and rain scattered across the
eastern half of the Great Lakes; rain over the upper Ohio Valley;
and showers and thunderstorms in southern Florida and western parts
of the southern Plains.
   Highs were expected to be in the 30s over Upper Michigan; in the
40s from the upper Mississippi Valley to New England; in the 70s
and 80s in southern Texas, the Florida Peninsula, and parts of
Washington, Oregon, California, Nevada and Arizona; in the 90s over
the Desert Southwest; and in the 50s and 60s elsewhere.
   Temperatures at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 17 degrees at
International Falls, Minn., to 77 degrees at Phoenix and Glendale,
Ariz., and Blythe, Calif.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 41 fair; Boston 33 fair; Buffalo 26 fair;
Charleston, S.C. 38 fair; Cincinnati 32 fair; Cleveland 32 fair;
Detroit 38 cloudy; Miami 67 partly cloudy; New York 35 fair;
Philadelphia 36 fair; Pittsburgh 26 fair; Portland, Maine 27 fair;
Washington 37 fair.
   _Central: Bismarck 36 partly cloudy; Chicago 43 cloudy;
Dallas-Fort Worth 47 partly cloudy; Denver 31 fair; Des Moines 28
fair; Indianapolis 32 fair; Kansas City 39 fair; Minneapolis-St.
Paul 26 fair; Nashville 33 fair; New Oreans 40 fair; St. Louis 43
cloudy.
   _West: Albuquerque 47 windy; Anchorage 40 fair; Las Vegas 64
fair; Los Angeles 60 cloudy; Phoenix 74 fair; Salt Lake City 44
fair; San Diego 61 cloudy; San Francisco 51 fair; Seattle 48 fair.
   _Canada: Montreal 27 fair; Toronto 27 fair.
</TEXT>
