<FIRST>r i PM-Namibia 1stLd-Writethru a0529 04-12 0528</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Namibia, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0529,0542</SECOND>
<HEAD>Guerrillas Reject South African Interrogation Plans</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with guerrillas rejecting interrogation;
new police quotes. No Pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURINDA KEYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WINDHOEK, Namibia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Namibian guerrilla leader today
rejected South Africa's plan to interrogate insurgents who report
to U.N. peacekeepers to be escorted back to bases in Angola.
   By midday today, territorial police said no guerrillas of the
South-West Africa People's Organization had shown up at any of nine
checkpoints established Tuesday by the U.N. force monitoring
Namibia's transition to independence.
   ``It is not the business of South Africa to interrogate or check
SWAPO cadres. It the business of UNTAG and UNTAG alone,'' guerrilla
official Kapuka Nauyala said today of the U.N. Transition
Assistance Group.
   Sam Nujoma, SWAPO's exiled president, has called on his fighters
to withdraw as part of an agreement to get the U.N. independence
plan back on track after heavy fighting last week.
   South Africa says about 1,900 guerrillas infiltrated into
northern Namibia starting April 1, the day a cease-fire was to take
hold. U.N. investigators agree the guerrillas violated a peace
accord requiring they stay in Angolan bases at least until May 15.
   Territorial officials said Tuesday the United Nations had agreed
that police supervised by U.N. peacekeepers could interrogate
guerrillas who report to the checkpoints about the whereabouts of
other insurgents and possible arms caches.
   But a U.N. official, speaking on condition of anonymity, no such
agreement was reached.
   Nauyala, SWAPO's chief representative in Zimbabwe, said any
questioning by security forces would be unacceptable.
   ``UNTAG will commit a monumental sin if it allows itself to be
co-opted into South Africa's campaign aimed at discrediting and
humiliating SWAPO and its military cadres,'' Nauyala told the
Zimbabwe Inter-African News Agency.
   Black African nations last week denounced the special U.N. envoy
to Namibia, Martti Ahtisaari, who outraged them by allowing South
Africa-led security forces out of bases to fight the guerrilla
incursion.
   White security force officers and Namibian civilians who support
SWAPO predict few guerrillas will report to the checkpoints. They
cite the deployment of security force personnel at the points, the
proximity of military bases, and poor communication between
guerrilla commanders and their forces.
   Police said some guerrillas might try to cross into Angola
without reporting to checkpoints and others might hide their
weapons, don civilian clothes and try to stay in Namibia.
   Police Chief Inspector Derrick Brune said groups of insurgents
were seen today moving south, away from the Angola border.
   No major skirmishes have been reported since last weekend. South
Africa says 263 guerrillas and 27 security force members were
killed in fighting that erupted April 1. SWAPO says 38 of its
fighters and 54 civilians were killed. Another 15 guerrillas were
captured.
   South Africa has ruled the mineral-rich territory north of its
border since World War I and in defiance of U.N. demands it
withdraw.
   In December, Pretoria agreed to give Namibia independence in
exchange for Cuba withdrawing its 50,000 troops from Angola, where
they supported the Marxist government's forces in a civil war
against rebels backed by South Africa.
   SWAPO has been fighting South African rule since 1966.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
