<DOCNO> AP890412-0085 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-12-89 1049EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Lebanon 1stLd-Writethru a0541 04-12 0570</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0541,0585</SECOND>
<HEAD>Artillery Battle In Lebanon Kills 4, Injures 17</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 1 and 5 pvs to UPDATE with four killed; INSERTS 2
grafs after 5th pvs, ``Counting ...'' to add embassy guard killed. Edits
6th pvs for transition. Pick up 7th pvs, ``The Christian ...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Christian and Moslem forces fired
artillery shells at each others' strongholds in Beirut and nearby
mountains today, and police said the barrage killed four people and
wounded 17.
   Motorists sped away after a shell slammed into a seaside
boulevard near fish restaurants in Moslem west Beirut's Raouche
district.
   French Ambassador Paul Blanc told reporters a shell hit the
French Embassy compound in the Christian Hazmiyeh suburb, causing
damage but no injuries.
   Christian and Moslem forces accused each other of ordering
gunners to target residential districts of Beirut.
   Counting today's casualties, 184 people have died and 636 have
been wounded since the latest round of fighting in the civil war
began March 8 between Gen. Michel Aoun's mostly Christian army and
an alliance of Syrian and Druse forces.
   Also today, a Lebanese Christian security guard at the U.S.
Embassy was found dead from a shot to the head, police reported.
   They said they are investigating the death of Elias Haddad, 24,
whose body was found in a building entrance about a mile from
embassy compound in northern Beirut's Aukar suburb. Lebanese guards
support the embassy's Marine contingent.
   In Kuwait, a group of right-wing Christian politicians met with
Foreign Minister Sheik Sabah Al-Ahmad Al-Sabah, head of a
six-member Arab League panel. The politicians, led by Phalange
Party leader George Saadeh, discussed ways of ending Lebanon's
14-year-old civil war. The panel, formed in January, already has
met with Lebanese Moslem and religious leaders.
   The Christian Voice of Lebanon radio said Syrian gunners
provoked today's artillery barrage by shelling several areas in the
310-square-mile Christian enclave northeast of Beirut.
   The Moslem-run Voice of the Nation blamed the escalation on
Christian gunners and said they were targeting the Raouche district.
   Civilians rushed back in to bunkers and underground bomb
shelters. Shopkeepers lowered their shutters, and employees ran out
of their offices as the thud of exploding shells rocked the city.
   Last week, Syrian rockets set fire to a depot containing nearly
two-thirds of Lebanon's fuel reserves. The resulting fuel shortage
has reduced power supplies in some areas to one hour a day.
   The worst fighting in four years started after Aoun, who also
heads the Christian military Cabinet in Lebanon's divided
government, ordered a blockade of ports run by Moslem militias. He
said the illegally operated ports were costing the state treasury
$100 million in lost import dues.
   In retaliation, Druse warlord Walid Jumblatt's Progressive
Socialist Party militia shelled Beirut port and the Christian
enclave.
   Later, Syrian gunners joined in the shelling and supported a
land blockade of the Christian heartland by Moslem troops of Maj.
Gen. Sami Khatib.
   The rival Christian and Moslem governments emerged Sept. 22,
when outgoing President Amin Gemayel appointed Aoun, a Maronite
Catholic like him, to head an interim military Cabinet pending
parliament's election of a new head of state.
   Pro-Syrian Moslems rejected Aoun's appointment, which violated a
45-year-old tradition that gave the premiership to the Sunni
Moslems, the house speakership to the Shiite Moslems and the
presidency to the Maronites.
   The division threatens Lebanon with permanent, sectarian
partition.
</TEXT>
