<FIRST>r k BC-EditorialRdp 2ndAdd   04-12 0799</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Editorial Rdp, 2nd Add,0830</SECOND>
<HEAD>UNDATED: reparation payments.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   April 11
   Los Angeles Times on the pro-choice abortion rally:
   At least 300,000 people marched in Washington Sunday to leave a
message for the U.S. Supreme Court. ...
   Whether the court reads such messages is a matter of debate
among legal scholars, but the crowd of men, mothers and daughters,
celebrities and ordinary believers in the cause could not have made
a more coherent statement, one with which we absolutely agree:
Government has no right to pry into a decision as deeply personal,
private and agonizing as the one that every year leads 1.6 million
women to have abortions.
   The march, the largest ever seen in the capital, was timed to
catch the court's attention as it near the April 26 date for
argument in a Missouri abortion case. The court is being asked by
anti-abortion forces to use the Missouri case as a vehicle to
reverse the 1973 decision in the case of Roe vs. Wade that made
abortion legal under federal law. ...
   The march also was intended as a reminder that abortion is a
powerful symbol of the rights of women, even the many who oppose
abortion, because it involves decisions they are determined to make
for themselves about their health and the life they will lead. ...
   The court must look beyond legal principles to tenable social
policy and good sense, and both dictate that the right of a woman
to choose to terminate a pregnancy meets both of those tests.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   April 10
   The Patriot, Harrisburg, Pa., on the Soviet elections:
   The recent voting for members to the Congress of the People's
Deputies was the first relatively open election held in the Soviet
Union in 70 years.
   And remarkable as it may seem, given our far greater experience
at democracy, the Soviet election may have something instructive to
offer the American political system.
   Whether the elected People's Deputies get to exercise any degree
of power remains to be seen. Nevertheless, the stunning number of
high and mighty who were defeated dealt what The New York Times
headlined was ``a mortifying blow to party officials.''
   The magnitude of the revolt was made extraordinary by the
substantial number of candidates who were defeated even though they
ran without opposition. Voters were able to cross out the name of
unopposed candidates and thus register a ``no'' vote.
   If Americans could vote ``none of the above'' or against an
unopposed candidate, we suspect many more would go to the polls.
   The question is: Would our politicians dare to give the people
the option of voting for none of the above?
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   April 7
   Northeast Mississippi Daily Journal, Tupelo, Miss., on Polish
elections:
   The march of democracy continues. It's enough to make Vladamir
Lenin ... spin his tomb.
   Poland (has) announced ... that the government and the outlawed
labor union Solidarity have reached an accord that will make free
elections possible again. Poles have not voted in democratic
elections since 1945.
   The first ballot this year is guaranteed to give the Communist
Party almost a two-thirds majority, but the agreement throws the
electoral process wide open in subsequent elections.
   Few people besides the democrats in Poland, like Solidarity
leader Lech Walesa, thought this day would come.
   But it's also true that few people, at least in the West,
thought they ever would see Russians able to vote for anything that
resembles a democratic ballot. Soviets, some of them within sight
of Lenin's tomb in Moscow, voted in open elections three weeks ago.
   The West, led by the United States, can't be a Pollyana in the
face of rapid changes. But neither can any peace-loving Western
nation overlook opportunities to defuse world tensions and make
additional democratic reforms attractive to the East.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   April 4
   Corvallis (Ore.) Gazette-Times on drift-net fishing:
   There's good reason for calling drift-net fishing ``strip mining
of the sea.''
   An Asian fleet of 1,000 to 1,500 vessels deploys as many as
30,000 miles of drift net each day. Floating 30 feet down from the
ocean surface, the fine-meshed nylon nets catch not only fish and
squid, but everything else they encounter _ dolphins, whales, birds
and sea lions.
   Perhaps even worse, the nets are inefficient, wasting about half
the catch that is killed but then lost overboard. ...
   Under the Drift Net Impact Monitoring Assessment and Control Act
of 1987, the United States has been negotiating with Japan, South
Korea and Taiwan to place observers on their ships to determine
just how damaging drift-net fishing is. ...
   (T)he immediate task facing the United States is to get its
observers onto the Asian drift-net vessels. ... U.S. negotiators
must make it clear to the Asian governments that this country is
serious about ... sanctions.
</TEXT>
