<FILEID>AP-NR-04-12-89 1231EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-SouthKorea-Labor     04-12 0313</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-South Korea-Labor,0322</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Warns Of Economic Disaster From Labor Disputes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By M.H. AHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Roh Tae-woo said Wednesday
that labor unrest has cost South Korea $600 million in exports this
year and threatens to destroy the nation's economic achievements.
   ``Our economy now stands at the crossroads,'' Roh told a meeting
of top economic officials and business leaders. In addition to the
lost exports, labor problems have resulted in a drop in the
country's production of $2.4 billion, he said.
   There have been 395 labor disputes in South Korea this year, up
27 percent from a year ago, and 282 cases have been settled,
according to the Labor Ministry.
   In the past, South Korean workers' rights were curbed by
authoritarian rule, but a pro-democracy movement in the past two
years has encouraged workers to demand more.
   Roh said exports have been sluggish after years of high growth
and that investment has been shrinking because of labor disputes,
coupled with the rising value of the Korean won. A strong won makes
Korean exports to the U.S. more expensive.
   Korea also is under U.S. pressure to open wider its market to
American products and services.
   Last month, South Korea suffered its first trade deficit in 19
months.
   Roh urged labor and management to refrain from confrontation in
seeking to settle their disputes.
   The Federation of Korean Industries and five other national
economic organizations, in a joint statement, said labor disputes
should be settled through dialogue and reconciliation.
   On March 30, about 14,000 police stormed the Hyundai shipyard in
the southeastern city of Ulsan to break a 109-day strike by
thousands of workers, allegedly supported by outsiders, who had
staged a sit-in.
   No settlement has been reached yet with management.
   The shipyard reportedly suffered losses of $560 million from
canceled orders and $646 million in delayed exports.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
