<FIRST>r i AM-Netherlands-Soviet     04-12 0197</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Netherlands-Soviet,0203</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dutch Expel Soviet Official For Spying</HEAD>
<DATELINE>THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government has expelled a
Soviet shipping official for attempting to bribe Dutch officials
into giving him secret information, the Interior Ministry said
Wednesday.
   ``His activities were deemed dangerous to the state,'' Willem
Egels, a spokesman for the ministry's Domestic Security Service,
told The Associated Press.
   G.S. Karpechenkov, an employee of the Soviet trade mission in
Amsterdam, left the Netherlands on Sunday, Egels said.
   He refused to disclose what information Karpechenkov allegedly
tried to obtain.
   The Soviet was accredited to Sovfrakt, the trade mission's
shipping agency that operates out of the capital, Amsterdam, said
Egels. But he had worked mostly at the Rotterdam offices of
Transworld, a Dutch-Soviet joint venture in shipping, Egels said.
   Rotterdam is the world's biggest port and a frequent transit
point for high technology and computer equipment shipped between
Western Europe, Japan and the United States. The North Atlantic
Treaty Organization bans the export of several types of such
equipment to Soviet bloc nations.
   The port also plays a vital role in bringing U.S. troops and war
material to Western Europe in the event of a Warsaw Pact attack.
</TEXT>
