<DOCNO> AP890412-0098 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-12-89 1232EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Japan-China     04-12 0434</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-China,0445</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chinese Premier Visits Japan After Long Hiatus</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID THURBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China's Premier Li Peng arrived Wednesday on the
first visit to Japan by a Chinese head of state in seven years, and
Japanese officials said he played down his country's growing ties
with the Soviet Union.
   In talks with Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita, Li also expressed
support for Japan's position in a long territorial dispute with
Moscow and welcomed increased Japanese investment in China, a
Foreign Ministry official said.
   The ministry official, who briefed reporters on condition of
anonymity, quoted Takeshita as telling Li that close ties with
China were an important pillar of Japanese foreign policy.
   ``We hope the improved relations between China and the Soviet
Union won't have an adverse effect on good China-Japanese
relations,'' Takeshita was quoted as saying. ``We hope the
improvements will be carried out in such a way that they will
promote peace in all of Asia.''
   Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev is scheduled to visit
Beijing in May for the first Soviet-Chinese summit in 30 years. The
Communist countries split in 1960 over bitter ideological and
strategic differences.
   The official quoted Li as saying Beijing and Moscow had ``made
some progress, but no major progress'' toward closer relations in
the areas of economics, technology and science.
   ``But China will continue to follow a foreign policy of
independence and self-reliance,'' the official quoted him as saying.
   Li said China supported Japan's demand that Moscow return a
group of islands off northern Japan that it seized at the end of
World War II, the official added. The dispute over the Kuril
islands has been a major obstacle to the improvement of
Soviet-Japanese relations.
   The official said Li expressed pleasure over increased
Japanese-Chinese trade, which totaled a record $19.3 billion last
year, according to Japanese figures.
   Although Japan provides 80 percent of China's credit and serves
as its second-largest trading partner after Hong Kong, it accounts
for only 8 percent of China's total foreign investment.
   Japanese reluctance to invest in Chinese industries apparently
has grown in recent months due to a Chinese austerity program aimed
at reducing inflation. Some factories have been cut off from credit
and raw materials.
   Shortly before Li's arrival, Japan's parliament approved an
investment protection agreement signed during a visit by Takeshita
to China last summer and already ratified by Beijing. The pact
guarantees Japanese investors in China will receive equal treatment
with Chinese businesses.
   Li's visit is the first to Japan by a Chinese premier since Zhao
Ziyang, now Communist Party head, visited in May 1982.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
