<FIRST>r i AM-France-Lebanon     04-12 0334</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-France-Lebanon,0347</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mitterrand Says France Has no Side in Lebanon War</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Lebanon, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELAINE GANLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two French shipments of humanitarian aid to Lebanon
are for both Moslems and Christians and do not mean France is
choosing sides in that country's civil war, President Francois
Mitterrand said Wednesday.
   ``France is the friend of Lebanese of all religions, all
communities,'' Mitterrand told his Cabinet. ``The humanitarian aid
is a sign of friendship and solidarity for the Lebanese people,
nothing more than that.''
   Both ships arrived in Larnaca, Cyprus, on Wednesday morning, the
French Foreign Ministry said. The French minister for humanitarian
affairs, Bernard Kouchner, was in Beirut trying to arrange a means
of distribution, a spokesman said.
   The supplies are to help ease shortages caused by a month of
sectarian fighting. One vessel contains fuel and food and the other
is a hospital ship with beds, surgical facilities and medical
supplies.
   France, which ruled Lebanon from the end of World War I until
independence in 1943, has voiced concern about the fate of
Lebanon's Christian community and sent a special envoy to help
mediate the crisis.
   Lebanese Moslems have said the former colonial power is biased
in the dispute. They renounced their share of the supplies and
warned the ships against docking, stirring fears the issue could
trigger heavier fighting in the nation.
   The latest confrontation broke out after Gen. Michel Aoun's
mainly Christian army units blocked illegal militia-run ports that
have been stripping the Lebanese state treasury of about $100
million annually. Syrian troops joined the Druse forces of Walid
Jumblatt in retaliating with a blockade of Christian east Beirut
and surrounding Christian communities.
   The French ambassador to Lebanon, Paul Blanc, said the embassy
was damaged Wednesday in heavy artillery shelling around Beirut
   There are currently more than 4,300 French in Christian east
Beirut and 840 in mainly Moslem west Beirut.
   A Tuesday night prayer vigil for Lebanon at Notre Dame Cathedral
drew nearly 4,000 people.
</TEXT>
