<FIRST>r i AM-SouthKorea-Dissident     04-12 0276</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-South Korea-Dissident,0283</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police to Arrest Dissident Returning From North Korea</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL SHIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police said Wednesday they would
arrest a South Korean dissident upon his return from communist
North Korea, where he made an unauthorized visit for talks on
national unification.
   Demonstrations protesting the government plan to arrest Rev.
Moon Ik-hwan broke out in the capital.
   Dissidents and student radicals said they would defy a
government warning and greet the dissident, who was to arrive
Thursday from his nine-day North Korean trip.
   Government authorities planned to deploy 15,000 police at Kimpo
International Airport and other areas to block pro-Moon rallies and
anti-government protests by radical groups.
   Officials said Moon, 71, faces charges of violating the National
Security Law, which bans unauthorized trips to North Korea,
capitalist South Korea's archrival. A conviction on the charge
carries a possible 10-year jail sentence.
   At several schools in the capital, groups of 100 to 400 students
Wednesday hurled firebombs and rocks at riot police to protest the
plans to arrest Moon. Police retaliated with tear gas. There were
no immediate reports of arrests or injuries.
   In Suwon, 30 miles south of Seoul, 15,000 people rallied against
Moon's trip. Organizers said they would hold more anti-Moon rallies
in other cities in the coming week.
   Moon, a Presbyterian clergyman, was the first dissident leader
to visit North Korea. He publicly called the North's leader, Kim Il
Sung, ``a respected president whom I have wanted to meet so long.''
   Moon's trip triggered a major crackdown on the nation's
increasingly militant dissident groups, which officials say are
bent on overthrowing South Korea's democratic system.
</TEXT>
