<FIRST>r i AM-Cambodia-Party     04-12 0241</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cambodia-Party,0252</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cambodian Rulers Expand Government Ranks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cambodia's Communist Party has expanded
its ruling Politburo and Central Committee in an effort to
strengthen its forces before a scheduled pullout of Vietnamese
troops.
   Vietnam installed the Cambodian government after invading in
1978. Vietnamese officials announced last week they would withdraw
their estimated 50,000-70,000 troops by the end of September.
   In order to reach a political settlement, Cambodia's communist
rulers would be forced to negotiate with resistance forces backed
by the United States and China.
   ``The restructuring of this Fifth Party Central Committee was
needed to further strengthen and expand the leading role of the
Cambodian revolution,'' said an official Cambodian radio broadcast
in announcing the changes.
   The Politburo moves were made at an extraordinary session of the
Central Committee on Tuesday, the radio said. A text was obtained
in Bangkok on Wednesday.
   The radio said Tie Banh, a vice prime minister and the defense
minister, was elected to the Politburo.
   It also said the three alternate members of the Politburo were
made full members and three new alternates were picked.
   The new Politburo comprises 12 full members and three alternates.
   Earlier in the day, a national conference of party members
elected 21 new members to the policy-making Central Committee,
including 11 full members, the radio said. Seven alternate members
were also made full members.
   The broadcast said the committee now has 49 full members and 16
alternates.
</TEXT>
