<DOCNO> AP890412-0105 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-12-89 1248EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r p AM-Democrats-Rules     04-12 0511</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Democrats-Rules,510</SECOND>
<HEAD>Democratic Chairman Says Restore `Super Delegate' Status to Officials</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic Party chairman Ronald Brown, saying
he wanted to avoid a ``bloody and divisive fight,'' slammed the
door Wednesday on any sweeping re-examination of party rules, but
said he would support restoring automatic delegate status to party
officials.
   Brown's backing for giving ``super delegate'' status to
Democratic National Committee members could raise a new conflict
with Jesse Jackson.
   However, Brown already was getting caught between Jackson and
party activists who want to eliminate a rule that provides for
allocating national convention delegates to presidential candidates
on the basis of the proportion of votes they received in primaries
or caucuses.
   Robert Beckel, manager of Walter F. Mondale's 1984 presidential
campaign, is leading an effort to restore rules that would require
candidates to get a certain percentage of the vote to qualify for
receiving any delegates.
   ``We have to get closure on this process as early as possible,''
said Beckel.
   Told of Brown's comments, Beckel said, ``The last thing I want
to do is get into a fight with Ron Brown over the rules. ... If
Brown goes to the wall on this thing it would be very difficult to
do.''
   Beckel said he was not advocating formation of a new rules
commission. He said he hoped the DNC would adopt his proposed
changes at a meeting next fall.
   At the 1988 Democratic National Convention, with Brown serving
as Jackson's convention manager, new party rules stripped
Democratic National Committee members of the automatic delegate
status for future conventions and instituted proportional
representation as the basis for selecting delegates.
   Still, Jackson contended that minimum-vote requirements resulted
in denying him a proportion of delegates equal to the popular vote
he received. He also viewed the party and elected officials sent to
the convention, as uncommitted super delegates, as a force largely
opposed to his candidacy. Only a handful of elected officials
backed Jackson's bid for the presidential nomination.
   ``I have absolutely no intention to appoint, empower or create
any kind of rules commission,'' said Brown, at a news conference at
which he announced the appointments of senior DNC staff.
   ``We don't win or lose elections because of rules. ... I frankly
think it would be foolhardy for this party to spend the next two
years in a bloody and divisive fight over the rules,'' he said.
   After presidential election defeats in 1968, 1972 and 1980, the
Democrats engaged in sweeping revisions of the party rules. After
the 1984 defeat, the party went through a more modest change.
   Brown also said recent Democratic election victories in contests
to fill vacant House seats were of ``tremendous national
significance.''
   Democrat Jill Long was an upset victor in the contest to fill
the House seat in Indiana once held by Vice President Dan Quayle.
The Democrats also held a Democratic seat in Alabama and are given
a good chance of capturing the Wyoming House seat formerly held by
Dick Cheney, who resigned to become secretary of defense.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
