<FIRST>r a AM-ChukchiDrilling     04-12 0380</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chukchi Drilling,0389</SECOND>
<HEAD>Alaska Signs Off On Drilling In Remote Chukchi Sea</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Tanker Spill Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shell Western E&amp;P Inc. has cleared the
last major hurdle in its quest to become the first company to
explore for oil in the remote Chukchi Sea, known for extreme ice
and weather.
   The state has signed off on the project between northwest Alaska
and Soviet territorial water, clearing the way for the federal
government to issue Shell a permit to drill 80 miles northwest of
Alaska's Icy Cape.
   The state's ruling that Shell's plan was consistent with the
Alaska Coastal Zone Management plan came the day before the Exxon
Valdez ran aground, fouling Prince William Sound with more than 10
million gallons of oil in the nation's worst spill.
   Bob Grogan, director of the Alaska Division of Governmental
Coordination, said any proposed development in the Chukchi Sea,
north of the Bering Strait, likely would be scrutinized carefully
by the state and federal governments.
   ``Virtually anything right now dealing with oil and gas has to
be taken in context of the Valdez disaster,'' Grogan said.
   ``There's a tremendous amount of clamor in the Lower 48 and
coastal states for the president to call for a reassessment of the
Outer Continental Shelf,'' Grogan said. ``Alaska also is being
asked to be involved in these discussions. The state, no doubt,
will be doing its own rethinking.''
   The U.S. Minerals Management Service already has approved
Shell's exploration plan, which calls for up to 60 wells on 11
federal leases over the next four years.
   ``Although we have not completed our review, we don't anticipate
any real problem with it,'' said Rodney Smith, the federal agency's
supervisor of field operations. Shell should get its permit within
30 days, he said.
   Shell wants to drill its first well more than 15,000 feet deep
in 140 feet of water this summer. It plans to drill from a floating
rig being refitted in Victoria, B.C.
   The state encouraged Shell to work with the state Department of
Environmental Conservation to ensure that its plan contains a
``valid prediction of discharge movement and spreading of an oil
spill ...''
   The state approval requires Shell to employ safeguards to
protect fish and wildlife, particularly walruses that inhabit the
area.
</TEXT>
