<FIRST>r i AM-Germany-Firebombs     04-12 0380</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Firebombs,0393</SECOND>
<HEAD>Firebombs Thrown in Stock Exchange, Electronics Firm</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE BOEHMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Assailants hurled firebombs
inside the Frankfurt Stock Exchange and an electronics firm
Wednesday, and police blamed both attacks on supporters of jailed
terrorists staging a hunger strike.
   Two employees were slightly injured in the stock exchange attack
when at least six masked youths entered the main hall before
opening time and threw firebombs at computer terminals.
   Security officials seized three attackers, but the others
escaped, said Frankfurt police spokesman Oswald Neumann. He said
those held were two women, ages 24 and 27, and a 28-year-old man.
   Authorities said the attack destroyed or damaged several
computers and delayed the opening time by a few minutes.
   Earlier in the northern city of Muenster, unidentified
assailants set off a firebomb inside the offices of the AEG
electronics firm, a subsidiary of the Daimler-Benz automotive and
high-technology conglomerate.
   Authorities said the 3:30 a.m. attack caused millions of dollars
worth of damage but no injuries.
   Those attackers got away. The federal prosecution spokesman in
Karlsruhe, Alexander Prechtel, said supporters of jailed Red Army
Faction members on a hunger strike claimed responsibility in a
letter left near the scene.
   At least 34 imprisoned terrorists have been fasting to demand a
special cell block for jailed members of the radical organization,
which seeks to undermine West German capitalism with
assassinations, bank robberies and other attacks.
   Police said they believe group sympathizers carried out the
stock exchange attack as well.
   ``We are going on the supposition that this (the stock exchange
attack) is in connection with the ongoing hunger strike and demands
for Red Army Faction inmates to be placed together,'' said Neumann.
   Two of the fasting prisoners, Christa Eckers and Karl-Heinz
Dellwo, claim to have subsisted only on vitamins and water for 71
days. They are reported to be in serious condition.
   The message left near the electronics firm demanded that the
hunger strikers be housed together in one or two large groups,
Prechtel said.
   Prechtel said the Federal Protection Office is worried the
attacks could be a prelude to more violence by sympathizers.
   ``We fear that this is going to continue. We can only hope that
people don't become victims of the attacks,'' Prechtel said.
</TEXT>
