<HEAD>House Panel Authorizes Subpoenas for Oil Spill Investigation</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Tanker Spill Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House Interior Committee voted Wednesday
to use subpoenas if necessary to gather information in its
investigation of the Exxon Valdez accident in Alaska.
   Rep. George Miller, D-Calif., who made the proposal, said the
committee hasn't used its subpoena power in at least 15 years, but
he felt it was important to ``send a strong message to the
interested parties that we expect all parties to cooperate.''
   Miller heads the Subcommitee on Water, Power and Offshore Energy
Resources which will be handling the spill investigation for the
House.
   Interior Committee Chairman Morris Udall, D-Ariz., said great
discretion would be used.
   ``We haven't been exactly fast and loose with subpoena power,''
Udall said.
   The committee vote was unanimous, though Republicans said it
seemed premature since no one had refused to cooperate yet.
   The Exxon Valdez, a tanker owned by Exxon Corp., dumped 10
million gallons of oil into the Prince William Sound on March 24
when it ran aground. The spill into one of the nation's most
pristine areas continues to threaten environmentally sensitive
areas of the Alaskan shore.
   Miller has not yet scheduled hearings.
