<FIRST>r w AM-US-Mideast     04-12 0520</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Mideast,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Administration To Release Aid To Egypt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States has decided to release $230
million in economic aid to Egypt that had been held up while the
Arab government undertook bureaucratic reforms, the State
Department said Wednesday.
   Formal notification to Congress is expected by the end of the
week. Congress can delay the resumption of aid, but legally cannot
block it. Besides, a U.S. official said, there is no serious
opposition to ending the one-month suspension.
   The $230 million covers cash payments to Egypt for this year and
for 1988. Overall, Egypt is due to receive $1.63 billion in U.S.
economic assistance for the two years plus surplus food, making it
the largest U.S. aid recipient except for Israel.
   Congress conditioned delivery of the $230 million in cash
payments on unspecified reforms in the way Egypt administers the
aid. A decision to resume was taken coincide with the visit here
last week of President Hosni Mubarak.
   In response to a reporter's question, the State Department press
office issued a statement quoting President Bush as saying Mubarak
``enjoys our full support as he implements courageous reform
measures to strengthen Egypt's economy for future generations.''
   The statement added: ``Our cash transfer assistance will be part
of that support. We will be consulting with Congress and working
out the details of the release of the money in cooperation with the
Egyptian government.''
   Aid to Israel and to Egypt was boosted after the two countries
signed a peace treaty in 1979. Since then, the United States has
been liberal in assisting the two countries as its most reliable
friends in the Middle East. The aid also is a subtle way of
encouraging Israel and Egypt to support U.S. foreign policy in the
region.
   At the moment, the Bush administration is backing a proposal by
Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir to hold elections among the
1.4 million Palestinian Arabs who live on the West Bank and in Gaza.
   Mubarak has called instead for an international peace conference
and said the Palestine Liberation Organization should participate.
But Mubarak has not rejected the proposal categorically.
   The Arab League, of which Egypt is a member, and the PLO both
rejected the proposal this week. On Tuesday, the State Department
asked all critics to withhold judgment until the proposal is
developed.
   The U.S. official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said no
direct appeal was made to the PLO, with which the United States
opened talks last December over Israel's objections. The official
said another meeting with the PLO will be held but not for several
days at least.
   Egypt has one of the most cumbersome bureaucracies in the world
as well as a booming birth rate. An estimated 1 million people are
added to Egypt's population every 10{ months. There is widespread
poverty and housing is at a premium.
   Mubarak, during his visit, told American businessmen his
government was making progress in cutting red tape and in curbing
population growth. But he said the effort was partly offset by a
decline in the death rate.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
