<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Subversion     04-12 0436</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Subversion,0451</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Lawyer Asks for Review of New Decree on Subversion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A leading lawyer called Wednesday for the Supreme
Court to review a new law on subversion, saying it may conflict
with President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's policy of glasnost.
   The decree appears to be aimed in part at stopping nationalist
unrest like that in the republic of Georgia. It bans premeditated
acts aimed at inciting nationalist or racial animosity and actions
aimed at undermining the Soviet political and economic systems.
   Many dissidents have said the decree restricts freedom of speech
and other human rights, but the criticism by Alexander M. Yakovlev
was the first made publicly by a Soviet lawyer.
   Yakovlev, a department head at the Institute of State and Law,
made the remarks at a news conference and in an article published
Wednesday in the weekly newspaper Moscow News.
   He said that in general, the decree was an improvement over
earlier regulations banning ``anti-Soviet agitation and
propaganda'' and ``anti-Soviet slander.'' Those rules have been
used to jail dissidents.
   However, the lawyer said a section in the new rules on
``discrediting'' government bodies should be clarified.
   The clause says ``publicly insulting or discrediting''
government or state bodies or officials can be punishable by up to
three years in prison or a fine of up to $3,200.
   Yakovlev said his institute, part of the Soviet Academy of
Sciences, had drafted the decree. However, he said it was surprised
by the clause.
   ``The regulation on insulting and discrediting was just as much
news for us as for you,'' he told reporters.
   The lawyer said he did not know who inserted it into the decree,
which was approved Saturday by the Presidium, or executive council,
of the Supreme Soviet. The decree took effect Monday and will be
reviewed later by the full legislature, which can make changes,
Yakovlev said.
   Yakovlev suggested the discrediting rule might conflict with
glasnost, Gorbachev's policy of openness, because people should
have the right to criticize their government.
   Yakovlev called for ``urgent authoritative clarification'' of
the clause by the Supreme Court. The court can overturn the decree
and send it back for revision if it is deemed unconstitutional.
   ``If an organ is discredited by true information that is
revealed and objectively a loss of faith occurs as a result of
unconstitutional, illegal or criminal actions, in that sense there
can be no moral or criminal reproach,'' Yakovlev said.
   Another lawyer at the news conference, Felix M. Reshetnikov of
the All-Union Research Institute on Soviet Legislation, said the
decree should have banned only false accusations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
