<FIRST>r w AM-SavingsBonds     04-12 0125</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Savings Bonds,110</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sales Increased 3.2 Percent in March</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sales of U.S. savings bonds increased 3.2
percent in March to $713 million, the government reported Wednesday.
   The Treasury Department said sales for the first six months of
fiscal 1989, which began last October, totaled $4.02 billion, up
9.5 percent from the comparable period a year earlier.
   Effective last Nov. 1 through April 30, bonds held five years or
longer earn at an annual rate of 7.35 percent for the six months,
up from 6.9 percent during the previous six months.
   On May 1, a new rate will take effect based on open market
interest rates.
   As of March 31, the total value of savings bonds held by
Americans was $112.16 billion.
</TEXT>
