<FIRST>r w AM-BRF--LaborHallofFame     04-12 0186</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Labor Hall of Fame,170</SECOND>
<HEAD>Newest Labor Hall of Fame Members Announced</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The late labor leaders John L. Lewis, George
Meany and A. Philip Randolph, and former Labor Secretary James P.
Mitchell, have been named newest members of the Labor Hall of Fame.
   The Friends of the Department of Labor, a non-partisan group
that sponsors the Labor Hall of Fame, announced the selections
Wednesday.
   The four will be honored along with previous inductees with
exhibits in the lobby of the Labor Department's Washington offices
at the Frances Perkins Building on Constitution Avenue.
   Lewis, who died in 1969, was president of the United Mine
Workers and founder of the Congress of Industrial Organizations.
Mitchell, who died in 1964, was labor secretary during most of the
Eisenhower administration.
   Randolph, who died in 1979, was founder of the Brotherhood of
Sleeping Car Porters, the first black vice president of the
AFL-CIO, and a leader in the civil rights movement.
   Meany, who died in 1980, was longtime head of the AFL-CIO and
was instrumental in the merger of the American Federation of Labor
with the CIO.
</TEXT>
