<FIRST>r a AM-DropoutRates     04-12 0220</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dropout Rates,0226</SECOND>
<HEAD>Little Improvement Cited in New Figures</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dropout rate for public school students has
leveled off over the past few years, according to statistics
released Wednesday.
   Figures from the Board of Education for the 1987-88 school year
show the four-year dropout rate for high school students was 26.8
percent and the systemwide percentage was 29.7.
   These are up slightly from the year before when the high school
rate was 26.3 percent and the systemwide figure was 29.2 percent.
   A separate study that followed individuals for their four years
of high school ending in 1988 said 20.8 percent of the students had
dropped out. In 1987, this study said 22.4 percent of students quit.
   Schools Chancellor Richard Green said more funding is needed for
dropout prevention programs.
   The studies use separate methodologies to determine the dropout
rate. The Cohort Report follows students for four years after they
enter ninth grade and the Annual Dropout Report analyzes the
students who dropped out during 1987-88.
   The Annual Dropout Report also offers a racial and ethnic
breakdown and showed that the dropout rate among Hispanic students
was significantly higher than the average.
   It said the four-year, systemwide dropout rate among Hispanic
students was 31.8 percent; for blacks, 24.5 percent; whites, 19.2
percent; and Asians, 15.2 percent.
</TEXT>
