<FIRST>u w PM-Bush-Honduras 1stLd-Writethru a0625 04-12 0332</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Honduras, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0625,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Document Strengthens Bush Link to Quid Pro Quo Deal</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Restores dropped words in 8th graf, It is</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A document introduced at Oliver North's
Iran-Contra trial strengthens the suggestion that then-Vice
President George Bush knew Honduras was being rewarded for its
support of the Nicaraguan rebels with additional U.S. aid.
   A National Security Council draft memo bears the handwritten
notation, ``We want VP to also discuss this matter'' with Honduran
President Roberto Suazo.
   The handwriting in the margin of the Feb. 20, 1985 document is
next to a typewritten section of the memo detailing the quid pro
quo arrangement.
   Bush had earlier warned against the possibility of such
arrangements, according to another document released earlier in
North's trial _ the minutes of a June 25, 1985 meeting of the
National Security Planning Group.
   Bush had said there could be a problem if the administration
used U.S. aid to entice third countries to aid the Contras.
   The congressional Iran-Contra investigating committees looked
into the possibility the administration had engaged in such
arrangements but were unable to prove they existed.
   Asked about the new documents coming to light at North's trial,
White House Press Secretary Marlin Fitzwater said today that all
the documents had been made available to the independent counsel
prosecuting North for his review in the past.
   It is up to the counsel to decide whether to turn them over to
the investigating committees, Fitzwater said. He said the White
House was not investigating any of the matters.
   A 42-page summary of the Reagan administration's quid pro quo
arrangements with other countries on Contra support was released
last week.
   It said Bush met with Suazo and told him about enhanced U.S. aid
shortly after the quid pro quo arrangement with Honduras was made.
But the summary did not say whether Bush knew the enhanced aid was
in exchange for the Central American country's support of the
Contras.
</TEXT>
