<FIRST>r a PM-MurderAcquital     04-12 0148</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Murder Acquital,0150</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jury Rejects Hand-Squeeze Identification</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury rejected a comatose man's
hand-squeeze identification of his attackers and acquitted two men
in his beating death.
   The jury late Tuesday found Gerald L. Scott, 26, and Elonzia
Armstrong Jr., 25, innocent of murder, manslaughter and robbery in
an attack on 47-year-old Robert Abreu outside a tavern Oct. 4.
Abreu died nine days after the attack.
   Abreu could not speak or open his eyes the day after the
beating, but police Investigator Timothy Chura testified that
during a hospital visit Abreu squeezed his hand when Chura named
Scott, Armstrong and a third man who was never charged.
   A neurologist called by the defense testified that Abreu could
not have been able to communicate because he was in a coma. The
neurologist said the squeeze was more likely a ``grasp reflex''
common among comatose patients.
</TEXT>
