<HEAD>President Cancels Trip to Maine Home</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush today abruptly canceled a
three-day vacation trip to Kennebunkport, Maine, that was to have
started Thursday.
   Despite the cancellation, Bush still will make a scheduled trip
to Union, N.J., on Thursday for a speech. He will return to
Washington the same day.
   Press Secretary Marlin Fitzwater said the president wanted to be
in town because budget negotiations between Congress and the
administration were at a critical point, with both sides shooting
for an agreement by Saturday.
   He said personal matters also were involved.
   Anna Perez, press secretary to Barbara Bush, said the first
lady's health was not a factor in the decision. Mrs. Bush underwent
radiation treatment to destroy her thyroid gland today because it
is producing excess levels of hormones.
   Ms. Perez said Bush's son, Jeb and his wife Columba, are flying
to Washington from Florida and that other family members may come
in.
   ``The kids are going to be in town and it occurred to them, `Why
are we going at all?''' Ms. Perez said.
   Dozens of hotel rooms have been booked for press and White House
staff members in Kennebunkport for the trip, which was to have run
from Thursday to Sunday. Bush also had planned meetings with
schoolteachers and firemen in Kennbunkport.
