<SECOND>AM-Brazil-Rain,0196</SECOND>
<UNK>Rains Leave 23 Dead in Brazil</UNK>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At least 23 people died and
thousands were left homeless Wednesday in rains that pounded
northeast Brazil, rescue officials said.
   Downpours left 19 dead in the coastal city of Joao Pessoa, 1,614
miles northeast of Rio in the state of Paraiba, Fire Department
official Luis Jose da Silva told The Associated Press by telephone.
   All of the victims were from two shantytowns on the city's
outskirts and were killed when their homes collapsed, da Silva said.
   ``Rescue workers are still at the shantytowns digging through
the mud, and we're sure there'll be more victims,'' da Silva said.
   The rains, which began a week ago, had already killed six other
residents of the city.
   In Recife, capital of the neighboring state of Pernambuoco, four
family members were killed in a slum neighborhood when their home
collapsed early Wednesday, according to Civil Defense coordinator
Col. Edvaldo Cunha Cavalcante.
   Cavalcante said about 200 families left homeless by the rains
were being housed in publc buildings in Recife and that another 300
families throughout the state were being given emergency shelter.
