<FIRST>u a PM-NuclearBarge 1stLd-Writethru a0560 04-12 0387</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nuclear Barge, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0560,0395</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reactor Vessel Reaches Hanford</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with vessel arriving in Richland;
PICKS UP 5th graf pvs, `As the ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICHOLAS K. GERANIOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RICHLAND, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A barge carrying the mammoth reactor
vessel from the nation's first commercial nuclear plant completed
an 8,000-mile trip today to Washington state, where it will be
buried at the Hanford nuclear complex.
   Protesters hurled paint canisters and unfurled banners as the
reactor vessel from the dismantled Shippingport, Pa., nuclear plant
made its way up the Columbia River in six-week journey that took it
through the Panama Canal.
   The barge arrived at a dock on the edge of Richland. The reactor
vessel will be trucked 25 miles to the burial trench where it will
be entombed Friday.
   Hanford, the government nuclear weapons complex, already is the
final resting place for three nuclear submarine reactor cores.
   The 1,000-ton reactor vessel, 45 feet high and 18 feet across,
once held the uranium fuel that powered the nation's first
commercial nuclear plant, which shut down in 1982.
   The vessel was packed with concrete for the journey, and
officials said it poses no threat of radiation.
   As the barge made its way up the Columbia River Gorge on
Tuesday, 50 to 70 protesters on a bridge waved banners and signs
and hurled canisters of lime green paint.
   At least three small containers of paint were hurled from the
bridge. One struck the gray cover of the reactor vessel and two
others hit the barge.
   ``We're trying to show that the local community in the gorge is
not thrilled to be a nuclear highway,'' said Cyndi deBruler of
Bingen, an organizer of the demonstration.
   Earlier Tuesday, a fire broke out in the engine room of the
tugboat pushing the barge, causing a seven-hour delay but no
injuries, said Wendy Anderson of the company that owns the tug.
   ``At no time was there any danger of the reactor vessel going
aground,'' she said.
   But Ms. DeBruler said the fire showed the potential for danger.
``If there were 60 mph winds, and it was powerless, it could lead
to an accident,'' she said.
   The protesters said their main concern with the vessel is
leakage into the river after it is buried.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
