<FILEID>AP-NR-04-12-89 1759EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-FSX     04-12 0386</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-FSX,360</SECOND>
<HEAD>`No Comment' on Report of Japanese Concessions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARTON REPPERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The White House declined to comment Wednesday
on a published report that Japan has agreed to allow 40 percent of
the work on a new, co-produced jet fighter to be done in the United
States.
   The New York Times, citing an unidentified Bush administration
official, said Wednesday that Japan has also eased its reluctance
to share technology from the FSX fighter venture.
   The newspaper said the concessions signaled that the deal would
shortly be sent to Congress, where critics have said the project
could amount to a U.S. giveaway of much-needed aircraft technology
to Japan's aircraft industry.
   Asked about the status of the FSX negotiations with Japan, White
House spokesman Bill Harlow said:
   ``I don't have anything new on it. As far as I know, it's still
under discussion. Nothing is resolved at this point.''
   Another U.S. official, who spoke on condition that he not be
identified, said he found the Times story ``a little bit premature.
Things are close, but not quite there yet.''
   Shingo Yamagami, press counselor at the Japanese Embassy, also
declined to comment on the Times story. He said U.S. and Japanese
officials ``are still continuing their discussions about
clarifications. We haven't reached any final conclusion yet.''
   The United States and Japan reached an agreement in principle
late last year under which St. Louis-based General Dynamics would
join with Japan's Mitsubishi Heavy Industries to co-develop and
co-produce a next-generation fighter, for deployment by Japan in
the late 1990s.
   The project to build the FSX, which would be an advanced version
of the F-16 fighter, has been stalled due to the Bush
administration's decision to obtain ``clarifications'' from the
Japanese.
   Proponents argue that the agreement represents the best the
United States could negotiate _ in view of Japanese opposition to
buying American-made F-16s _ and will promote beneficial technology
transfer in both directions while providing income and jobs for
U.S. companies.
   Critics, however, contend that the deal amounts to a giveaway of
$7 billion worth of technology that Japan likely will use to help
propel its aircraft industry into head-to-head competition with the
United States. They say Japan should, instead, purchase American
planes to help offset the $50 billion U.S. trade deficit with Japan.
</TEXT>
