<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Duchess of York says she's hurt by public
criticism that she takes too many vacations and does too little
work, but doesn't care what people say about her clothes.
   In an interview with Yorkshire Television to be broadcast
Sunday, the duchess said she calls on ``inner strength and
control'' to ignore criticism and get on with her job. ``I am
sensitive and I do get hurt,'' she said.
   The duchess, who was known as Sarah Ferguson before her marriage
to Prince Andrew, described him as ``the most incredible husband''
and said their infant daughter, Princess Beatrice, has ``enhanced
our lives.''
   A recent survey of public engagements carried out by members of
the royal family placed the duchess and her husband, Queen
Elizabeth II's second oldest son, near the bottom.
   The 29-year-old duchess said that when people claim she takes
too many vacations, ``My immediate reaction is `if only they knew.'
''
   The duchess said she's not bothered by frequent criticism of her
fashion sense.
   ``My clothes and what I look like, really that's entirely up to
me ... Andrew likes it and I like it and if no one else does, well
that's their problem.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sophia Loren says she doesn't mind being
recognized on the street or stopped for an autograph.
   ``Being famous has a price, but it's useless and utterly
hypocritical to complain about it,'' the 54-year-old actress said
in the May issue of McCall's.
   In fact, Loren says she takes advantages of few of the perks of
stardom.
   ``I do it all myself: dye my hair, do my nails, everything,''
she said.
   And she adds that aging doesn't scare her.
   ``All seasons of life are beautiful if you keep up with things,
with your family, with your career, with your everlasting dreams
and ambitions,'' Loren said. ``Besides, I don't think there is a
specific age at which one feels at his best; happiness doesn't have
a prefixed rendezvous.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Entertainer Sammy Davis Jr. will receive
the third annual Harry Zimmerman Memorial Award on June 22 for his
contributions to the Muscular Dystrophy Association.
   Davis has been a longtime co-host and performer for the national
Jerry Lewis Labor Day Telethon to benefit the association. He also
is national vice president of the group, which will present the
award at a dinner at the Opryland Hotel.
   Lewis received the award last year. It is named in memory of a
longtime supporter of the association who was the founder of
Nashville-based Service Merchandise Inc., a discount store chain.
   Davis is performing in concerts and in the movie ``Tap.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jack G. Copeland, chief heart surgeon at
the University of Arizona Medical Center, wasn't celebrating after
he performed his program's 200th heart transplant.
   ``It feels good, but it'll feel a lot better when she's out of
the hospital,'' he said Tuesday. Patient Nobuko Rosenberg of Tucson
received a retransplant earlier in the day.
   The Arizona heart transplant program marked its 10th anniversary
last month. The 100th transplant was performed in 1986.
   The 200th ``came a lot sooner than we thought it would,'' said
Copeland. ``We're doing more every year.''
   In addition to new technology, the program has been lucky at
getting donors ``and we're ready to go at any time. We make
ourselves available,'' he said.
</TEXT>
