<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     04-12 0405</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LANSING, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michigan would have an official state soil
to nourish its official state tree and state flower under
legislation passed Wednesday by the state Senate.
   The bill, approved 25-8 and sent to the House, would honor the
Kalkaska soil series. The sandy soil, one of about 450 soil types,
is located across both peninsulas and covers 500,000 acres of the
state's 35 million acres.
   The soil type is named for Kalkaska County, where it first was
found by state soil researchers in 1927. The soil is practically
exclusive to Michigan, with only a small amount found in northern
Wisconsin.
   ``It is a very pretty soil, with distinct layers of dark and
light,'' said Sen. Connie Binsfeld, a Republican who represents _
no surprise here _ Kalkaska County. ``Our state tree, the white
pine, is found in Kalkaska soil.''
   The bill provoked the inevitable jokes: ``A real dirty, rotten
filthy piece of legislation,'' said Sen. Mich Irwine.
   Some lawmakers expressed concerns about approving legislation
that voters could regard as trivial. But at least none proposed an
official state manure to fertilize the state soil.
   For the record, Michigan's state flower is the apple blossom.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CRYSTAL LAKE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When a book was returned to the
Crystal Lake Public Library 22 years late and worse for wear,
librarians had no complaints. Four $100 bills fluttered out, more
than enough to pay the fine.
   ``The book's a bit shabby, but it's back home again,'' Librarian
Arden Perkins said Tuesday.
   The book, titled `The Folk Song Abecedary'' by James F. Leisy,
arrived at the library in a plain brown wrapper last week.
   Folded inside was a note from the anonymous borrower.
   ``This book was removed from your library several years ago. I
am returning it with overdue fines and apologies,'' the note said.
   Ms. Perkins said that based on the 5-cent-per-day fine the
library levies for overdue books, this one must have been checked
out 22 years ago, shortly after it was put on the shelves.
   Circulation records are not kept that long, so the only clues to
the whereabouts of the borrower is the postmark from De Kalb, Ill.,
and the book being wrapped in the De Kalb Chronicle.
   Ms. Perkins said the library only would have required the
borrower to pay the value of a book, plus $3, but will treat the
$400 as a gift.
</TEXT>
