<FIRST>r i AM-Hamadi     04-12 0438</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hamadi,0456</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lebanese Police Say They Wanted Confessed Hijacker For Murder</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NESHA STARCEVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hijacker Mohammed Ali Hamadi was
wanted for murder in Lebanon two years before his 1985 seizure of a
TWA jetliner, according to a police document presented Wednesday at
his trial.
   Lebanese police sent the document in response to a request from
West German federal police for information on Hamadi following his
arrest in January 1987.
   Hamadi, a Lebanese Shiite Moslem, is charged with murder and air
piracy in the June 1985 hijacking of TWA Flight 847. Thirty-nine
Americans were held hostage for 17 days and U.S. Navy diver Robert
Stethem was killed.
   Hamadi admitted taking part in the hijacking but denied shooting
Stethem. He was arrested at Frankfurt airport when customs
officials discovered liquid explosives in his luggage.
   The document read in court said a Lebanese arrest warrant was
issued for Hamadi in July 1983 for ``murder and illegal possession
of weapons.'' It gave no details.
   Hamadi, who lived in West Germany from 1982 to 1984, told the
court he knew nothing about it. It was not clear if the warrant is
current.
   ``I have been carrying weapons since 1979 with the permission of
west Beirut authorities,'' he said. Since the civil war broke out
in 1975, the Lebanese capital's western part is policed by Moslem
militias and the eastern sector by Christian forces.
   Hamadi said the arrest warrant may have been issued by Christian
authorities. He has testified he fought in battles in Lebanon
before and after his stay in West Germany.
   He also has testified that he belonged to Amal, a mainstream
Shiite Moslem militia, from 1980 to 1982. He has denied prosecution
charges he later joined Hezbollah, a radical Shiite group backed by
Iran.
   The court also was read five letters Hamadi wrote from the
Frankfurt prison after his arrest. Prison authorities apparently
intercepted them after Hamadi tried to have them smuggled out.
   In one letter, Hamadi appeared to solicit the help of his
brother, Abdul-Hadi, who is Hezbollah's security chief in Beirut.
   Several times Hamadi advises Abdul-Hadi to be ``very careful.''
   ``They are asking me about you all the time and they have found
out that I am with Hezbollah,'' one letter says.
   Hamadi confirmed he wrote the letters but refused to answer any
questions about them.
   In several letters, he discussed worries he would be extradited
to the United States.
   Washington requested his extradition but the West German
government refused. The trial resumes April 19, when Chief Judge
Heiner Mueckenberger says he hopes to have the final presentation
of evidence.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890412-0135 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-12-89 2110EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Israel-PLOSpy     04-12 0245</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-PLO Spy,0251</SECOND>
<HEAD>Israeli Sentenced To Three Years For Passing Secrets To PLO</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet-born Israeli was sentenced to three
years in prison Wednesday for passing army secrets to the Palestine
Liberation Organization, Israel radio said.
   Benjamin Shenkman, 36, was convicted March 30 of giving
information to the organization, which Israel considers a terrorist
group. He also was convicted of having contacts with PLO agents.
   The maximum sentence for the charges was 33 years, but the
prosecution agreed to a shorter sentence because Shenkman confessed
and aided police investigators.
   Shenkman told the Tel Aviv court he traveled to Athens three
times in 1988 and gave PLO officials information on his military
service, including locations of bases and the names of his
commanders.
   He also offered to fly to PLO headquarters in Tunis, Tunisia,
and hold a news conference where he was to tear up his passport and
denounce Israel as a racist state.
   He asked for $1.5 million in return but never received any
money. He was arrested at Israel's Ben-Gurion airport when he
returned from his third visit to Athens.
   Shenkman immigrated to Israel in 1978 from the Soviet Union and
served in the army for four months in 1985.
   His was the second case of espionage involving a Soviet emigre.
On Dec. 15, 1988, Shabtai Kalmanovich, 45, was sentenced to nine
years in prison on charges of spying for the Soviet Union and
having contacts with a foreign agent.
</TEXT>
