<DOCNO> AP890412-0137 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-12-89 2113EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Budget     04-12 0381</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Budget,360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Budget Negotiators Say Agreement Near</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congressional budget negotiators expressed
confidence Wednesday that agreement with the White House was near
on a $28 billion deficit reduction plan for next year.
   ``The parameters are there. The outline of an agreement is
there,'' said Sen. Jim Sasser, D-Tenn., chairman of the Senate
Budget Committee.
   The negotiating group, which includes Treasury Secretary
Nicholas Brady, White House budget director Richard Darman, and the
senior members of the House and Senate budget committees, was
checking its own ideas with people who would have to approve them.
   ``When you do a budget, there are a whole lot of numbers and
agreements to put together in which you have to gain the complete
cooperation of a lot of people in Congress other than the
negotiators. So you have to run around and talk to all your
friends'' on various committees, said Rep. Bill Frenzel, R-Minn.,
senior Republican on the House Budget Committee.
   ``We have not hit anything that could be called a snag,'' said
Rep. Thomas Foley, D-Wash., the House Majority Leader.
   In more than a month of talks, the group has been searching for
a compromise that would reduce the fiscal 1990 federal deficit by
about $28 billion, to comply with the Gramm-Rudman law's goal of
limiting red ink to $100 billion.
   About half of the savings would come from holding spending
growth below inflation for military and many domestic programs, and
the other half from new revenues _ user fees, sales of government
assets, and about $5 billion in new taxes.
   President Bush's budget included about the same amount of new
revenues, but mostly from his proposal to cut the tax rate on
capital gains. A lower tax rate on capital gains would actually
yield additional revenue of $4.8 billion next year, according to
the administration.
   Congressional Democrats oppose the capital gains plan as a break
for the wealthy, but the negotiators have agreed to include the
overall tax figure in their plan in hopes that Congress and the
president can agree later on something that won't violate Bush's
``no new taxes'' pledge.
   The House Republican Study Committee, a group of conservative
lawmakers, on Wednesday approved a resolution opposing any new
taxes in the pact.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
