<FIRST>r a AM-Spill-Nature'sHand     04-12 0480</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Spill-Nature's Hand,0492</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mother Nature Proves Better Oil Cleanup Force Than Man</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Tanker Spill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FRED BAYLES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP National Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VALDEZ, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After 20 days of arduous work and
uncounted millions of dollars, the worst effects of the nation's
biggest oil spill appear to be waning.
   Yet for all the work done by 1,000 people on the water and
shoreline and other thousands of support personnel, much of the
result is being attributed to the muscular forces of nature.
   ``The natural processes have far outweighed ours,'' Jim Hayden,
the state's cleanup coordinator, said earlier this week.
   Hayden and other officials acknowledge much of the easing
situation must be credited to nature:
   _An estimated 30 to 40 percent of the 10.1 million gallons of
oil that poured from the tanker Exxon Valdez has been dissipated by
natural evaporation of the more volatile components of the crude
oil. By Thursday less than 20,000 barrels, under 10 percent of the
spill, will have been recovered by human effort.
   _Favorable weather through most of the 20 days since the spill
pushed vast amounts of the oil out of Prince William Sound and into
the Gulf of Alaska where several days of high wind and heavy seas
churned and broke up the slick.
   _Aerial observations this week indicated that some blackened
beaches on the islands and inlets of the sound are being cleansed
by the heavy wave action.
   The spill's disastrous effects are far from over. It is feared
the toll of wildlife will continue and even grow as migrating birds
return to the oiled beaches.
   It will be years before scientists know the impact on the vast
ecosystem in Prince William Sound.
   Yet scientists are warning that nature must be given a big share
of the cleanup work that remains. They say too much human labor and
technology applied to oiled areas could do more harm than good.
   ``We've seen from other spills that if we hit an area too hard
with things like high pressure water or heavy equipment, we wind up
killing everything,'' said John Robinson, chief of the hazardous
material response branch of the National Oceanic and Atmospheric
Administration.
   Robinson said much of the shoreline hit by the oil is of a rock
and gravel mix. If efforts to clean the beaches are too vigorous,
he said, it could force the oil deep into the ground, where it can
affect microscopic life valuable to the area's ecosystem.
   Robinson said the public's anxiety to clean the remaining mess
as quickly as possible must be balanced with the realization that
some areas would be better left to a slower cleanup job by nature.
   ``I'm optimistic that the officials here understand that,'' he
said. ``I would hope that the public doesn't get frustrated with
what might seem like a slow process and not press us into doing it
too fast.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890412-0141 </DOCNO>
