<FIRST>r i AM-Israel-Prison     04-12 0565</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Prison,0585</SECOND>
<HEAD>Palestinian Women Inmates Complain Of Conditions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICOLAS B. TATRO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEL MONDE, Israel (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rulla Abdo Dihu sat on the steps of the
prison exercise yard Wednesday and said with chilling conviction
that she would take up arms again if she were freed.
   ``I didn't kill for myself. I'm not a criminal. I'm a political
prisoner. What I did, I did for my people,'' the Palestinian
Christian told a reporter during a tour of the security wing of Tel
Monde prison in central Israel.
   Ms. Dihu, 20, from the West Bank town of Ramallah, was sentenced
in January 1988 to 25 years jail for getting a gun that another
Palestinian used to kill an Israeli soldier.
   Asked if she regretted her act, Ms. Dihu responded in a voice
choked with emotion: ``Why should I be? We are fighting for our
justice. We are at war. All's fair in love and war ...
   ``I would love to go back to fighting with my people in the
intefadeh,'' she said, using the Arabic word for the uprising
against Israeli rule in the occupied territories.
   She is one of 24 Palestinian women transferred to a segregated
wing here after the rebellion spilled over to the central women's
prison at Neve Tirza.
   The tensions resulted in hair-pulling battles between Israeli
criminals and Arab political detainees.
   ``They beat up one of the Palestinian women and shouted curses
against the PLO and our leaders,'' said Terry Boulatta, 22, of
Jerusalem, who awaits trial on charges of organizing anti-Israeli
demonstrations March 8.
   The political activism of Arab women is a change in traditional
lifestyle that has grown out of the uprising. As thousands of
Palestinian men have been arrested or wounded, women and children
have taken their places at the forefront of street protests.
   Israeli officials refuse to say how many women are behind bars.
   During the tour, Palestinian women complained of rodent
excrement in food, mosquitoes in cells and lack of medical
attention.
   They live two to a cell in a two-story wing with a central
courtyard open to the sky. Children's paintings of an Arab village
and a field of flowers remain from the facility's days as a
juvenile center.
   Ms. Boulatta, who has been jailed four times for political
activism, complained she receives no medical help for a liver
dysfunction diagnosed by Arab doctors.
   She said a doctor visits the prisons for a half hour three times
a week. ``They only look at me and say `you're okay and go back to
your room.'''
   Prison physician Dr. Victor Romanov said an Israeli specialist
examined and tested Ms. Boulatta but found nothing wrong.
   Some complaints about food and conditions seemed exaggerated.
Prison Commissioner Levy Shaul rejected them.
   He called Tel Monde a model prison but conceded overcrowding and
poor standards plague other facilities where anti-Israeli activists
are held.
   ``Overcrowding is such that in some facilities prisoners have to
stand in line for a bathroom,'' he said.
   Shaul noted women in Tel Monde are allowed family visits and
have access to radio, television, newspapers and some non-political
books.
   Israeli authorities have refused requests from reporters to
visit other prisons, especially the Ketziot detention center in the
Negev desert, where several thousand Arab activists are living in
tents, exposed to searing desert winds and heat. Most are held
without trial for up to six months.
</TEXT>
