<FIRST>r a AM-Soviets-Libel     04-12 0277</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviets-Libel,0283</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Refuses To Reinstate Libel Case Against Izvestia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court refused Wednesday
to reinstate a businessman's $250,000 libel award against the
Soviet newspaper Izvestia, saying a foreign government publication
cannot be sued for libel.
   The 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals also overturned $163,165
in breach-of-contract damages for Raphael Gregorian of Palo Alto
against Soviet trade organizations. Despite initially refusing to
appear in court on the advice of their government, the
organizations should have a chance to contest Gregorian's claims,
the court said.
   Gregorian's California International Trade Corp. had sold
medical and laboratory products to the Soviet Union since 1970.
Gregorian said the government and two trading organizations,
Medexport and Licensintorg, accepted and used hospital equipment in
1984 but failed to pay for it.
   In November 1984, the Soviet Ministry of Foreign Trade withdrew
the company's license to maintain a business office in the Soviet
Union. The following week, an article in Izvestia accused Gregorian
of smuggling, bribery and unethical business practices, and implied
he had been spying for the United States, the court said.
   Gregorian's lawsuit contended the newspaper article and the loss
of his license were attempts to avoid payment for the hospital
equipment.
   When Soviet officials refused to respond to the lawsuit, U.S.
District Judge David Kenyon found them in default and awarded
damages. Gregorian then seized a typewriter belonging to a U.S.
correspondent for Izvestia and got an order allowing him to
confiscate money in a U.S. bank account held by a Soviet agency.
   Kenyon later overturned the libel judgment. Wednesday's 3-0
ruling upheld that decision and ordered him to reconsider the
contract claim.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
