<FIRST>r i AM-AussieEarl     04-12 0666</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Aussie Earl,0682</SECOND>
<HEAD>Aussie Says The Title Ain't Enough To Leave Home For</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LINCOLN, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A retired Australian sheep shearer who
inherited the title of Earl of Lincoln toured his namesake city
Wednesday, but even the prospect of sitting in the House of Lords
wasn't enough to make him stay.
   ``It's a splendid place, but we will be going back to
Australia,'' Edward Fiennes-Clinton, 75, said after he and his wife
Linda, the new Countess of Lincoln, visited Lincoln's castle,
cathedral and prosperous shopping malls.
   Fiennes-Clinton, who also worked as a gold miner and milk
deliveryman, said they decided to return home Thursday after
discovering there is no ancestral home to go with the title _ only
a seat in the hereditary House of Lords.
   ``This won't change our lives. We are still the same people and
I hope it's not going to change me at all,'' said the earl, who
calls his wife ``Mum.''
   He was telephoned in January at his retirement village in
Bunbury near Perth, Australia, and asked to call the College of
Arms in London.
   ``I had no idea what it was all about but I spoke to a man who
said he would be the first to congratulate me,'' said the 18th Earl
of Lincoln.
   ``I knew the title was in the family, but there are so many
different branches it never occurred to me that I might inherit it.
It is an old and honorable title and I would like to carry it on in
the few years left to me.'' Fiennes-Clinton inherited the
16th-century title on Christmas Day upon the death in England of a
remote kinsman, the 10th Duke of Newcastle and Earl of Lincoln. The
family had fallen on hard times, and the duke was chiefly known as
a collector of butterflies and moths.
   The old family seat, Clumber in Nottinghamshire, was pulled down
as long ago as 1938, and its 3,800-acre park is now owned by the
National Trust, which cares for historic homes.
   As the duke was unmarried, the dukedom became extinct, but the
lesser title of the Lincoln earldom passed to the Australian, whose
forebears had emigrated.
   The earl said he gave up full-time work 13 years ago and does
not have the resources or desire to move to England. The only cash
benefit available to him would be a maximum payment of 57 pounds
($97) daily if he attended the House of Lords and had to stay in
London overnight.
   ``We had some very nice letters from the city council assuring
us of a warm welcome if we ever visited Lincoln, so we came over to
see it and to look into this title business,'' the earl said.
   The earl's only previous visit to Britain was in 1977 for the
silver jubilee to mark Queen Elizabeth II's 25 years on the throne.
He never thought of visiting Lincoln at that time.
   ``I grew up in the depression in Australia and there was no dole
(welfare). My first job was as a butcher, earning 10 shillings ($2)
a week. We used to kill out in the paddock and hang up the carcass
in a tree,'' the earl said.
   He said he never found a crock of gold in his prospecting but
before he retired, he was running the water supply for a large part
of the country.
   The earl said, ``I was a widower when we were married and Mum
was a widow. I have been lucky both times.'' He said he would like
to take up his House of Lords seat, but there was little prospect
of it.
   The College of Arms said it could be five or six months before
the necessary research was completed. The cost of confirming the
title to make it legal and securing recognition by the queen could
be $8,500.
   ``Mum and I are registered in the House of Lords, but it is not
all legal until the research has been done,'' the earl said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890412-0144 </DOCNO>
