<FILEID>AP-NR-04-12-89 2131EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-OrphanDiseases     04-12 0385</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Orphan Diseases,390</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Office Urged</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A congressional commission on Wednesday
recommended a permanent office in the federal health department to
coordinate fights against so-called orphan diseases that afflict an
estimated 20 million Americans.
   Orphan diseases are relatively rare ailments that, by
definition, affect no more than 200,000 people.
   But because there are so many separate diseases, the total
number of people suffering from them is larger than from many
better-known ailments.
   Some diseases that qualify for orphan status are fairly
well-known themselves _ such as autism, multiple schlerosis and
Tay-Sachs diseases.
   Some, such as cholera, are common in the Third World, but rare
in the United States.
   Still others are obscure, such as Wilson's disease, a hereditary
illness that causes liver and brain damage.
   The final report of the National Commission on Orphan Diseases,
established by Congress in 1985, called for creation of a Central
Office of Orphan and Rare Diseases _ to be known as COORD _ within
the Department of Health and Human Services.
   It would work to:
   _Increase financing for biomedical research, training,
fellowships and clinical research centers.
   _Provide access to affordable health care for all American and
eliminate health insurance restrictions on pre-existing conditions.
   _Speed the government approval process for medications designed
to help sufferers of rare diseases.
   _Create a centralized information datebase on rare diseases.
   ``Research is critical, and we must make it clear to doctors and
investigators that the tratment of rare diseases is a national
priority,'' said Dr. Jess G. Thoene, chairman of the commission.
   He was joined at a news conference by Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah.,
and Rep. Henry A. Waxman, D-Calif., main backers of the legislation
that created the commission.
   Both also were instrumental in passage of th Orphan Drug Act, a
companion law that provides tax breaks for drug companies who make
research investments to develop drugs for such a small patient base
there is not a large enough market to justify the effort otherwise.
   Hatch said the success of the act has been ``staggering'' and
``has accomplished mroe than Congress ever expected it to.''
   Waxman said more than 260 drugs have been developed for rare
diseases since the Orphan Drug Act took effect, compared to less
than a dozen prior to the legislation.
</TEXT>
