<DOCNO> AP890412-0148 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-12-89 2156EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-ElectricitySupply     04-12 0350</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Electricity Supply,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Analysts Foresee Brownouts In Northeast This Summer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The New England states are likely this summer
to face a repeat of last year's temporary electricity shortages,
and the squeeze may be a prelude to more widespread ``brownouts''
in the 1990s, energy analysts said Wednesday.
   ``What happens in the Northeast will be a harbinger for the rest
of the country,'' said Leonard J. Kujawa, an Arthur Andersen &amp; Co.
analyst who helped direct a study on electric power trends in the
United States.
   Although electricity supplies for the peak use periods of summer
are tightest in New England, the power outlook for the nation as a
whole is growing more uncertain, said Daniel Yergin, president of
Cambridge Energy Research Associates and a partner in the study.
   The central problem is that U.S. electricity demand has grown
more rapidly than expected since 1985, while utilities have chosen
not to add to their generating capacity, Kujawa and Yergin told a
news conference on the results of their study.
   The key question, they said, is who will build the generating
capacity that will be needed in the 1990s. The answer is uncertain
because utilities are wary of the financial risks involved in major
new additions to plant capacity, while smaller power producers face
an array of regulatory and other obstacles, they said.
   In the Northeast, utilities in recent years have been forced to
import power from the mid-Atlantic. Last summer the problem was
compounded by record heat. In the Boston area, several thousand
customers lost power for a weekend because of overheated
transmission cables, and in New York City about 10,000 customers
lost power for a day.
   Other parts of the country have excess generating capacity, but
if demand for electricity continues growing at the pace of recent
years, constraints on supply could be felt in many areas, the
analysts said.
   Environmental and regulatory issues also may compound the
problem, they said.
   ``What is missing is an overall framework for balancing needs
for new generating capacity with environmental concerns and the
questions about who will pay,'' said Yergin.
</TEXT>
