<FIRST>r a AM-HelicopterCrash     04-12 0234</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Helicopter Crash,0239</SECOND>
<HEAD>2 State Police Officers Die In Helicopter Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>YORK, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A helicopter hit power lines Wednesday and
crashed into the Susquehanna River, killing two state police
officers who were searching for a suicide victim, authorities and
witnesses said.
   Scuba divers found the bodies of a state police corporal and a
trooper in the wreckage of the five-passenger Bell Jet Ranger
helicopter, police said. Their names were not immediately released.
   A witness, Hazel Keller, said she saw the crash from the York
County side of the river several miles north of the Maryland border.
   ``It hit a wire that crosses the river then it exploded and fell
into the water,'' said Mrs. Keller. ``It broke up in pieces and
pieces were floating down the river. We were all looking to see if
there were any bodies. We didn't see any bodies, just the debris.''
   State police spokesman Tom Lyon said the helicopter was being
used to search for the body of a suicide victim who reportedly
jumped from a bridge in the area several days earlier.
   Lyon said it was the first crash of a state police helicopter
since 1974. One trooper was killed in the 1974 crash; the cause of
which was never determined.
   There was no hint of any factors that may have contributed to
Wednesday's crash, which occurred about 9:45 a.m. in clear and calm
weather.
