<FIRST>u a AM-Kilroy'sHometown     04-12 0618</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Kilroy's Hometown,0635</SECOND>
<HEAD>Friends Shocked Over Mark Kilroy's Grisly Death In Mexico</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Satanic Slayings Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto HT-3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURA TOLLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA FE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A ceremony planned to revive hope for
Mark Kilroy's safe return became a memorial service Wednesday, a
day after his body was discovered in a Mexican grave dug by a
voodoo cult of drug smugglers.
   ``I'm still kind of shocked about the whole thing,'' said Bill
Huddleston, 21. ``I'm feeling a lot of different things _ anger,
sadness.''
   Huddleston, Bradley Moore, 20, and Brent Martin, 20, were
walking with Kilroy down a busy street in Matamoros, Mexico, the
night the 21-year-old was abducted. Kilroy's body and 11 others
were discovered Tuesday buried on a ranch south of the Mexican
border.
   Police said the victims were killed by drug smugglers seeking
demonic protection against police.
   Many Santa Fe residents who had worked to publicize Kilroy's
disappearance in an effort to find him gathered Wednesday to mourn
the University of Texas pre-med student's death.
   ``We come today to pray for Mark Kilroy,'' the Rev. John DeForke
said at a brief ceremony held outside Our Lady of Lourdes Catholic
Church, the Kilroy family's church. ``We come to pray for those
other wonderful people who died so violently.''
   About 150 children from the church school pinned yellow ribbons
around two trees outside the church in remembrance of Kilroy.
   ``I can't imagine anything worse happening,'' said Susan
Kuebler, a friend of the family.
   After the church ceremony, the three friends with Kilroy the
night he was taken said they wished now they had stayed at a party
they were at instead of going drinking at a Mexican bar.
   ``We should have never gone over (the border),'' said Huddleston.
   The four attended different colleges but are from Santa Fe, a
small, quiet community about 30 miles south of Houston. They all
had gone to the beach in southern Texas for spring break and had
ventured across the Mexican border for a late-night outing.
   They said Kilroy left the group after a stranger beckoned to him
on the crowded Matamoros street in the early hours of March 14. But
they said Wednesday they still can't recall the precise moment
when, or exact spot where, Kilroy disappeared.
   Under hypnosis, Huddleston said he and Kilroy passed a man
wearing a blue plaid shirt who motioned to Kilroy and called out.
According to a friend of the Kilroy family, Sheila Hughes,
Huddleston said under hypnosis that he went to a nearby bathroom
and Kilroy was gone when he returned.
   The three said they did not recognize any of the suspects in
pictures released by authorities Tuesday and Wednesday.
   The three expressed hope that Kilroy's murderers would be
prosecuted and punished. ``I think they deserve to get what he
got,'' Huddleston said.
   Kilroy lived for about 12 hours after his abduction and was
slain with a machete, authorities said. Suspects in custody have
confessed to removing Kilroy's brain and spine and chopping off his
legs, said Cameron County Sheriff Alex Perez.
   Kilroy's friends at the university in Austin said his ambition
to go to medical school drove him.
   ``School came first to him and he knew how to draw that line,''
said Frank J. Padula, Kilroy's neighbor and a senior history major.
``He was just an average, typical incoming kid. He was nervous, he
wanted to meet some girls, but he knew he had school work to do.''
   ``He was very intelligent, a super-smart guy,'' said Tammy
Shead, a UT psychology junior who attended high school with Kilroy.
``In high school I remember him winning all kinds of math and
science awards. I know he was confident about school.''
</TEXT>
