<FIRST>r a AM-People-Perelman     04-12 0250</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People-Perelman,0257</SECOND>
<HEAD>Financier Buys Palm Beach Home With $9 Million Cash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PALM BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Billionaire Ronald Perelman, a Wall
Street financier and chairman of the Revlon Corp., bought a Palm
Beach mansion for $9 million _ cash.
   The 2.3-acre estate was owned by D. Mead Johnson, a former
pharmaceutical company executive who has lived there for 20 years.
   Johnson said Perelman didn't need a mortgage but paid for the
house and grounds outright. Papers were expected to be filed in a
few days, The Palm Beach Post reported Wednesday.
   ``I had been contemplating it for some time,'' Johnson said. ``I
would never have sold the place. (But) I don't want the
responsibility of maintaining it, and I want a smaller place.''
   The 8,000-square-foot home, built 20 years ago, features about
200 feet of beach, a pool, a 2,700-square-foot guest home and a
2,700-square-foot garage apartment.
   Perelman is one of America's most active corporate raiders and
in the past 10 years has parlayed a $1.9 million stake in a small
jewelry distributorship into a $4.8 billion empire.
   With the help of Drexel Burnham Lambert junk-bond wizard Michael
Milken, Perelman has purchased a collection of companies that
include Technicolor, a film processor; Video Corp. of America, a
manufacturer of video cassettes; Consolidated Cigar; and Pantry
Pride, a troubled supermarket chain.
   Two years ago, financier Nelson Peltz paid $18 million for the
mansion Montsorrel in Palm Beach's most expensive purchase. The
Perelman home is a few houses north of Montsorrel.
</TEXT>
