<FIRST>u i AM-AuschwitzConvent     04-12 0371</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Auschwitz Convent,0384</SECOND>
<HEAD>Catholics, Jews Tussle About Convent At Auschwitz</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Roman Catholic newspaper Wednesday
criticized Jewish demands to relocate a Carmelite convent away from
the former Auschwitz concentration camp.
   The Roman Catholic hierarchy has agreed to move the convent, but
its failure to meet a promised Feb. 22 deadline has provoked an
outcry from Jewish organizations.
   The newspaper Slowo Powszechne published an open letter from
1,375 people from Oswiecim ``protesting the pressure on the nuns to
leave the building they occupy.'' Oswiecim is the Polish name for
the city the Germans called Auschwitz.
   The newspaper does not represent the Catholic Church. It is
owned by a Catholic pro-government organization called PAX.
   Jews want the convent moved because Auschwitz, now a museum,
holds special significance for them. About 2.8 million of the 6
million Jews killed in the Nazi holocaust died at Auschwitz'
factory-like gas chambers and crematoria and those of Birkenau, a
larger death camp a mile away that shared the same Nazi
administration. Victims came from throughout Europe.
   Ernst Ludwig Ehrlich, European Director of B'nai B'rith, said
Jewish relations with the Catholic Church will ``remain frozen''
until the convent is moved.
   In a telephone interview from his home in Geneva, Ehrlich cited
``resistance by the Catholic rank and file and others in all of
Poland.''
   He said he doubts Polish assurances that a start will be made
soon to build a new home for the convent's 14 nuns.
   Slowo Powszechne questioned any decision to move the convent, in
a former theater used as a warehouse by the Nazis and located a few
yards outside the camp's barbed wire fence.
   ``In the Auschwitz camp, it was mainly non-Jews who were
murdered, above all Polish and POWs of other nationalities, and the
extermination of Jews was being conducted in Birkenau,'' the paper
said in a March 31 article.
   ``Therefore it is hard to understand why people of a different
nationality and citizenship declare themselves so fiercely against
a handful of nuns, living in a Polish city, on Polish soil, next to
one of the biggest sites of martyrdom of Poles,'' the article said.
   More than 4 million people were put to death at the
Auschwitz-Birkenau complex.
</TEXT>
