<DOCNO> AP890412-0155 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-12-89 2158EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-WorldGrain     04-12 0413</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-World Grain,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>EEC Continuing to Push Grain Exports: USDA</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The European Economic Community continues to
push grain exports aggressively, with shipments expected to be at a
record level this year, the Agriculture Department said Wednesday.
   An analysis by the department's Foreign Agricultural Service
said EEC exports of wheat and coarse grains such as barley and corn
are expected to total 33.3 million metric tons in 1988-89, up 39
percent from 23.9 million tons last year.
   International trade years begin on July 1 for wheat and Oct. 1
for coarse grains. A metric ton is about 2,205 pounds and is equal
to 36.7 bushels of wheat or soybeans, or 39.5 bushels of corn.
   Wheat exports by the EEC are at a record 21 million tons, up
from 15.3 million in 1987-88.
   But the coarse grains, mostly barley, also have grown and are
forecast at 12.3 million tons against only 8.6 million tons last
year.
   ``Over the past seven years, subsidized barley exports by the
EEC have jumped by 150 percent,'' the report said. ``While EEC
barley exports comprised less than 30 percent of world barley trade
as recently as the early 1980s, their share is now almost 60
percent, a growth in exports that has come at least partially at
the expense of U.S. coarse grain market share.''
   The United States, the world's leading grain exporter, was
forecast to have total wheat and coarse grain shipments of 103.4
million tons in the current trade year, up from 96.9 million tons
in 1987-88, a 7 percent increase.
   Part of the growth reflects recent large corn sales to the
Soviet Union and subsidized wheat sales to China.
   The Soviet Union is expected to import 37.5 million tons of
wheat and coarse grains from all sources this year, up 2 million
tons from the March forecast and 16 percent more than the 32.2
million tons imported in 1987-88. It also would be the most wheat
and coarse grains imported by the Soviets since 55.4 million tons
were bought in 1984-85.
   According to other USDA figures, the Soviets have bought about
17 million tons of U.S. wheat and corn for delivery in the year
that began Oct. 1, all but 4 million tons of it corn.
   China has bought about 8.5 million tons of U.S. wheat for
delivery this year, about half of the 16.5 million tons China is
expected to import from all sources in 1988-89.
</TEXT>
