<FILEID>AP-NR-04-12-89 2158EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-PigletPlague     04-12 0343</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Piglet Plague,0357</SECOND>
<UNK>Farmers Fighting Mysterious Swine Illness</UNK>
<DATELINE>WABASH, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mysterious disease is striking infant pigs
on some Indiana farms and in some cases 100 percent of the
infected, weakened litters have died.
   Eight hog operations in Wabash County have been hit by the
disease, said farmer Dean Haupert, whose farm was stricken.
   ``We probably lost 30 litters,'' Haupert said. ``We're spending
a couple of thousand (dollars) a week on medication.''
   Purdue University scientists said other isolated cases have been
recorded across the state.
   ``At this stage no one knows exactly what the disease is,'' said
Kenneth B. Meyer, professor of veterinary adult education at Purdue.
   The illness strikes sows with a loss of appetite during the
latter part of their 113-day gestation period. Some farrows, or
litters, are stillborn. The survivors have weakened heart membranes
and cardiac muscles and a short life expectancy.
   In some hog operations, 100 percent of the weakened litters have
died.
   Farmers and veterinarians first identified the disease about
seven weeks ago, Haupert said.
   Purdue researchers are studying victims of the disease, hoping
to find links to similar illnesses that damaged hog populations in
North Carolina and Minnesota last year.
   ``Minnesota people called it the Plague of '88,'' said Kerry
Keffaber, a veterinarian with the Swine Health Center in Roann.
   Keffaber says infected herds in Wabash County have 150 to 600
sows each, producing 3,000 to 12,000 piglets each year.
   ``It isn't killing big hogs,'' said Lewis J. Runnels, veterinary
diagnostician for swine diseases at Purdue.
   The disease is similar to other illnesses that infect swine
herds, such as Aujesky's disease, more commonly known as
pseudorabies.
   The disease should not affect entire herds.
   ``It's not going to be a wipe-out disease,'' Meyer said.
   Medication has done little to help his infected sows and
piglets, Haupert said.
   Meyer suggested that hog producers with healthy swine near
infected herds should isolate their animals. Pets should not be
allowed to roam near an area where the disease has been prevalent
and then return to a healthy herd.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
