<FILEID>AP-NR-04-12-89 2026EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r p AM-LAMayor     04-12 0566</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-LA Mayor,0580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bradley Squeaks Through To Win Fifth Term</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JUDY FARAH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Tom Bradley said Wednesday he couldn't
explain the narrow margin by which he won an unprecedented fifth
term of the nation's second-largest city.
   ``You can speculate. I've won some close ones and lost some
close ones. Winning is better. I am satisfied with the election,''
he said at a news conference.
   Pollsters had predicted the 71-year-old ex-cop and son of a
sharecropper would coast to victory. Instead, Bradley found himself
at one point Tuesday night barely maintaining the 50 percent needed
to avoid a runoff in June.
   ``Well, my friends. I've learned something in this election ...
never take anything for granted,'' he told supporters in his 1 a.m.
victory speech.
   ``I made a mistake during the campaign. I didn't make the kind
of vigorous all-out effort I could have or should have,'' Bradley
said. ``During the next four years, I will be a vigorous all-out
mayor.''
   A lackluster campaign and apparent voter apathy kept the turnout
at 17 percent, the lowest in decades, according to the City Clerk's
Office. Just 328,194 of the city's 1.9 million registered voters
cast ballots.
   Unofficial results showed Bradley with 156,724 votes, or 52
percent, to freshman Councilman Nate Holden's 84,376 votes, or
27.99 percent. Former county Supervisor Baxter Ward had 44,816
votes, or 15 percent. They were among 10 candidates.
   ``A little more time and more money, there could have been a
difference,'' said Holden, who gathered only $150,000 for his
campaign war chest compared to Bradley's $2 million.
   Holden told reporters Wednesday he would continue his campaign
to battle crime, drugs, traffic congestion and overdevelopment.
``The people are saying they are dissatisfied with the way this
city has been managed,'' he said.
   He said the outcome of the election conveyed two statements from
voters: ``The statement was that they are unhappy with the status
quo and that they want change. And another statement was that only
20 percent of the people felt enough confidence in this election
and their government to go on and continue to support it.
   ``The people are turned off with the process and I know that
more now than ever. And that is why they stayed at home.''
   Bradley earned the nickname ``Teflon mayor'' during the campaign
because political polls showed the city's 3 million residents held
him blameless for such things as rising crime, gang violence,
pollution and traffic congestion. Holden said his upstart campaign
showed that Bradley wasn't as invincible as he thought.
   The mayor drew his fiercest criticism in years just before the
election when the city attorney's office announced an ethics
investigation of him after learning the mayor performed consulting
work with Far East National Bank, which did business with the city.
Bradley returned the $18,000 he was paid by the bank and called the
charges politically motivated.
   In the Los Angeles Police Department, Bradley rose to the rank
of lieutenant before leaving police work for politics and election
to the City Council.
   Bradley, mayor since 1973, lost his first bid for the job in
1969 to incumbent Sam Yorty. He has twice run unsuccessfully for
governor, losing to Republican George Deukmejian in 1982 and 1986.
   Other mayoral candidates included Raul Reyes, who got 1.2
percent of the vote. The other candidates all received less than 1
percent.
</TEXT>
