<FIRST>r w AM-EmbassySpending     04-12 0323</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Embassy Spending,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Amendment Would Limit Spending On Multi-Room Houses</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHERINE RIZZO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some employees of American embassies and
consulates live too well at taxpayer expense, Rep. John Kasich,
R-Ohio, said Wednesday after convincing the House to limit luxury
overseas accomodations.
   On a voice vote, the House added to a State Department budget
bill Kasich's proposal to provide better-than-average rental houses
to fewer foreign service workers.
   A 1987 report by the State Department's inspector general
indicated the perk of plush housing had been extended beyond its
intended purpose of giving high-ranking officials appropriate homes
in which to entertain official guests.
   According to Kasich's office, the inspector general report and a
subsequent General Accounting Office inquiry discovered examples of
apparent abuse of the housing perk:
   _In Brussels, two childless couples were given six-bedroom homes.
   _In Manila, a couple with one child lived in a five-bedroom home.
   _In Hong Kong, every family routinely had rented homes with an
extra bedroom.
   A cross-check of 202 employees given the extra housing privelege
showed 30 of them spent no money for official entertaining,
Kasich's office said.
   The inspector general's report had indicated the perk of
upgraded housing, excluding the cost of maintaining homes for
ambassadors and deputy ambassadors, cost the government an average
$48,000 per embassy.
   In an interview in his Washington office, Kasich said pressure
from the State Department to water down his proposal came within 30
minutes of his distributing courtesy copies to colleagues.
   Even if the amendment doesn't survive the rest of the
legislative procedure _ it could be axed in the Senate or in a
conference committee _ ``the State Department has the message,'' he
said. ``You've got to put the bright light on them sometimes.''
   The amendment is attached to a measure authorizing $4.8 billion
in fiscal 1990 and $4.96 billion in 1991 for the State Department,
the U.S. Information Agency and other federal international
agencies.
</TEXT>
