<DOCNO> AP890412-0162 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-12-89 1837EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-BushQuayle-Taxes     04-12 0838</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush Quayle-Taxes,880</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>President Gets Tax Refund; Quayle Has Sizeable Honoraria</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush reported that he earned
$155,662 last year from business holdings kept in a blind trust, a
sum well above his $115,000 vice presidential salary.
   In the federal tax form that Bush filed jointly with his wife,
Barbara, the pair reported an adjusted gross income of $287,171.
   That was based on Bush's $155,662 in interest-and-dividend
earnings through partnerships and other interests, masked by the
blind trust, and his government salary. Also included was $7,147 in
other interest along with $12,362 in income from other sources,
primarily profits that Bush made from his partnership in a firm
that leased a liquefied natural gas transportation barge in
Louisiana.
   The Bushes paid taxes equivalent to 21.6 percent of their total
income, which was nearly $30,000 below the $308,396 income of 1987.
   The government withheld $29,480 from Bush's income last year,
and he made $65,404 in quarterly payments based on assuming what
his tax liability would be.
   When his 1988 federal tax liability of $62,106 was deducted from
the $94,884 total in money withheld or prepaid, Bush had overpaid
by $32,778. White House press secretary Marlin Fitzwater said he
applied $15,000 to next year's tax liability and pocketed $17,778.
   Meanwhile, the office of Vice President Dan Quayle released the
tax forms filed jointly by Quayle and his wife, Marilyn.
   The Quayles, who records show hold assets worth more than $1.4
million, reported an adjusted gross income of $156,546 last year,
the bulk of that coming from Quayle's $89,500 Senate salary.
   But the form also showed that Quayle, while a U.S. senator from
Indiana, earned $52,797 in speaking honoraria last year _ $16,997
above the maximum senators may accept.
   Quayle listed charitable contributions totaling $17,304, or just
a little above the $16,997 in speaking fees that he could not keep
for himself.
   The vice president's press secretary, Dave Beckwith, said Quayle
had written off the excess speaker's fees in an appropriate fashion.
   ``He earned more in honoraria than he's allowed to keep, so he
gave all the excess to charity,'' Beckwith said.
   The spokesman said Quayle gained no tax advantage by writing off
the extra speaking fees as charitable contributions, saying ``you
have (approximately) $17,000 more in income and $17,000 more in
deductions (to report), so it's a wash.''
   Quayle earned all his speaking fees before August, when the
Republican Party nominated him to be Bush's vice presidential
running mate.
   The balance of his $156,546 income came from interest, dividends
and capital gains relating to his family's Central Newspapers, Inc.
Quayle also made $2,000 as a director of Central Newspapers _ a
position he would have to relinquish under ethics legislation that
Bush proposed to Congress Thursday.
   Estimates on Bush's net worth have varied substantially,
although records show that the president, who made the bulk of his
money as an oil entrepreneur in Texas, has assets worth well over
$2 million.
   White House press secretary Marlin Fitzwater said, ``I would
say, however, that reports of his wealth are vastly over-estimated.
Most of his net worth is in the Kennebunkport (Maine) estate.''
   In his tax return, Bush reported a net capital gains loss,
through his blind trust transactions, of $3,480. The nature of the
loss was not divulged.
   After availing himself of the standard $3,000 deduction allowed
by law for such losses, Bush had a $458 loss which was carried over
to next year's capital gains losses _ a procedure permitted by the
U.S. Tax Code.
   Bush paid only $3,328 in state and local income taxes, with most
of that going to Louisiana in payment of taxes based on the income
generated by his partnership in the barge-leasing leasing
enterprise. The president's legal home address is in Houston, and
Texas has no state income tax. He did pay some taxes to other
states, Fitzwater said, but that, too, is sheltered from disclosure
by the blind trust.
   Bush also paid $19,034 in real estate taxes, with the bulk of
that involving the Walker's Point estate at Kennebunkport and the
remainder involving taxes paid on a vacant lot he owns in Houston.
   And he paid $277 in miscellaneous personal property fees on a
pickup truck, a Bronco vehicle and a boat he has in Maine.
   The Bushes donated $12,468 to charity, including contributions
to a host of church and civic organizations and donations to
foundations established in the memory of Edward Byrne, a New York
City policeman killed in the line of duty, and in honor of the late
Margaret Fitzgerald Grogan, the wife of presidential aide Gregg
Petersmeyer, who died of cancer.
   Bush also reported $9,998 in business-related expenses, of which
$9,712 was reimbursed by the government. The vice president is
given a $10,000 allowance for such expenses. But $286 of Bush's
claimed expenses were disallowed, and so he was therefore able to
deduct this from his tax liability.
   Fitzwater said he did know what Bush expense submissions were
rejected.
</TEXT>
