<FILEID>AP-NR-04-12-89 1725EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Poland-Katyn     04-12 0418</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Katyn,0437</SECOND>
<HEAD>Urns From Massacre Site Displayed At Army Museum</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DRUSILLA MENAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two urns holding soil from the Katyn
graves of 4,500 Polish officers were displayed at the army museum
Wednesday, indicating official Poland has come to terms with the
crime widely attributed to the Soviets.
   A trickle of mourners, some in tears, others carrying flowers,
visited the two small black containers, which Poles say have come
to symbolize Soviet crimes against their country.
   ``It is important historically that these facts are revealed,''
said a widow who stood before the memorial with her daughter.
   The officers, the cream of Polish society called up from the
reserves in World War II, were shot in the back of head and dumped
in mass graves in Katyn, near the Soviet city of Smolensk.
   For years, Poland's communist government stuck by the Soviet
accounting of events whereby the Nazis committed the murders in
1941 after invading the Soviet Union.
   But most historians believe the Soviet secret police carried out
the massacre in 1940, when the Soviet Union and Nazi Germany were
still allied. And in recent months, the official Polish position
has changed.
   In 1987, Polish leader Gen. Wojciech Jaruzelski and Soviet
leader Mikhail Gorbachev agreed to appoint a joint commission to
study ``blank spots'' in the two countries' histories.
   Polish members of the commission issued tentative conclusions,
based on what officials called circumstantial evidence, pointing to
Soviet responsiblity. Soviet members reportedly are still studying
the case.
   The government press has written about Katyn, a subject that had
been forbidden but not forgotten by Poles.
   The urns were brought from Katyn on April 5 by a delegation of
victims' families. They were placed first at a garrison church in
Warsaw where a Mass was celebrated by army chaplains.
   On Wednesday, the urns were moved to the army museum, where they
were placed on a pedestal bearing the words ``Soil from the Katyn
graves'' and draped with a long banner in Poland's red and white
colors.
   Overhead are hung embroidered flags from army units mustered in
pre-communist Poland before World War II. Officers stand at
attention on either side.
   In ceremonies scheduled for Tuesday, one urn will be placed on
the Tomb of the Unknown Soldier and another on a monument to the
Katyn victims at Warsaw's Powazki cemetery.
   The wording on the monument, which previously blamed ``Hitlerite
fascists,'' is being changed, but the government has not said what
the new phrasing will be.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890412-0165 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-12-89 2200EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-BRF--CongressmanRobbed     04-12 0087</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Congressman Robbed,90</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mass. Representatiave, Aide Robbed on Capitol Hill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Massachusetts congressman and a House staff
member were robbed by an armed man near the Supreme Court, police
reported Wednesday.
   Rep. Chester Atkins, D-Mass., and Richard J. Phelan, special
counsel for the House ethics committee, were approached late
Tuesday by a man armed with a revolver who demanded their wallets,
U.S. Capitol police said. After the men complied, the robber fled
on foot.
   No injuries were reported. No arrests have been made.
