<FIRST>u i AM-HospitalKillings 1stLd-Writethru a0652 04-12 0769</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hospital Killings, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0652,0791</SECOND>
<HEAD>Doctor Suspended Over `Mercy Killings' At Austrian Hospital</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 18 grafs to UPDATE with comment from Pesendorfer,
mayor. Pick up 13th pvs, `Alois Stacher...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   City authorities on Wednesday suspended
the head of a hospital department where four nursing aides
confessed to at least 49 ``mercy killings,'' and they ordered the
exhumation of bodies of several presumed victims.
   Dr. Franz Pesendorfer's suspension follows mounting criticism of
his reported refusal to cooperate with police during an
investigation last year to find evidence of mass killings at
Vienna's Lainz hospital.
   Four assistant nurses arrested since Friday have confessed to
killing at least 49 elderly patients with overdoses of medicine or
by forcing water into their lungs. Most victims were in their 80s.
   Newspaper reports say the lives of 22 of the 49 victims could
have been saved if Pesendorfer had cooperated last year, when
senior investigator Max Edelbacher said police met ``a wall of
silence'' at the hospital.
   Pesendorfer defended his conduct on a national television
discussion Wednesday evening.
   Pesendorfer said he was told last April by a female doctor that
another doctor, Dr. Waschnig, learned in a wine bar of rumors that
patients were being ``put to rest'' by assistant nurses.
   Pesendorfer said he alerted doctors and senior nurses to the
rumor, and ordered an immediate blood test on an 84-year-old woman
who died unexpectedly days later.
   The blood test results prompted him to advise city medical
officials and the hospital director, and police were called,
Pesendorfer said.
   A later forensic test on the 84-year-old woman turned up nothing
suspicious, officials have said.
   Pesendorfer said Dr. Waschnig's name was mentioned in the
presence of police, although he was not identified as the source of
the rumor. A police report says Pesendorfer refused to give
investigators the name of the doctor who alerted him to the
possible killings.
   Austria's largest daily newspaper, Neue Kronen Zeitung, asserted
that if Pesendorfer and the second doctor ``had not kept quiet, it
would fairly certainly have been possible to stop the series of
murders a year ago.''
   ``As it was, however, the sadistic nurses could kill another 22
people,'' the newspaper said.
   Police have not confirmed media reports that 22 people were
killed in the past year.
   The killings reportedly began in 1983 at Lainz hospital's
Pavilion Five, dubbed ``the Death Pavilion'' by Neue Kronen Zeitung.
   On Wednesday, patients sat in stairwells, smoking cigarettes and
whispering about Pesendorfer's suspension, but they refused to talk
to reporters. So did Pesendorfer and hospital officials.
   The hospital refused to describe the function of the First
Medical Department, which Pesendorfer ran. However, it appears to
practice general medicine on people suffering ailments related to
old age.
   Mayor Helmut Zilk said he suspended Pesendorfer ``on the grounds
of the results to date of the police investigations.'' He declined
further comment.
   In a statement read on the television discussion program, Zilk
added the suspension was intended not as a judgement of Pesendorfer
but to facilitate further inquiries and encourage his staff to
speak out.
   Alois Stacher, chief of the city's health department, said the
suspension was linked to ``lingering lack of clarity'' over the
investigation.
   Pesendorfer consistently has defended his role and the conduct
of officials in his department at Lainz, Vienna's fourth-largest
hospital, since first word of the killings on Friday.
   Assistant nurses Maria Gruber, 25, Irene Leidorf, 37, and
Waltraud Wagner, 30, were detained Friday. Another assistant nurse,
Stephanie Mayer, 50, was detained Sunday after Ms. Ferrada-Avendano
went to police. She too was arrested after she admitted witnessing
one of the killings, Edelbacher said.
   Three other witnesses have come forward. Edelbacher said two say
they witnessed killings as patients in the hospital, while another
_ the daughter of a patient who has since died _ reported her
mother told her about killings at the hospital.
   The nursing aides have not been charged, but police say Ms.
Wagner alone has confessed to killing 39 patients.
   Her lawyer, Wilhelm Philipp, hinted it may be difficult for
police to get any murder charges to stick.
   He was quoted by Austria Press Agency as speaking of ``so-called
confessions'' to police and noting state prosecutors will have to
prove ``the murder really did happen'' because of his client's
actions.
   In an apparent attempt to get more evidence, city authorities
late Wednesday ordered the exhumation of the bodies of several
presumed victims. Officials declined to identify the bodies or say
how many will be exhumed.
   Pesendorfer is the first doctor or official suspended because of
the killings.
</TEXT>
