<FIRST>r w AM-Bennett-Budget     04-12 0500</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bennett-Budget,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bennett Asks For More Money, And More Freedom to Spend It</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   National drug policy director William J.
Bennett asked Congress on Wednesday for a $12 million budget in
1990, an $8.5 million increase over the current budget, and freedom
to allocate the money as he sees fit.
   ``Why this amount? Why this growth? Given the fact that the 1989
appropriation of $3.5 million was intended to cover our operations
for only a portion of the year, and given the substantial tasks
facing this office, I believe it will become apparent that the $12
million proposed for 1990 is a very reasonable request,'' Bennett
told the House Appropriations subcommittee on Treasury, Postal
Service and general government.
   ``What's more, I believe it is vital to the advancement of this
nation's drug control efforts,'' he said, adding that it would be
spent to provide for 64 jobs, 24 more positions than appeared in
the budget proposed by then-President Reagan in January.
   In addition, Bennett requested a change in the appropriation
language to remove the earmarking of $7 million for staff and $5
million for research to give him greater flexibility in how the
money is spent.
   ``It is not clear to me yet what the size of this office should
be, what the strategy should be,'' he told the panel, adding,
however, ``I intend to keep this office lean and mean. I do not
intend to build a bureaucracy.''
   Asked why he wanted to merge the funds, Bennett said, ``There's
a lot of research going on in the 30-odd agencies involved in these
areas.'' It's possible, he said, that his office would not need to
spend money for research but could use that money instead for
personnel.
   Although he was pressed repeatedly by panel members for specific
plans for various agencies and budgets, such as the Customs Service
and the Drug Enforcement Administration, Bennett declined to
provide details.
   ``I'm essentially ... listening now to what people tell me. ...
I'm getting people's perspectives'' on how to structure the
national drug control strategy, which by law he must provide 180
days from his swearing in March 13.
   Bennett said the strategy, which will include priorities and
financing requests, will be completed by Sept. 5.
   Meanwhile, District of Columbia Mayor Marion Barry Jr. said he
has a ``cordial'' relationship with Bennett, even though one of
Barry's top aides, and not the mayor himself, is handling the
district's involvement with Bennett's office.
   In releasing a multi-million dollar federal plan designed to
help the city curb its record murder rate, Bennett lashed out
Monday at Barry's government, and accused the city of letting the
drug problem grow ``out of control.''
   ``I don't want us to get sidetracked by any personalities or
debates,'' Barry said Wednesday after a meeting with other
Washington-area local government officials. ``The issue isn't
William Bennett and Marion Barry of the city government _ the issue
is the international trafficking of drugs.''
</TEXT>
