<FIRST>u i AM-NorthernIreland     04-12 0413</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Northern Ireland,0424</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bomb Kills One, Injures 40; Criticism from Sinn Fein</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A car bomb exploded next to a
police station Wednesday, killing a young Roman Catholic woman and
injuring 31 civilians and nine police officers, authorities said.
   The hospital where the victims were taken received four warnings
of a blast at the police station, but all came after the bomb
exploded in a stolen van parked next to the station in the coastal
town of Warrenpoint in County Down.
   Suspicion fell on the Irish Republican Army. The group did not
immediately claim responsibility for the attack.
   The outlawed IRA is fighting to unite the province, where
Protestants outnumber Catholics 3-to-2, with the Catholic Republic
of Ireland.
   Gerry Adams, president of the IRA's legal political wing, Sinn
Fein, has urged the IRA to be more careful in its attacks.
   On Wednesday, he said: ``We are against the killing of
civilians. Sinn Fein does not condone in the strongest possible
terms what happened at Warrenpoint this morning.''
   The Royal Ulster Constabulary said Joanne Reilly, 20, an office
worker at a hardware store next to the police station, died in the
explosion.
   Police said most of the injured were treated and released but
that five remained hospitalized at Daisy Hill Hospital in nearby
Newry. The hospital received the first bomb warning nine minutes
after the explosion, police said.
   Police said the blast ignited gas cylinders in the yard next to
the police station and touched off further explosions and a huge
fire. Windows up to a mile away were shattered, and the police
station and nearby buildings were heavily damaged, police said.
   Warrenpoint has a population of 6,500 and is less than a mile
from Northern Ireland's border with the Republic of Ireland.
   Seamus Mallon, deputy leader of the Social Democratic and Labor
Party, the mainstream Catholic party, said ``people who carry out
this sort of attack listen to nobody. They simply have a murderous
desire in their hearts to kill.''
   Warrenpoint Council Chairman Eugene Markey condemned the attack
as ``total madness.'' He said the town had just started to attract
tourists, ``and now this happens.''
   The IRA killed 18 British army soldiers in an ambush outside
Warrenpoint on Aug. 27, 1979. The same day, Lord Louis Mountbatten,
India's last viceroy and a cousin of Queen Elizabeth II, was killed
in an IRA bomb blast aboard his yacht off the coast of County Sligo
in the Republic of Ireland.
</TEXT>
