<FIRST>r a AM-CholesterolPoll     04-12 0222</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cholesterol Poll,0226</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cholesterol Poll Finds Jump in Awareness</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The number of Americans who know their
cholesterol level has nearly doubled in a year, and more than four
in 10 say they have changed their eating habits to cut their
cholesterol, a poll said Tuesday.
   Among 1,016 people age 18 or over polled by the Gallup
Organization in January, 31 percent said they knew their
cholesterol level. A year before, when Gallup asked the same
question, just 17 percent knew.
   That increase ``clearly indicates that people are getting the
message'' that cholesterol can contribute to heart disease, said
Dr. DeWitt S. Goodman, the head of an advisory board on cholesterol
for Voluntary Hospitals of America Inc., which commissioned the
survey.
   The survey, conducted Jan. 9-22 and released by the organization
Tuesday, found that about two-thirds of respondents said they had
taken a blood test to check their cholesterol level, and four in 10
said they had changed their diet or eating habits in the past two
years to reduce their cholesterol.
   The hospital group sponsors ``Countdown USA,'' at which about
450 of its member hospitals offer free cholesterol and blood
pressure tests. The event this year is April 26; more than 400,000
people took the tests last year.
   The poll had a 3-point margin of sampling error.
</TEXT>
