<FIRST>r w AM-FAA-Pilots     04-12 0266</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-FAA-Pilots,270</SECOND>
<HEAD>FAA Plans Action</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Aviation Administration said
Wednesday it plans enforcement action against more than 1,000
pilots who failed to report required information about alcohol or
drug-related convictions.
   The FAA said the pilots could have their medical certificates
revoked and their airman certificates suspended or revoked,
depending on the seriousness of the violations.
   The FAA said more than 6,000 names were obtained through
computer matches of FAA medical records and FBI criminal history
records and Florida state motor vehicle records.
   The search, the FAA said in a written statement, turned up ``a
significant number of airmen who appear to have falsified their
applications for airmen medical certification with regard to drug
convictions and drug or alcohol-related traffic convictions.''
   The FAA said that because of the large number of cases, the FAA
plans to focus its enforcement effort only on cases involving
convictions since Feb. 17, 1984, although it may take action in
severe older cases.
   The agency said it would also take action where necessary in
cases involving drug convictions but no falsification of
applications for FAA certificates.
   In a separate matter, the FAA proposed a new safety rule that
would increase the number of flight attendants that must be present
to supervise passenger boarding operations when an airliner is on
the ground.
   The proposal would mainly affect mid-size airline aircraft with
101 to 150 seats, and in many cases would require two attendants to
remain on board instead of one.
   The FAA said it was publishing the proposed rule in the Federal
Register this week and soliciting comment.
</TEXT>
