<FIRST>u i AM-WarsawPact     04-12 0249</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Warsaw Pact,0255</SECOND>
<HEAD>Warsaw Pact Unveils Detailed Proposal On Short-Range Missile Talks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Warsaw Pact on Wednesday unveiled a detailed
proposal to NATO for starting negotiations to eliminate short-range
nuclear weapons in Europe in a move that could widen differences
within the Western alliance.
   The North Atlantic Treaty Organization already has rejected
previous Soviet pressure to begin talks aimed at reducing or
eliminating the tactical nuclear weapons, which have a range of
less than 310 miles.
   But a growing number of people in West Germany, a key NATO
country, have expressed doubt the short-range weapons are still
needed because of a perceived reduction of the East bloc threat.
   Warsaw Pact foreign ministers, ending a two-day meeting in East
Berlin, issued a communique proposing ``separate negotiations in
the near future on tactical nuclear weapons in Europe.''
   The communique said ``preparations for the proposed
negotiations, its mandate and who should participate can be
discussed in special consultations,'' which it said the Warsaw Pact
countries are ready to begin immediately.
   Most of NATO's short-range nuclear weapons are based in West
Germany.
   The Warsaw Pact also said both sides should agree not to
modernize their short-range nuclear weapons. The Warsaw Pact has
previously denounced NATO's modernization plans, which also are
opposed by a growing number of West Germans.
   ``The member states of the Warsaw Pact are of the opinion that a
decision not to modernize tactical atomic weapons would create a
favorable atmosphere for such negotiations...'' the communique said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
