<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-OilSpill     04-12 0430</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Oil Spill,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bush Defends Oil Spill Decision</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush said Wednesday he still
believes the federal government should not have taken over the
Alaskan oil spill cleanup effort, although he conceded it could
have gotten involved earlier.
   Fielding questions after a speech to a convention of the
American Society of Newspaper Editors, Bush maintained the
administration moved ``more quickly and more boldly than it gets
credit for.''
   But at the same time, he said, ``Maybe I should accept some
criticism'' that he should have moved earlier than April 7 to step
up federal involvement in the environmental disaster off the coast
of Alaska.
   Bush said that he now believes the federal government ``is
properly involved'' in that effort and said ``we should not have
done what some are urging upon us _ federalizing that whole
cleanup.''
   Last Friday, Bush put Transportation Secretary Samuel Skinner in
charge of coordinating actions by federal agencies in connection
with cleaning up the spill from the Exxon Valdez in Prince William
Sound. He also ordered the Defense Department to make military
troops and equipment available to assist in the effort.
   Bush said that while he was pleased the federal government has
stepped up its involvement in the cleanup, ``I would also like to
see more volunteers involved.'' The president said he believes
liability laws should be eased to that volunteer groups won't be
kept from helping out because of fears by the government of
potentially ``outrageous liability claims.''
   ``We have moved forward on the cleanup,'' he said. ``The first
was containment, and now it's mainly in the cleanup phase, although
there still are some containment problems.''
   On other matters, Bush said:
   _He often invites reporters to private White House social
events, although he is not doing it to get friendlier coverage from
the White House press corps.
   Bush said he and first lady Barbara extend such invitations
``not to defuse the press _ treating them as human beings.''
   _He knows of ``no retaliatory action'' taken by his
administration because of the Senate defeat of former Sen. John
Tower as a nominee to be secretary of defense.
   Bush was asked if there any plans by the Republican Party to
retaliate against House Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas, who is under
investigation by a House panel for alleged ethics violations.
   ``I think it would be impossible to do, anyway,'' Bush said,
``and it would be wrong, and certainly I would condemn anyone in
our administration that had any hand in anything of that nature.''
</TEXT>
