<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-NATO     04-12 0373</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-NATO,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>NATO Leader Says Soviet Bloc Should Cut Weapons</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The secretary general of the North Atlantic
Treaty Organization challenged Warsaw Pact nations Wednesday to
begin reducing their short-range nuclear weapon strength if they
are interested in talks with the West on the subject.
   Manfred Woerner made the comment after meeting with President
Bush and advisers at the White House concerning NATO strategy,
East-West relations and preparations for the NATO summit May 29-30
in Brussels, Belgium, which Bush will attend.
   Warsaw Pact ministers meeting in East Berlin on Tuesday called
for negotiations with NATO on tactical short-range nuclear weapons.
   ``This is no news; they have repeatedly stated such
intentions,'' Woerner told reporters.
   ``I would call to your attention that they have 14 times more
short-range weapons than we have,'' he said. ``It would be a good
idea, if they are interested, to reduce and start to build down
their short-range nuclear weapons.''
   A White House statement said Bush and Woerner met for half an
hour. It said they discussed ``NATO summit preparations, the
continuing validity of NATO strategy and developments in the Soviet
Union and Eastern Europe.''
   ``The president emphasized the success of the alliance in
keeping the peace and promoting prosperity for 40 years, and his
desire that their May summit project a broad vision of the
alliance's future,'' the statement said.
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III, National Security Adviser
Brent Scowcroft and White House Chief of Staff John Sununu attended
the meeting.
   The suggestion in East Berlin came in a speech by Polish Foreign
Minister Tadeusz Olechowski, who said the Warsaw Pact ministers had
agreed that progress in the Vienna conventional arms talks last
month should be broadened to include ``the start of negotiations on
tactical nuclear weapons.''
   Woerner said he and Bush ``discussed a broad range of
disarmament questions including conventional arms.''
   ``The first part, of course, is to get the Soviets to agree to
our proposal, reduce, come down to lower levels and equal ceilings
and then of course, the president as much as NATO is interested to
consider further steps. But first, let us come and make a success
out of our proposal,'' he said.
</TEXT>
