<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-Firefighters     04-12 0212</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Firefighters,210</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Salutes Firefighters</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush paid tribute Wednesday night to
America's volunteer firefighters, saying they deserve a federal
government that ``understands and values'' their place in the
nation's communities.
   ``I was struck by the fact that 85 percent of our nation's fire
protection is supplied by volunteers,'' Bush said in a speech
prepared for delivery to a Fire Service Institute dinner.
   ``For more than 200 years, firefighters have been this nation's
neighbor _ in word and deed _ the backbone of America,'' the
president said. ``You have met local emergencies through volunteer
and paid fire and emergency service networks. And today, you meet
them still _ 3 million members strong.''
   Bush said he believes the federal government should support
volunteer firefighters and noted that he supports the National Fire
Academy ``retaining its prominence as a national training center.''
   ``Each year, more than 6,000 lives are lost in fires and over
$10 billion lost in property damage,'' he said. ``To combat such
tragedy, we must foster greater public awareness of fire problems
by supporting the federal fire safety programs.''
   Bush said that as part of that effort, the death benefit for
fallen fire fighters was raised from $50,000 to $100,000 in
legislation passed by Congress last year.
</TEXT>
