<FILEID>AP-NR-04-12-89 2312EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Hastings     04-12 0775</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hastings,780</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senators Cool as Hastings Attorney Pleads for Government Funds</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorneys for impeached Judge Alcee L.
Hastings pleaded Wednesday for up to $950,000 from the government
to finance his fight to stay on the bench but they encountered a
cool reception from senators.
   ``You're making an unprecedented request for compensation which,
just speaking for myself, I don't think you're going to have
available,'' Sen. Arlen Spector, R-Pa., told Hastings attorney
Terence J. Anderson.
   The House on Aug. 3 approved 413-3 articles of impeachment
accusing the 52-year-old District Court judge of conspiring to
obtain a bribe in 1981 and lying about it in 1983 before a jury
that eventually acquitted him.
   One impeachment article also accuses Hastings, the first black
federal judge in Florida history, of improperly disclosing secret
wiretap information and as a result torpedoing a federal
investigation.
   Hastings says he knew nothing of any plot. He claims it stemmed
from an idle boast by a friend and one-time classmate, Washington
attorney William Borders, that he could influence the judge's
actions.
   Borders, described in a House committee report as politically
influential in the late 1970s, was convicted of conspiracy and
imprisoned after accepting a garment bag stuffed with $125,000 in
cash from an FBI undercover agent.
   A 12-member Senate panel is preparing to hear evidence. Based on
its report, the full Senate will then vote on whether to remove
Hastings from the bench and halt payment of his $89,500 salary.
   Anderson said he is unsure if he will call on Borders, who has
``grounds to fear that he will be murdered'' if he testifies.
   Anderson said he based that statement on talks with Borders'
attorney and others. The cast of the case is spiced with shady
characters, including Florida mob boss Santo Trafficante and a
Miami antique dealer who kept the FBI informed Borders' plans in
return for lenient treatment on a narcotics charge.
   Anderson asked the Senate panel for $200,000 in expenses as well
as unspecified fees which he said at a fair rate of compensation
could add up to $750,000. He said that, even though Hastings is
well paid as a judge, he is indigent for purposes of the
impeachment trial because his salary is not enough to pay the high
costs.
   Anderson said that as a law professor at Miami University, he
could afford to take the summer off and work on the Hastings case.
But he said that without government funding, co-counsel Patricia
Williams would be ``committing economic suicide'' to devote full
time to the trial to the neglect of her law practice.
   After presenting his case to the lawmakers, however, Anderson
was not overly optimistic. ``I felt an awful lot like the train is
continuing to run down the track,'' he told reporters afterward.
   The attorney also asked for a 180-day delay in the start of
hearing evidence, saying he needs time to question potential
witnesses. The list includes former U.S. Chief Justice Warren
Burger and current Chief Justice William Rehnquist.
   In addition, Anderson asked the senators to force the House to
provide him with an array of documents ranging from working papers
produced by the prosecution to Justice Department and FBI
investigative files.
   The lawmakers went into closed session to deliberate following
the hearing and the chairman, Sen. Jeff Bingaman, D-N.M., said it
might have decisions to announce later in the week.
   Prosecutors from the House of Representatives urged the senators
to turn down the request for more documents. Rep. John Bryant,
D-Texas, said the House already had provided the defense with
numerous documents and offered to work with Anderson to duplicate
others.
   He said, however, that it was unreasonable for Anderson to
request ``every single document that we ever reviewed.'' Even if
the House complied, he said, it would be of little benefit to the
defense.
   ``He knows very well that we have no documents that exonerate
the defendant,'' Bryant said. ``If we did, why on earth would we be
here? We have had no desire to spend the last three years working
on this matter.''
   Bryant urged the senators not to delay the start of hearing
evidence and instead begin around June 1. He said the House would
take no position on whether to provide government money to wage
Hastings' legal battle.
   Rep. George W. Gekas, R-Pa., however, did express concern about
defense plans to question Burger, Rehnquist and a wide array of
other witnesses if granted the delay it seeks.
   ``We find that all of this evidence, that none of it is relevant
to the facts that must be presented to this committee,'' Gekas said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
