<FIRST>r a AM-FloridaBrushfires     04-12 0306</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Florida Brushfires,0314</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cold Front Helps Lift Smokey Haze Choking Southeast Florida</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SANDRA WALEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A cold front brought relief Wednesday from dense
smoke that had choked south Florida when wildfires spread through
about 32,000 acres of dry sawgrass.
   Smoke from the brushfires, which had enveloped metropolitan
Miami, cleared considerably and forecasters said the haze wasn't
expected to return.
   Meanwhile, increased humidity and lighter winds helped
firefighters control the blazes, according to Seb Farina, spokesman
for the state Division of Forestry.
   Two major fires in Dade County were contained overnight, with
only hot spots and some flare-ups being battled, officials said.
   In all, 27,000 acres have burned in Dade and another 5,000 acres
in Palm Beach County.
   There had been particular concern about one fire that appeared
headed toward the Everglades National Park. But spokeswoman Pat
Tolle said the closest the 18,000-acre fire got was about 4.5 miles
from the park boundary.
   On Tuesday, smoke from the fires made it difficult for some
workers in downtown Miami to see Biscayne Bay a few blocks away. It
also forced the evacuation of nearly 750 immigrants from a
detention facility that was overwhelmed by the choking haze.
   The detained aliens were bused back to the Krome Avenue
Detention Center on Wednesday, according to Perry Rivkind, district
director of the U.S. Immigration and Naturalization Service.
   ``We expected it to clear mostly overnight and it practically
has,'' said Wayne Colin, a forecaster for the National Weather
Service. ``We had a cold front come through and wind directions
changed.''
   Some of the lingering smoke blew further south, producing hazy
conditions and acrid air down to Key West. But Dr. Jose Bofill of
the Monroe County Health Unit described it as a ``very, very mild
situation. We have some smoke and you can smell it.''
</TEXT>
