<FIRST>r a AM-BorderDanger     04-12 0442</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Border Danger,0459</SECOND>
<HEAD>Satanic Slayings Don't Pose Threat To U.S. Travelers, Officials Say</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: With AM-Satanic Slaying; stands for DALLAS-datelined item on
digest.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID SEDENO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MATAMOROS, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Americans considering a trek across the
United States-Mexico border should not be dissuaded by the gruesome
discovery of 12 people slaughtered in satanic rituals, officials
said Wednesday.
   ``We do not believe there is any danger to people traveling to
Matamoros,'' said Texas Attorney General Jim Mattox.
   Members of a voodoo cult of drug smugglers, arrested in at least
12 ritual slayings, including a U.S. college student, said
Wednesday they sacrificed their victims for demonic protection from
police.
   The U.S. State Department was monitoring the situation,
officials said.
   ``We do not issue travel advisories in connection with isolated
criminal acts,'' said Frances Jones, spokeswoman for consular
affairs at the State Department in Washington.
   Last year, more than 118 million people crossed the United
States-Mexico border, according to Charles Conroy, public affairs
officer for the U.S. Customs Service.
   Of those, about 4.5 million were American pedestrians crossing
from Brownsville, Texas, into Matamoros, where authorities
discovered the mutilated body on Tuesday.
   Thousands of Americans come over for food, shopping or drinking
excursions. Restaurants, bars and curio shops dot Obregon Street
along the first mile into the city.
   Authorities Wednesday were quick to say the mass killing should
not alarm potential tourists.
   Arturo Moreno, supervisor at the Brownsville station of the U.S.
Border Patrol, said it could not be determined whether the killings
indicate tourists are in danger.
   ``We always tell people to travel with caution and stay in the
tourists area,'' Moreno said.
   Residents of Matamoros said they hope they can ward off a stigma
that could be attached to their city because of the slayings.
   ``We are very concerned and we will tell the tourists that 99.9
percent of the people here are good and that it only takes one or
two to give the others the bad name,'' said Ignacio Garcia, a shift
supervisor at Pancho Villa's restaurant, on Wednesday.
   It was the second drug-related mass killing discovered near the
international border in less than two weeks, officials said.
   Mexican authorities found the bodies of three women and six men
March 29 on an abandoned ranch near Agua Prieta, Sonora, just
across the border from Douglas, Ariz. All nine had been tortured,
mutilated and bound, officials said.
   On April 1, the bodies of three more men killed in similar
fashion were found there.
   Investigators said possible motives for the Agua Prieta slayings
range from revenge for lost narcotics or drug money to discouraging
informants to fighting between drug-smuggling factions.

</TEXT>
</DOC>
