<FIRST>r w AM-US-Angola     04-12 0483</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Angola,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Official Concedes UNITA Abuses But Says U.S. Aid Will Continue</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A State Department official said Wednesday
that Angolan rebels had committed human rights abuses but told
Congress the United States would continue to back them.
   ``No doubt hey (abuses) are taking place. They are on both
sides,'' E. Gibson Lanpher, the department's director of Southern
African affairs, responded under sharp questioning by Democrats
Howard Wolpe and Stephen Solarz.
   But he added that ``continued U.S. support for UNITA and
national reconciliation inside Angola are essential'' to ensure an
end to the country's 14-year civil war.
   The rebel Union for the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA) has
proposed talks with the Angolan government on a peace accord and
power-sharing, he said, and the government also ``is coming to
realize'' such a need.
   Lanpher's comments came at a hearing convened by the House
Ssubcommittee on Africa to debate U.S. policy in Angola in the wake
of the Cuban troop pullout that began earlier this year.
   In a related development, the House adopted an amendment that
would withhold the U.S. contribution to U.N. peacekeeping activity
in Angola unless all Cuban troops are withdrawn from that country
according to the stipulations of a U.S.-mediated agreement signed
last December.
   Rep. Gerald Solomon, a New York Republican who introduced the
measure, said it would require the president to report to Congress
periodically on the progress of the withdrawal of an estimated
40,000 Cuban troops.
   Solomon's amendment reflects the distrust felt by many
Republicans in Congress about the intentions of Cuba and its ally,
the Angolan government.
   Representative Dan Burton, ranking minority member of the Africa
subcommittee, accused the Angolan government of using chemical
weapons against rebels. He said allegations against UNITA of gross
human rights abuses are part of an Angolan campaign to discredit
the organization and stop the U.S. covert support begun in 1985.
   U.S. aid is estimated at $15 million to $40 million.
   Human Rights Watch, an American monitoring group, recommended to
Congress that U.S. aid to UNITA be stopped in light of evidence
``showing a practice of gross abuses of human rights.''
   A just-released report by the organization blames both UNITA and
the Angolan government for systematic and indiscriminate attacks on
civilians and charges UNITA with forcible conscription of
civilians, taking hundreds of foreigners hostage and using food as
a starvation weapon.
   Lanpher said the United States does not have any evidence to
substantiate accusations leveled in recent months by former UNITA
members that their families have been burned to death because they
practiced witchcraft.
   Solarz, a member of the House Intelligence Committee which
monitors the covert aid to Angola, urged Lanpher to investigate the
allegations. ``I can't imagine the American people want to
subsidize a movement that burns witches at the stake,'' he said.
``We got over that several hundred years ago at Salem.''
</TEXT>
