<FIRST>r i AM-Concorde 1stLd-Writethru a0665 04-12 0649</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Concorde, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0665,0664</SECOND>
<HEAD>Concorde Loses Party of Tail While Trying to Set Speed Record</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto SYD9, LaserColor SYD1, LaserGraphic NY19</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUB grafs 10-12, `But Ms....in London' with 5 grafs to ADD comment
from tour agency that arranged trip. EDITS throughout to tighten; no pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD BILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SYDNEY, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A supersonic Concorde jet carrying 100
Americans dropped a chunk of its tail over the South Pacific
Wednesday during an attempt to set a speed record, but it landed
safely and passengers were reported eager to try again.
   The 9-foot tail section of the British Airways plane ripped off
about 25 minutes after the plane left Christchurch, New Zealand,
for Sydney 1,000 miles away. Passengers said the plane shuddered,
but the craft landed in Sydney about an hour later. No one was
injured.
   The plane is attempting to set speed records for each of 12
parts of a three-week journey around the world. The passengers, who
included commentator William F. Buckley Jr., each paid $39,000 for
the trip, which began in London on April 1.
   Peter Stanton, an airline spokesman, said part of the rudder
disintegrated while the jet was flying at 40,000 feet at about
1,500 mph _ nearly twice the speed of sound.
   ``It experienced a shudder while over the Tasman Sea that was
thought to have been air turbulence,'' said Stanton. ``But it was a
normal landing; there was no emergency.''
   He said the control tower told the pilot, Capt. David Leney,
that a piece of the tail was missing.
   ``It wasn't until we got out of the plane and saw the firetrucks
and all the press ... that we knew something was wrong,'' Buckley
later told ABC's ``Good Morning America.''
   ``About 25 minutes after takeoff from New Zealand there was a
large thump,'' free-lance journalist Sheila Cole-Nilva told The
Associated Press. ``Everybody looked at everybody else and lunch
was served. The stewardesses looked terrified.
   ``The pilot came on and said there was nothing to worry about
and that there was a piece loose on the airplane.''
   Investigators began analyzing the Concorde's flight data
recorder to find out why the tail section broke off. British
Airways airport service manager Pat Boody said the crew noticed
``unusual vibrations'' during the flight.
   Buckley, who helped organize the trip, planned to broadcast his
television show ``Firing Line'' during stops in Cape Town, South
Africa, and Sydney. Other stops on the itinerary include Acapulco,
Mexico; Colombo, Sri Lanka; and Mombassa, Kenya. The trip was
scheduled to end April 23 in London.
   The Lorraine Travel Bureau in Miami, which arranged the trip,
refused to release the passengers' names. ``There were no
celebrities that are household names,'' said company president Jack
R. Guiteras.
   He said all 100 passengers were ``very excited and happy with
the trip,'' and that none had asked to leave the tour.
   Ms. Cole-Nilva said they ``can't wait to get back on board.''
   A British Airways spokeswoman, who by custom is not identified,
said the trip would cover 38,343 miles. ``It's the first ever
supersonic circumnavigation of the earth,'' she said.
   A prototype of the Anglo-French Concorde first flew 20 years
ago. It has been in commercial service since 1976, but mainly on
trans-Atlantic routes.
   An airline spokesman in London said a spare part was being sent,
but it was not known if the plane could be repaired in time to make
its scheduled flight Friday to Perth in western Australia. The
airline gave no details on how much of the tail needed to be
replaced.
   British Airways gave its Concordes a clean bill of health two
months ago after inquiries that were prompted by the discovery of
tiny cracks in the roof of one plane. Similar checks were made on
Air France Concordes.
   Concordes have been involved in a number of minor incidents, but
there have been no fatal accidents.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
