<DOCNO> AP890412-0198 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-12-89 2123EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w BC-EthicsGlance     04-12 0493</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Ethics Glance,510</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are major provisions of President Bush's
proposals Wednesday to tighten ethics rules for judges, members of
Congress and the executive branch:
</TEXT>
<NOTE>PAY RAISES</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Bush proposed a 25 percent pay increase for federal judges,
coupled with a ban on acceptance of speaking fees and other
honoraria. Associate justices of the Supreme Court, for example,
would see their salaries rise from $110,000 to $137,000 while U.S.
district court judges' pay would go to $111,900 from $89,500.
   Bush said he supported pay hikes and a honoraria ban for
Congress but did not make a specific proposal.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>CAMPAIGN FINANCING</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Bush proposed a ban on the use of leftover campaign
contributions for personal use and office expenses. The law now
allows anyone who held office before 1980 to use such funds for any
lawful purpose.
   Bush also called for a ban on campaign contributions by
political action committees, although he did not make a formal
proposal on it. He also said he opposes efforts to set up a federal
fund for congressional races like the taxpayer-supported one that
is used for the presidential campaign.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>FINANCIAL DISCLOSURE</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   To tighten financial disclosure rules, Bush proposed a uniform
system for the three branches of government, requiring individuals
to disclose the actual value of each asset and source of income,
rounded to the nearest thousand dollars. Currently, individuals are
required to report only within broad categories, such as $5,000 to
$15,000.
   More members of the executive branch also would have to file
disclosure reports.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>CONFLICTS OF INTEREST</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Bush proposed to expand a law that forbids individuals in the
executive branch from taking official actions that financially
benefit them or members of their family. He said it also should
apply to the judiciary and employes of Congress, though not to
Congress members themselves.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>OUTSIDE ACTIVITIES</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Senior officials in all three branches of government would be
barred from serving on the board of directors of for-profit
enterprises.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>POST EMPLOYMENT ACTIVITIES</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Bush proposed that members of Congress who retire or are
defeated be barred for a year from contacting former colleagues to
lobby them. This ban also would be extended to senior officials in
the judicial branch.
   His proposed bill also would abolish ``compartmentalization'' of
the various agencies of the executive branch for purposes of
lobbying. That means that executive branch workers, currently
barred for a year from lobbying their former office once they leave
the government, would be under the same restriction regarding all
the departments of the executive branch.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>ENFORCEMENT</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The independent counsel statute that has been invoked to
authorize investigations of members of the executive branch would
be extended to cover the Congress.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EXECUTIVE ORDER</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Under an executive order issued by Bush, fulltime, non-career
presidential appointees in the executive branch would be prohibited
from receiving any earned income from outside employment.
   The executive order also would give elevated rank to a
designated ethics officer in each department.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890412-0199 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-12-89 2005EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     04-12 0393</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Record Cold in South; Rain in Great Lakes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A cold snap set low temperature records in more than 20 cities
across the South on Wednesday, and light rain and snow fell on the
Great Lakes region and the northern Ohio Valley.
   Moist air steamed northward from the Gulf of Mexico and bbrought
cloudy skies and scattered light showers to Texas. There also were
scattered showers in eastern Kentucky and eastern Tennessee, and a
few showers over the Florida peninsula. It was sunny across most of
the rest of the nation.
   Low pressure over Lake Huron caused the light snow and rain in
the upper Midwest. Grand Rapids, Mich., received an inch of snow
during the six hours ending at 2 p.m. EDT.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 30
degrees at Marquette, Mich., to 88 degrees at the China Lake Naval
Air Station and Palm Springs, both in California.
   The low for the nation Wednesday morning was 7 degrees at
Warroad, Minn.
   Low temperature records that were set or tied included 32
degrees in Augusta, Ga., 37 in Baton Rouge, La., 29 in Chattanooga,
Tenn., 15 in Elkins, W.V., 41 in Jacksonville, Fla., 26 in
Knoxville, Tenn., 33 in Macon, Ga., 34 in Montgomery, Ala., 43 in
New Orleans, 24 in Roanoke, Va., 35 in Savannah, Ga., and 32 in
Wilmington, N.C.
   The National Weather Service forecast for Thursday called for
showers and a few thunderstorms across the southern Plains and the
lower Mississippi Valley, with rain and snow showers over the
northern Atlantic Coast states and northern New England. A few
showers and thunderstorms were forecast for the Florida peninsula.
   A few rainshowers also were forecast for northern Minnesota and
northwestern Wisconsin. Sunny skies were expected across the rest
of the nation.
   Afternoon highs were expected to be in the 60s and 70s over much
of the nation, with highs below 60 from eastern North Dakota
through the Great Lakes region and the northern Ohio Valley to the
middle and northern Atlantic Coast, and in the 50s from Colorado to
the Texas panhandle. Highs in the 80s were forecast for the Florida
peninsula, and from southern Arizona through much of California to
southwest Oregon. Highs in the 90s were expected in the
southwestern deserts and some of the California valleys.
</TEXT>
