<DOCNO> AP890412-0202 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-12-89 2342EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Zimbabwe     04-12 0505</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Zimbabwe,0525</SECOND>
<HEAD>Corruption Report on Car Racket Names Five Zimbabwe Ministers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN EDLIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judicial commission investigating
top-level corruption linked five Cabinet ministers to a
black-market car racket, according to a report published Thursday.
One minister quit hours earlier.
   The report said that of six ministers quizzed in a two-month
inquiry headed by Judge Wilson Sandura, only Foreign Minister
Nathan Shamuyarira was cleared of wrongdoing.
   Senior Cabinet Minister Maurice Nyagumbo, a staunch ally of
President Robert Mugabe, resigned his post on Wednesday, hours
before the report was made public.
   Two of Mugabe's top aides, Defense Minister Enos Nkala and
Political Affairs Minister Frederick Shava, quit the government and
the ruling Zimbabwe African National Union (Patriotic Front) party
after lying to the commission.
   But Sandura's three-member commission said Higher Education
Minister Dzingai Mutumbuka should be prosecuted, Industry and
Technology Minister Callistus Ndlovu evidently lied in his
testimony and doubts exist about Nyagumbo's evidence.
   The commission also recommended that Matabeleland North Gov.
Jacob Muzenda be prosecuted. But it exonerated army commander Gen.
Tapfumaneyi Mujuru.
   The commission sent its report to Mugabe two weeks ago after
interrogating 60 witnesses. It is Zimbabwe's biggest political
scandal in nine years of independence.
   Mugabe ordered the probe after a provincial newspaper exposed
the racket in December. He promised the full report would be made
public.
   While identifying abuses of power, position and privileges in
the leadership, the inquiry also won Mugabe praise for ordering
some of his closest aides to face the embarrassment of being
quizzed under the public spotlight.
   Nyagumbo, 64, is a staunch ally of Mugabe, a veteran nationalist
and a founder of the government party, the nation's only legal
party, in which he holds the third-highest position.
   Zimbabwe TV gave no explanation in announcing Nyagumbo's
resignation. But aides, speaking on condition of anonymity, linked
it to the corruption scandal and said Mugabe is expected to make an
announcement this week about changes in government.
   The probe that shook Africa's youngest nation was into purchases
of cars and trucks from Willowvale car assembly plant by ministers
and their friends at low, fixed prices.
   High-ranking officials allegedly used their influence to jump
waiting lines for vehicles and then resell them illegally on the
black market for up to five times what they paid.
   Zimbabwe has suffered a severe shortage of cars because it lacks
hard currency. Would-be buyers may wait up to 10 years for a new
vehicle.
   Nyagumbo admitted helping 38 friends buy cars, but insisted he
took no money in return.
   The report said ``it was difficult to believe he received no
benefits at all.''
   The commission disputed the testimony of four other ministers
who testified they bought cars but sold them at the statutory price.
   Charges being considered range from price control violations and
sales tax evasion, which usually involve nominal fines, to perjury,
which carries a maximum prison sentence of five years.
   The commission praised Geoff Nyarota, the crusading editor who
spotlighted what became known as Willowgate.
</TEXT>
