<SECOND>BC-AP Arts: Chaplin, Adv 16,1179</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv 16</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, April 16 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>MEMORIES OF LAUGHTER</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   ``You know, this fellow is many-sided _ a tramp, a gentleman, a
poet, a dreamer, a lonely fellow, always hopeful of romance and
adventure. He would have you believe he is a scientist, a musician,
a duke, a polo player. However, he is not above picking up
cigarette butts or robbing a baby of its candy.'' _ Chalie Chaplin.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>By HILLEL ITALIE</NOTE>
<NOTE>Associated Press Writer</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ask George Burns to say something funny and
he'll come back with two words: ``Charlie Chaplin.''
   To Lucille Ball, Chaplin was ``pure genius,'' and Jack Lemmon
calls him ``the definitive artist of this century.''
   Few characters in film history ever touched as many lives as
Chaplin's Tramp. ``The Little Fellow,'' as he called him, was the
epitome of the fighting underdog: down but never out; hopelessly
romantic despite endless disappointment; determined to retain his
dignity in the face of despair and humiliation.
   Chaplin moved beyond the pie-throwing and wild chases of
slapstick to make audiences understand the Tramp's feelings about
himself and the world around him. He was, as the film critic James
Agee once said, ``the first man to give the silent language a
soul.''
   April 16 marks the 100th anniversary of Chaplin's birth, and his
centennial is being celebrated with tributes throughout the world.
   His admirers included kings and queens, soldiers and prisoners.
Children chased him in the street. Writers and poets sought his
company. From London to Japan, crowds would swarm around him.
   Generations of performers looked to Chaplin as they sculpted
their own brands of humor.
   Bill Cosby realized the extent of Chaplin's influence after
seeing his 1931 classic, ``City Lights,'' in which the Tramp
befriends a millionaire and falls in love with a blind girl.
   ``While watching the feature, I was getting very angry at
Charlie Chaplin because I was noticing he was doing a lot of funny
things that I'd seen other comedians in other features do,'' Cosby
said. ``It was only later that all those things I saw him doing
were things he created, and that the other talents had copied him.''
   The famous assembly-line sequence from an ``I Love Lucy''
episode in which Lucy and Ethel try to keep up with the chocolates
is derived from a similar scene in Chaplin's 1936 ``Modern Times,''
in which an assembly-line worker goes crazy.
   The silent chase scene in Woody Allen's ``Bananas'' is another
Chaplin-inspired bit. The filmmaker once said in an interview that
he admired the way Chaplin used thin plots on which to hang funny
scenes.
   Chaplin could take the simplest human predicament and expand it
into a lifetime. A scene in the old TV series, ``The
Honeymooners,'' finds Ralph and Ed locked up in Ralph's freezing
apartment on a rent strike. They're running out of food and must
eat celery for dinner. Ed (Art Carney) pretends the celery is a
full-course steak dinner, and eats with great flourish. Chaplin did
a similar bit when he devoured his boot in ``The Gold Rush.''
   Chaplin, who died in 1977 following a stroke, was born in
Lambeth, a ghetto in the south of London. The son of music hall
performers, his early years were difficult. His parents, Charles
and Hannah, were separated by 1892; his father rarely made child
support payments, forcing Charlie and his older brother, Sydney, to
spend time in a local orphanage. Charlie was close to his mother,
but she was mentally unstable and drifted in and out of nursing
homes.
   ``I don't think he ever lost that thing about poverty,''
recalled Jerry Epstein, a longtime friend whose book ``Remembering
Charlie'' has recently been released. ``That haunts you, one day
you wake up and it's all gone. That's a living nightmare. He once
said to me, `What would have happened to me if I never left
England?'''
   Chaplin showed talent as a mime and acrobat and first appeared
on stage when he was 4, singing at a nearby music hall for a wildly
appreciative audience of soldiers who threw money at the young
performer. By 1899, he had become one of the Eight Lancashire Lads,
a traveling group of dancers and comedians.
   In 1908, he became a comic with the celebrated Fred Karno
company, impressing and, at times, alienating peers with his
single-minded devotion to his craft. Chaplin would later punctuate
a creative dispute by insisting, ``This is my work!''
   On a tour of the United States late in 1912, he was spotted by a
talent agent. The following year, he signed a one-year contract for
$150 a week with Mack Sennett's Keystone Films, known for slapstick
movies that concluded with spectacular chases.
   Chaplin's first motion picture, ``Making a Living,'' was
released in 1914 to generally favorable reviews, although his
character bore no resemblance to the Tramp. Chaplin, wearing a top
hat, monacle and droopy mustache, portrayed a slicker who tries to
``scoop'' a reporter.
   In his third picture, ``Mabel's Strange Predictament,'' he
unveiled the Tramp, drawing on English music hall costumes. He
contrasted oversized pants and extra long shoes with a shrunken
jacket and battered bowler hat, adding a tiny mustache and walking
cane to give the impression of a man aspiring for status but not
succeeding.
   ``He said the cane was the key to the whole characterization,''
Epstein recalled. ``The minute he found that cane he knew he had
the character. He could attack people with it, he could act like
the gentleman with it.''
   Chaplin gave the Tramp a shuffling, ``splay-footed'' walk that
he picked up by imitating an old man called ``Rummy'' Banks, who
used to hold horses for coachmen outside a neighborhood pub.
   Audiences instantly responded. A Chicago reporter interviewed
Chaplin and commented, ``You can't keep your eyes off his feet.
Those big shoes are buttoned with 50 million eyes.''
   Charlie Chaplin cartoons began appearing in newspapers. Songs
came out _ ``Those Charlie Chaplin Feet,'' ``Charlie Chaplin, the
Funniest of Them All'' and ``The Moon Shines Bright on Charlie
Chaplin.''
   By 1916, Chaplin was with the Mutual Film Corporation, making a
staggering annual salary of $670,000, and critics were starting to
regard his films as more than just entertainment. An article in
Harper's Weekly, ``The Art of Charles Chaplin,'' praised the star
in ways comedians never were. It compared the vulgarity of his
films to the works of Aristophanes and Shakespeare.
   In 1919, Chaplin, Mary Pickford, Douglas Fairbanks and D.W.
Griffith formed United Artists as a way of independently producing
and financing their own films.
   ``Initially it was great,'' said William Everson, a professor of
cinema studies at New York University. ``None of these people were
getting the full results of their labor. On paper it seemed ideal,
but financially it wasn't feasible.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890412-0228 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-12-89 1452EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s e BC-APArts:Chaplin Adv16-1stAdd   04-12 1212</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-AP Arts: Chaplin, Adv 16-1st Add,1255</SECOND>
<HEAD>NEW YORK _ ``wasn't feasible.''</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Chaplin began fleshing out his films _ mostly one-reelers _ with
social commentary, relating the hardship faced by Europeans coming
to America in ``The Immigrant,'' and stressing the bonds shared by
warring soldiers in ``Shoulder Arms.''
   His sentimental side emerged even more strongly in his feature
films, starting in 1921 with ``The Kid,'' which depicted the
Tramp's friendship with an abandoned boy, Jackie Coogan.
   The film, Chaplin's first full-length feature, grossed $2{
million, made an instant star out of young Coogan and gave full
display to Chaplin's dramatic range. His next feature, ``The Gold
Rush,'' came out in 1925, and is regarded by Chaplin and many
others as his finest work.
   Inspired by stories of the 1898 gold rush, the movie starred
Chaplin as the Lone Prospector, and contained one of the most
famous sequences in film history, ``The Dance of the Rolls.''
   Chaplin invites an attractive singer and her friends to dinner
on New Year's Eve and enthusiastically prepares the meal. But his
company never shows up and Chaplin falls asleep. He dreams about
entertaining the guests by sticking forks in two dinner rolls and
acting out a puppet-like dance on the table.
   In another immortal segment, he's stranded without food in a
freezing cabin and boils his own boot, consuming the dinner with
considerable relish, even twirling the laces like spaghetti.
   Chaplin often referred to an early love affair that would
forever leave him with the desire to ``reach out for beauty,'' a
yearning he employed to heartbreaking effect in ``The Gold Rush''
and ``The Circus,'' in which the Tramp falls in love with a circus
girl.
   In vain, the Tramp would pursue beautiful, unreachable women,
never more movingly than in ``City Lights,'' in which he befriends
a pretty blind flower girl and convinces her that he is a man of
wealth and distinction.
   As Agee wrote, the Tramp is eventually brought down to painful
reality when he raises the money necessary for the blind girl to
regain her sight:
   ``At the end of `City Lights,' ... (she) sees him for the first
time. She has imagined and anticipated him as princely, to say the
least; and it had never seriously occurred to him that he is
inadequate. She recognizes who he must be by his shy, confident,
shining joy as he comes silently toward her. And he recognizes
himself through the terrible changes in her face.
   ``The camera just exchanges a few quiet close-ups of the
emotions which shift and intensify in each face. It is enough to
shrivel the heart to see, and it is the greatest piece of acting
and the highest moment in movies.''
   Chaplin's peers praised him in similar terms. The great Buster
Keaton repeatedly deferred to his ``rival'' as being in a class by
himself, writing that ``nobody ever made so many people laugh as
did Charlie with his Little Tramp.''
   Although the onset of talking films in the late '20s ruined the
careers of many stars, notably John Gilbert, Chaplin was reluctant
to use sound, complaining that ``dialogue, to my way of thinking,
always slows action, because action must wait upon words.''
   ``Motion pictures need dialogue as much as Beethoven symphonies
need lyrics,'' he once said.
   ``City Lights'' was Chaplin's last silent movie. In 1936, he
released ``Modern Times,'' which had some crude sound effects and
made a star out of Paulette Goddard, the third of his four wives.
   Both movies were box-office hits, as was 1940's ``The Great
Dictator,'' a stinging attack against Hitler, who bore an uncanny
resemblance to the comic. In 1941, his artistic dreams played
second to his personal life. He met and had a brief relationship
with a young actress, Joan Barry. She later accused Chaplin of
fathering her child. Although blood tests backed up his claims that
the baby wasn't his, a California jury said he was, causing
considerable damage to his reputation and paving the way for
right-wing branding of communism.
   With McCarthyism in full and furious throttle, Chaplin, an
outspoken liberal and supporter of the wartime alliance with the
Soviet Union, came under harsh attack. He had lived in California
but had never become a U.S. citizen, considering himself ``a
citizen of the world.''
   When he went to England in the early '50s to film ``Limelight,''
his entry permit was revoked. The man who had embodied the American
Dream, working his way from music hall performer to international
celebrity, lived his final years in Vevey, Switzerland.
   ``I never saw him depressed,'' Jerry Epstein said. ``He loved
America. He would say, `After all, that's where I met Oona.'''
   Oona O'Neill, daughter of the playwright Eugene O'Neill, was 18
when they married. Chaplin was 54.
   ``She devoted her whole life to him,'' Epstein said. ``She knew
how to handle an artist. Oona is completely reserved,
self-effacing; never wanted the career, never wanted the limelight.
She was in love with him her whole life.
   ``She always said, `When I was young he looked after me, now
that he's an old man, it's my turn to look after him.'''
   Their eight children carved their own fame: Geraldine, the
oldest, became an actress who soared to fame in David Lean's 1965
epic, ``Dr. Zhivago.'' Josephine portrayed Hemingway's wife in a TV
miniseries about the writer. Michael played one of the leads in
``King in New York'' when he was 9. All three children had walk-ons
in ``Limelight.''
   Victoria runs a French circus called Le Cirque Imaginaire.
Eugene is a businessman. Jane lives in Florida with Ilya Salkind,
producer of the Superman movies. Annette recently appeared in a
stage production of Sam Shepard's ``Buried Child'' in France.
Christopher, 25, the youngest, appeared in ``Notes From the
Underground'' in London.
   Chaplin also had two children from his second wife, Lita Grey.
Sydney won a Tony playing opposite Judy Holliday in ``Bells Are
Ringing,'' and co-starred with Barbra Streisand in ``Funny Girl''
on Broadway. Charlie Jr. died about 20 years ago.
   After ``Monsieur Verdoux'' flopped in 1947, Chaplin never again
regained his commercial appeal. ``Limelight,'' released in 1952,
contained a memorable musical sequence with Chaplin and Buster
Keaton, but had only moderate success. He made just two more
movies, both poorly received: ``A King in New York,'' and ``A
Countess From Hong Kong,'' a 1967 comedy starring Marlon Brando and
Sophia Loren.
   Chaplin spent the last 10 years of his life collecting honors,
composing new scores for his movies and working on a project, ``The
Freak.'' It was never completed.
   He returned briefly to the United States in 1972 to receive an
``honorary'' Oscar from the Academy of Motion Picture Arts &amp;
Sciences. The Cannes Film Festival had paid tribute to him the year
before, and the Venice Film Festival gave him a special Golden Lion
award. He received knighthood from Queen Elizabeth II in March 1975.
   A fan of the underdog to the end, Chaplin expressed admiration
for Sylvester Stallone's ``Rocky,'' murmuring, ``excellent,
excellent,'' as he watched the movie.
   ``He just took life as it came,'' Epstein said. ``He never spoke
about death. He never spoke about old age. He felt he was still
young. He never lost his sense of curiosity.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, April 16</NOTE>
