<FIRST>s e BC-APArts:Chaplin-Grave Adv16   04-12 0472</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-AP Arts: Chaplin-Grave, Adv 16,0482</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv16</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, April 16 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-AP Arts: Chaplin</HEAD>
<HEAD>MEMORIES OF LAUGHTER</HEAD>
<HEAD>A White Marble Tombstone Has Replaced the Wooden Cross</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HANNS NEUERBOURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   CORSIER-SUR-VEVEY, Switzerland (AP) _ The plain wooden cross
that marked the burial site before the sensational theft of the
body, was replaced long ago.
   Now there's a white, marble tombstone with the simple
inscription: ``Charles Chaplin, 1889-1977,'' dropping the ``Sir''
to which the world-famous comedian was entitled after being
knighted by Queen Elizabeth II in 1975.
   Under a bright spring sun, the forget-me-nots and the white and
rose hyacinths seemed freshly planted. Other graves in the Swiss
cemetery were equally well kept, bearing names more familiar in the
village where the reclusive actor never really struck roots.
   ``I am sure their gardner will prepare some special floral
decoration for the anniversary,'' said Etienne Buenzod, a communal
employee who takes care of the cemetery of Corsier, a wine-growing
village overlooking Lake Geneva where Chaplin spent the last 25
years of his life.
   ``I saw some of his films but I saw him in person only once
during these 25 years. He was a very discreet man.''
   So seems his widow, Lady Oona, who still resides in the
Chaplins' Manoir de Ban _ an 18th-century manor just above Corsier
_ but who is rarely seen in the village.
   Corsier was preparing for weeks of festivities marking the 100th
anniversary of Chaplin's birth. He was the village's most famous
resident and, posthumously, put its name on front pages worldwide
when two would-be extortionists snatched his body.
   Buenzod discovered the theft on March 2, 1978, more than two
months after Chaplin died on Christmas Day following a stroke. The
300-pound oak-and-silver coffin with the body inside was recovered
10 weeks later, buried in a cornfield about 10 miles from here.
   News of the bizarre theft spread throughout the world. The
Soviet news agency TASS denounced it as ``typical for the
atmopshere of crime in the inhuman Western world.''
   But a Swiss court took a more lenient view of the two
perpetrators, political refugees from Poland and Bulgaria.
   ``I wanted to get money without harming anyone,'' testified
Roman Wardas, the theft's bungling Polish mastermind, who was
arrested when he ran out of coins at a public phone during ransom
negotiations with the Chaplins' family lawyer.
   The two also had to dig up the coffin for a second time because
they had forgotten to take photographs to prove they were holding
it. Lady Oona, according to the lawyer, categorically rejected
ransom demands, lowered gradually from $600,000 to $100,000, saying
her husband was ``in heaven and in my heart.''
   Wardas was sentenced to 4{ years in prison, but freed after
three years because of good conduct.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, April 16</NOTE>
</DOC>
