<FILEID>AP-NR-04-12-89 1334EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--FilmReview Adv00-1stLd-Writethru b0810 04-12 0499</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Film Review, Adv 00-1st Ld-Writethru, b0810,0507</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv00</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Anytime</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS name from family from Henderson to Campbell throughout.
Opens nationally on Friday, April 14.</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>At the Movies: ``Winter People''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB THOMAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Some of the most interesting films of 1988 stemmed from novels:
``Dangerous Liaisons,'' ``The Accidental Tourist,'' ``Little
Dorrit,'' ``The Last Temptation of Christ,'' ``The Unbearable
Lightness of Being,'' ``Pelle the Conqueror.''
   While original screenplays remain the most prevalent source of
films, it is heartening to see the comeback of novels.
   Why so? Because from ``The Birth of a Nation'' to ``Gone With
the Wind'' to ``Terms of Endearment,'' novels have lent film
entertainment a substance that is often lacking on a diet of
scripts originated by screenwriters and homogenized by countless
rewrites.
   ``Winter People'' is the latest evidence. Adapted by Carol
Sobieski from John Ehle's novel, the film has faults and excesses.
But it also offers a certain majesty and an accurate sense of time
and place _ the Blue Ridge Mountains in the Depression 1930s.
   Wayland Jackson (Kurt Russell) is a watchmaker who is driving
his motherless daughter (Amelia Burnette) to Philadelphia to start
a new life. When their pickup truck is wrecked in a mountain
stream, they take refuge with a mysterious woman (Kelly McGillis),
who lives in a remote cabin with her fatherless baby boy.
   The mystery unravels. McGillis has been ostracized by her
family, the Wrights, who are the leading citizens of a nearby
village. The father of her child is the unruly son (Jeffrey Meek)
of the lawless Campbell clan, longtime enemies of the Wrights.
   Russell wins the young mother's confidence and love, and the
respect of her family _ after proving his manhood on a bear hunt.
When the father of McGillis' son dies mysteriously, the
long-smoldering feud between the Wrights and the Campbells erupts
in violence.
   Director Ted Kotcheff manages to keep the complicated plot
running smoothly, though at times the mountain dialect is hard to
comprehend. Kelly McGillis gives understated strength to her role,
and Kurt Russell has his strongest characterization to date, though
the transition from milquetoast to macho man is less than smooth.
   Lloyd Nolan and Mitchell Ryan are powerful as patriarchs of the
two families. As the violent Campbell, Jeffrey Meek is terrifying.
The mountain scenery have been stunningly photographed by Francois
Protat.
   ``Winter People'' was produced by Robert H. Solo for Columbia
Pictures. Scariness and sexual tension give it a PG-13 rating.
Running time: 115 minutes.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Motion Picture Association of America rating definitions:
   G _ General audiences. All ages admitted.
   PG _ Parental guidance suggested. Some material may not be
suitable for children.
   PG-13 _ Special parental guidance strongly suggested for
children under 13. Some material may be inappropriate for young
children.
   R _ Restricted. Under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult
guardian.
   X _ No one under 17 admitted. Some states may have higher age
restrictions.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Release Anytime</NOTE>
</DOC>
