<FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     04-12 0820</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0855</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A midnight Tuesday deadline to complete
agreements to sell Eastern Airlines to ex-baseball commissioner
Peter V. Ueberroth passed without the parties reaching a deal, but
the judge overseeing the talks ordered all sides to return to his
courtroom today.
   It remained unclear whether the parties had agreed to extend the
deadline, which was imposed by Ueberroth and Texas Air Corp.,
Eastern's parent company. None of those involved would comment
immediately.
   Although a group led by Ueberroth has agreed with Eastern union
leaders on labor concessions necessary to complete the $464 million
buyout, sources said remaining obstacles included resistance by
Texas Air to demands that include the naming of a special trustee
to run the airline.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NWA Inc. and Los Angeles billionaire Marvin
Davis filed lawsuits against each other in an increasingly bitter
battle over Davis's $2.62 billion takeover bid for the parent of
Northwest Airlines.
   Davis, who has offered to buy NWA for $90 a share, filed suit
Tuesday challenging adoption of a ``poison pill'' anti-takeover
plan by NWA and said he planned a shareholder proxy fight to win
control of the airline's board.
   Northwest later announced it was suing Davis in federal court in
St. Paul.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate rejected President Bush's minimum
wage plan and moved closer to confronting him with legislation
raising the hourly figure to $4.55, which he repeatedly has
promised to veto.
   The Senate, on a 61-39 vote Tuesday largely along party lines,
backed an amendment to legislation sponsored by Sen. Edward M.
Kennedy, D-Mass., that brought the measure essentially in line with
a House-passed bill that would boost the minimum wage to $4.55 by
October 1991.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NATICK, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Computer Inc. said it will seek a
buyer willing to pay more than the $20 a share offer by hostile
suitor MAI Basic Four Inc. that values the company at $970 million.
   Prime said Tuesday its financial advisers, First Boston Corp.
and Smith Barney, Harris Upham &amp; Co., had been instructed to
``actively solicit proposals and to pursue discussions and
negotiations'' to sell the company for more than $20 a share.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A House banking panel voted to gut the key
reform of the Bush administration's savings and loan proposal, but
then rolled back in several follow-up votes on some of the changes
that most weakened the plan.
   By a 24-23 vote Tuesday, the House Banking subcommittee on
financial institutions diluted a requirement to force S&amp;L owners to
back loans with more of their own capital.
   Then, the subcommittee partly retightened the definition of
capital regarding subordinated debt and deferred loan losses.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A House panel approved legislation to end 35
years of federal control of natural gas prices, a step cheered by
the energy industry but criticized by some consumer groups even
though decontrol could mean slightly cheaper gas for consumers.
   The House Energy and Commerce Committee, on a voice vote Tuesday
without dissent, sent the measure to the full House, where even its
strongest critics say approval is likely. A similar measure has
been introduced but not yet act on in the Senate.

</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Construction contracting will fall about 3
percent in 1989, pulled down by sharp drops in office and other
commercial instruction, a private forecast says.
   A glut of commercial space on the market and rising interest
rates are the main reasons for the projected decline, according to
the Dodge-Sweet's Construction Outlook by McGraw-Hill Information
Systems Co. released Tuesday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Pritzker family has reduced its stake in
Ramada Inc. to less than 5 percent, indicating the billionaire clan
has chosen to take profits rather than try to take over the
Arizona-based hotelier, analysts said.
   HCC Corp., a Chicago company headed by Jay A. Pritzker, said in
an April 5 filing with the Securities and Exchange Commission that
it had sold 959,100 shares of Ramada stock from March 16 through
April 5 at an average price of $11.29 a share. Ramada stock closed
Tuesday at $11.75 a share, unchanged.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita reversed himself
before Parliament, acknowledging he accepted $1 million from a
company at the hub of a political scandal that has prompted calls
for his resignation.
   Though Takeshita went before lawmakers Tuesday seeking to clear
his name in the nationally televised session, opposition leaders
and some conservative analysts said he only raised more doubts.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>By The Associated Press</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market advanced Tuesday, as the Dow Jones average of
30 industrials rose 9.71 to 2,311.58.
   Bond prices edged higher in light dealings.
   The dollar finished firmer against most major currencies.
   Wheat futures prices rose; other grain and soybean futures
finished narrowly mixed; gasoline futures surged while other oil
futures were mixed; livestock and meat futures retreated; and
precious metals were mixed.
</TEXT>
