<DOCNO> AP890412-0236 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-12-89 0407EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Bilzerian     04-12 0294</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bilzerian,0308</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Drops One Count, Refuses to Move Bilzerian Securities Trial
to Florida</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge has dismissed one of 12 felony
counts against Singer Co. chairman and corporate takeover
specialist Paul Bilzerian but refused to shift the securities fraud
trial to Florida.
   Bilzerian, 38, is accused of violating securities and tax laws,
conspiracy and making false statements in connection with four
failed takeover transactions in 1985 and 1986.
   U.S. District Judge Robert J. Ward on Tuesday dismissed one
count of making false disclosure statements in a transaction with
Armco Inc. One felony count remains connected to that deal.
   The defense had asked Ward to dismiss all charges against
Bilzerian, who has denied the government's claims.
   Ward also denied a request to move the trial to federal court in
Tampa, Fla., where Bilzerian lives.
   Ward said he expects the trial, scheduled to begin May 1, to
last four to six weeks.
   The government contends Bilzerian made millions of dollars by
accumulating stock in takeover targets _ specifically, Hammermill
Paper Co., H.H. Robertson Co., Cluett Peabody &amp; Co. _ concealing
ownership of the stocks in secret accounts and then selling his
holdings after the stock price had risen.
   None of the charges involve Bilzerian's $1.06 billion takeover
of Singer, a defense contractor he acquired last year after a
lengthy struggle.
   Much of the government's case is derived from information
supplied to the government by Los Angeles broker Boyd L. Jefferies,
who has admitted to two felonies for violating federal securities
laws.
   Jefferies also supplied information for the government's stock
manipulation case against GAF Corp., which ended in a second
mistrial last month.
   Bilzerian faces a maximum penalty of five years in jail and a
$250,000 fine on each count.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
