<DOCNO> AP890412-0237 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-12-89 0408EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-ButcherAward     04-12 0323</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Butcher Award,0335</SECOND>
<HEAD>Butcher Trustee Awarded $19.3 Million In Damages</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHATTANOOGA, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge has ordered C.H.
Butcher Jr. and others to pay $19.3 million in damages for a plot
to hide the bankrupt financier's wealth when his banking empire
collapsed.
   U.S. District Judge R. Allan Edgar awarded the damages Tuesday
to bankruptcy trustee David Martin to pay creditors in the last
major civil lawsuit against Butcher.
   A federal jury in Knoxville last month found that C.H. Butcher
Sr. and two disbarred Atlanta lawyers conspired to help the younger
Butcher keep some of his wealth.
   The jury found the senior Butcher, Robert L. Schwind and David
L. Hill guilty under the Racketeering Influenced Corrupt
Organizations Act following a four-day trial.
   C.H. Butcher Jr. and his brother, 1978 Tennessee Democratic
gubernatorial candidate Jake Butcher, were convicted in connection
with the 1983 failure of their twin banking empires, Southern
Industrial Banking Corp. and United American Bank chain.
   Testimony included assertions that Hill received $1.6 million
from Butcher Jr. to buy gold bars and coins after the financier had
declared bankruptcy.
   Martin has been trying to locate the $1.6 million and documents
produced at the trial showed that Hill was the last person known to
have handled it.
   Hill was not present at the trial. He and Schwind, his former
law partner, were disbarred after their money-laundering
convictions in an unrelated case.
   The jury awarded damages of $245,437 from Butcher Sr., $474,288
from Schwind and $1.63 million from Hill. Under a RICO provision
tripling that amount, the total jury award was $7,049,176.
   But Edgar found that Schwind and Hill were liable for $4,889,999
after the damages were tripled, while Butcher Jr. was responsible
for $11,276,250 individually and $2,422,583 with his wife, Shirley.
   The suit initially sought $126 million in damages from a dozen
defendants. But after a series of out-of-court settlements, it
changed the damages sought to $8 million from five defendants.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890412-0238 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-12-89 0409EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Time-Warner Bjt   04-12 0585</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Time-Warner, Bjt,0604</SECOND>
<HEAD>Time Exec Says Company Will Be Active In Cable, Defends Merger Plans</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Time Inc. intends to become a major player in
basic cable television programming, says the media giant's
chairman, who also took a few jabs at broadcasters who have tried
to belittle the medium.
   In a speech Tuesday to cable executives and advertisers,
Chairman J. Richard Munro also defended Time's planned $15 billion
merger with Warner Communications Inc. against criticism from those
he called the ``lords of leverage'' and domestic rivals that he
said were suffering ``merger envy.''
   The deal is subject to review by federal regulators and approval
by the shareholders of both companies. The Justice Department
recently announced it will not oppose the merger.
   Time is only indirectly involved in basic cable programming _
those channels cable subscribers automatically receive _ through
investments in companies such as Turner Broadcasting System Inc.,
which operates the Cable News Network and other basic cable
services.
   Time's Home Box Office Inc. subsidiary owns two premium cable TV
services, HBO and Cinemax, for which cable subscribers pay an
additional fee over their monthly charge. There have been published
reports that HBO is considering launching a comedy cable network.
   While Munro did not specifically address those reports in his
talk to the Cabletelevsion Advertising Bureau's annual conference,
he said, ``Our goal in basic (cable) is to develop a high-quality,
well-defined, differentiated service with the audience appeal of
HBO and the channel identification of CNN.''
   He noted that some critics have described the basic cable
audience as ``underpaid, overaged, out of touch.''
   But Munro said cable has changed television from a passive
medium with three main viewing choices into a responsive medium
``able to appeal to a far broader range of tastes and interests
than before.''
   He said some broadcasting executives have responded by refusing
to acknowledge the changes that have occurred in viewing habits.
   Time recognizes the networks' dilemma, Munro said, because it
faced the same situation in magazines in the late 1970s, when
regional and specialized magazines began attracting bigger
increases in ad spending than Time's mass market magazines were
seeing.
   Munro said Time faced up to market realities and built itself
into the nation's largest regional publisher.
   ``I don't want to sound like I'm making a blanket attack on
broadcast. I'm not,'' he said. He said there are a lot of ``smart
people at the networks'' who know the value and potential of cable
and are trying to get in on it.
   The National Broadcasting Co., for instance, launches a business
network on basic cable next week.
   Regarding the merger plan with Warner, Munro repeated the
dealmakers' assertions that the pact would guarantee an American
company will be among the few global giants expected to dominate
the communications business by the mid-1990s.
   He said some of Time's and Warner's domestic competitors don't
like the deal. Munro called it a ``chronic case of merger envy.''
   ``My advice to them is to save their energy to invest in finding
the kind of match that will help keep them competitive in global
markets,'' he said.
   Munro also chided ``the lords of leverage,'' who he said ``hate
the deal because it builds a new company instead of breaking up two
existing ones.''
   ``To put it politely, I think their expressed concern that
shareholders are being shortchanged by this deal resembles nothing
so much as the cat worrying about the good health of the canary,''
he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890412-0239 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-12-89 0117EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Mexico-Debt 1stLd-Writethru f0293 04-12 0423</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mexico-Debt, 1st Ld - Writethru, f0293,0432</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 2 grafs to CLARIFY that IMF money would help reduce
payments on debt to spur growth that would reduce debt. Pick up 2nd pvs,
`Significantly, the...'. Also moved on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ANDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mexico has signed an agreement with the
International Monetary Fund under which Mexico will receive up to
$3.65 billion over three years to help reduce payments on its $107
billion debt, the treasury secretary announced Tuesday.
   The goal is to reduce the net outflow of funds to provide the
investment money needed to spur growth and reduce the debt.
   Significantly, the accord stipulates that the IMF supports
Mexico's current economic austerity and modernization programs and
requires no additional austerity measures, Treasury Secretary Pedro
Aspe said.
   That means that the IMF will not require any further
devaluations of the Mexican peso, as has been called for in
previous agreements in an effort to stimulate exports, an official
said on condition of anonymity.
   ``The agreement reached with the IMF constitutes a plain
endorsement of the economic strategy of Mexico,'' Aspe said. ``The
fund has completely subscribed to this strategy.''
   The treasury chief also announced Mexico will conclude ``in the
next several days'' an agreement with the World Bank for $1.5
billion in credits to support the government's restructuring
programs.
   Aspe said the IMF agreement will promote Mexico's efforts to
reach restructuring agreements with creditor government banks.
Tuesday's accord may be extended for a fourth year at Mexico's
request.
   On April 19, Mexico will formally present to creditor banks its
proposals to reduce the foreign debt's value, cut servicing and
obtain additional lending over several years, Aspe said.
   The loan amount is $2.79 billion in Special Drawing Rights, a
denomination used by the IMF and also known as ``paper gold.'' SDRs
are a measure of a nation's reserve assets in the international
monetary system, and their value is based on an amalgam of major
currencies.
   The value in this case is $1.30 for every dollar in the reserve
assets, making the total loan worth about $3.6 billion.
   Mexican President Carlos Salinas de Gortari, who took office
Dec. 1, has pressed efforts to cut the outflow of capital needed to
revitalize Mexico's stagnant economy. Economic growth was nil last
year.
   Salinas has sought to reduce foreign debt servicing, which will
cost about $16 billion this year, and to obtain $7 billion through
lower payments and new loans each year for the next six years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
