<FIRST>r f PM-Wendy'sCampaign Bjt   04-12 0550</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wendy's Campaign, Bjt,0568</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wendy's Offers Money-Back Guarantee In Taste Test</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEITH ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wendy's International Inc. is putting its
money where its mouth is by offering customers a refund if they
don't think they've tasted the best hamburger in the business.
   The promise is part of a six-week advertising campaign in which
Wendy's, one of the nation's largest fast-food chains, proclaims
itself the winner in a taste contest with industry leader
McDonald's Corp. The ad campaign started Monday and ends in mid-May.
   Charles W. Rath, executive vice president of marketing, said the
suburban Dublin-based company favors the taste-test over a campaign
emphasizing discounts.
   ``The problem I have with discounts is that if you lower the
price, then it must have only been worth that much in the first
place,'' Rath said in an interview Tuesday. ``We've got a product
that we have a lot of confidence in its worth and its value to the
consumer. Nobody's done this before.''
   The money-back guarantee is in addition to the company's policy
of refunding money to dissatisfied customers. Under the special
offer, the company will refund the price of the hamburger to
customers who do not agree that the one they just ate was the best
in the burger business.
   Rath said the company did not estimate how much the special
refunds would cost the company.
   ``We don't think we're going to lose any more than we would on a
legitimate complaint of a product that doesn't meet our
standards,'' he said.
   Industry analyst Malcolm Knapp of the New-York based marketing
research company Malcolm Knapp Inc. called the promotion ``a great
proposition.'' He said Wendy's came out No. 1 in a taste test this
year in Restaurant and Institutions magazine.
   Knapp said the strategy will cost the company less money than
such promotions as couponing or discounts.
   ``Couponing always gives away products, for sure. And if you do
discounting, you're giving away money,'' he said.
   Knapp also said the campaign will bring more people into Wendy's
restaurants. Wendy's is virtually tied for third with Hardee's Food
Systems Inc. in size among national fast-food chains. Burger King,
a division of Pillsbury Co., is second.
   Wendy's spokesman Denny Lynch said the refund strategy was
tested in eight markets last year. ``It was never a problem,'' he
said.
   He said customers trying to abuse the offer likely will be
discovered because patrons tend to return to the same restaurant.
He also said only a few people would try to get refunds by going to
several restaurants.
   ``Is it worth it to do that for $1.39? I don't think so,'' Lynch
said.
   The advertising campaign includes a claim of taste superiority
over McDonald's.
   Wendy's contends customers surveyed at random in 1987 and 1988
preferred Wendy's hamburgers by a 2-1 ratio over those offered by
McDonald's. Rath said the company hired C.J. Research of Chicago to
conduct the surveys. About 1,500 consumers were interviewed
quarterly.
   McDonald's spokesman John Onoda was not available for comment
Tuesday and did not return a call seeking comment.
   Wendy's, with about 3,750 restaurants nationwide, has annual
sales of nearly $3 billion. It earned $28.5 million last year,
continuing to rebound from 1986, when it lost $4.9 million. The
company made $4.5 million in 1987.
</TEXT>
