<FIRST>r f PM-CorporateTax     04-12 0235</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Corporate Tax,0242</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bill Introduced To SImplify Corporate Tax</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Dan Rostenkowski, D-Ill., chairman of the
House Ways and Means Committee, has introduced a bill to simplify
the corporate minimum tax.
   Committee aides said no estimate of how the bill would affect
tax collections has been produced, nor is it clear which
industries, if any, would be hurt by the change.
   In a speech to the House, Rostenkowski said Tuesday he is open
to suggestons for changes in the bill. However, he added, ``I will
oppose any attempt to extend the arbitrary book-income preference
beyond its scheduled expiration at the end of this year.''
   The corporate minimum tax is designed to ensure that any firm
with a profit pays some tax, no matter how many deductions are
claimed. A company calculates is liability under the regular
corporate tax, figures the minimum tax and pays the larger figure.
   The 1986 tax overhaul amended the minimum levy to base the tax
in 1987 through 1989 on the concept of book income, a term normally
used in reporting profits to stockholders but not to the IRS. For
years starting in 1990, the law drops the book-income concept and
substitutes one known as ``adjusted current earnings.''
   Rostenkowski's bill would eliminate adusted current earnings as
a separate tax preference. Instead, individual items of earnings
would be treated as separate preferences, eliminating one
complicated set of calculations.
</TEXT>
