<HEAD>London Shares Slightly Firmer At Midday Amid Low Volume</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices were slightly higher Wednesday
following news of the merger between British pharmaceutical giant
Beecham Group and SmithKline Beckman Corp. of the United States.
   The new company, to be called SmithKline Beecham, would be the
second largest pharmaceutical company in the world.
   Prices surged higher at the opening, but by late morning, most
of the broad-based eurphoria from the merger dissipated, leaving
only pharmaceutical and health and household stocks alight.
   ``I think the market retreated when players decided they were
getting a little too overexcited'' by the Beecham-SmithKline
merger, one trader said.
   At midday, the Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-stock index
was 2.6 points, or 0.1 percent, higher at 2,033.9.
   The index surged as much as 14.8 points higher in early trading.
   Turnover by midday was only 227.3 million shares, compared with
322.7 million shares at the same time Tuesday.
