<FIRST>r f PM-Pritzkers-Ramada     04-12 0489</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pritzkers-Ramada,0506</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pritzkers Sell Part of Ramada Stake</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chicago's wealthy Pritzker family apparently is
abandoning a plan to buy Ramada Inc. and choosing instead to enjoy
the profits flowing from the Arizona-based hotelier's restructuring
efforts.
   HCC Corp., a Chicago company headed by Jay A. Pritzker, has
reduced its stake in Ramada to 4.8 percent from the 7.2 percent it
held when it offered last September to buy the company for $10 a
share, or about $368 million.
   Ramada rejected the proposal and embarked on a corporate
restructuring that includes the sale of its hotel and restaurant
businesses and will leave the company with three casinos in Nevada
and one in Atlantic City, N.J.
   Pritzker would not comment Tuesday on the reasons for the stock
sale, which was revealed in an April 5 filing with the Securities
and Exchange Commission.
   John Uphoff, a stock analyst who follows Ramada for Raymond
James &amp; Associates in St. Petersburg, Fla., speculated that the
Pritzkers simply saw the restructuring as a better deal.
   ``I think that when ... it became clear that the restructuring
would be completed at a price to shareholders 20 percent higher
than the Pritzkers had offered for the company, the Pritzkers
decided they would be better served by taking their profits and
letting management restructure the company,'' Uphoff said.
   He said HCC probably began buying Ramada stock at $4 to $6 a
share. The stock's price has risen from about $9 a share to nearly
$12 since the company announced its restructuring plan.
   Ramada closed Tuesday at $11.75 a share, unchanged from Monday's
close.
   HCC said in its SEC filing that it had sold 959,100 shares of
Ramada stock from March 16 through April 5 at an average price of
$11.29 a share.
   The sale leaves the Pritzkers, owners of the Hyatt hotel chain
and the industrial conglomerate Marmon Group Inc., with just under
1.9 million shares of Ramada, according to the SEC filing.
   Ramada's restructuring involves the sale of its 825 hotels and
Marie Callender's Pie Shops Inc., which it acquired in 1986.
   Ramada has already agreed to sell the restaurant business to the
Wilshire Restaurant Group Inc., a group of private investors from
New York, and expects to announce the sale of its hotel group by
mid-year, said spokesman Joe Cole from company headquarters in
Phoenix, Ariz.
   ``We haven't heard from the Pritzkers since last October so I
don't think we have any comment on what they've just done,'' Cole
said.
   Ramada will retain its hotel-casino operations: the Tropicana
resort-casino in Las Vegas, Nev.; the newly remodeled TropWorld
resort-casino in Atlantic City, N.J.; the Ramada Express
hotel-casino in Laughlin, Nev.; and Eddie's Fabulous '50s Casino in
Reno, Nev.
   Ramada reported a net loss of $5.1 million for 1988 on revenue
of $476.6 million. The hotel and restaurant operations showed a net
loss of $3.9 million for the year.
</TEXT>
