<FIRST>r f PM-BankingBid     04-12 0374</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Banking Bid,0390</SECOND>
<HEAD>War Of Words Between Banks Intensifies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NCNB Corp. has vowed to keep alive its $2.4
billion bid for Citizens &amp; Southern Corp. even though the Atlanta
banking company has rejected the offer and steadfastly refused to
negotiate.
   ``NCNB will proceed with its merger proposal,'' NCNB Chairman
Hugh L. McColl Jr. said in a statement Tuesday. ``It is time for
C&amp;S to stop posturing. The C&amp;S board should promptly begin
negotiations with us.''
   Citizens' board of directors last week rejected as inadequate
the stock-swap propsal by Charlotte, N.C.-based NCNB and said it
had no plans to discuss the offer further.
   Citizens repeated its concerns about the bid in a lengthy
statement issued Tuesday. It speculated the deal would face
numerous legal and regulatory obstacles, primarily because of
NCNB's holdings in Texas.
   NCNB took over the management of the banks of the First
RepublicBank Corp. of Dallas last year as part of a government
bailout. That bank is now called NCNB Texas National Bank.
   On Monday, Georgia Banking Commissioner Jack Dunn said the
regulatory issues involved in the deal could stretch the review
process up to 18 months.
   ``NCNB must now recognize the severe disruption and enormous
cost to both institutions that could accompany a continuation of
the NCNB bid,'' Citizens said.
   Industry analysts took note of the aggressive tone of both NCNB
and Citizens this week.
   ``They (Citizens) took the gloves off,'' said Thomas K. Brown,
an analyst with Smith Barney, Harris Upham &amp; Co. in New York. ``The
only mistake they could make is to not be aggressive enough and
look bad and regret it later.''
   But Brown added, ``I don't expect NCNB will just walk away from
it. They'll bring out their lawyers' opinions to show where they
believe C&amp;S is wrong.''
   NCNB is offering 1.075 of its shares for each of Citizens'
stock, or around $40 a share. The company has hinted it might be
willing to raise its bid by around $5 a share if Citizens agrees to
negotiations.
   The combination of the two would result in a bank with assets of
around $75 billion, placing it firmly in the top 10 among the
nation's bank holding companies.
</TEXT>
