<FIRST>r f BC-SchererFight     04-12 0245</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Scherer Fight,0255</SECOND>
<HEAD>Capsule Maker Asks For Bids</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TROY, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   R.P. Scherer Corp., whose president stepped
down in a family battle over whether to sell the company, is asking
prospective buyers to submit their bids.
   Scherer, a maker of soft gelatin capsules and other
drug-delivery systems, has been helping a number of potential
buyers conduct reviews of its finances, Ernst A. Schoepe, the
company's new president and chief executive officer said in a
letter to shareholders mailed Tuesday.
   ``We anticipate that a final agreement of sale should be
completed by the end of May, or soon thereafter,'' the letter said.
   Scherer secretary and board member Theodore Souris declined
comment on the number or identity of possible buyers, or whether
Quantum Corp., formed by former Scherer president Peter R. Fink,
was among them.
   Fink, who has said he would try to buy Scherer, did not
immediately return a telephone call.
   The Scherer board voted Sept. 30 to consider selling the company
after a battle between Fink and his estranged wife, Karla Fink,
daughter of the company's founder.
   With her brother, John S. Scherer, Karla Fink controls about 38
percent of the company. They led a group favoring sale that seated
two directors in an Aug. 17 proxy vote.
   Peter Fink stepped down as president Nov. 10.
   Scherer has 22 facilities in 13 countries and employs about
4,400 people. The company reported sales of $290.7 million in its
fiscal year ended March 31, 1988.
</TEXT>
