<FIRST>r f BC-Fujitsu-Britain     04-12 0139</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Fujitsu-Britain,0148</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fujitsu to Build Semiconductor Plant in Britain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fujitsu Ltd., a leading Japanese computer maker,
announced Wednesday it will build a $682 million semiconductor
manufacturing plant in Britain.
   The announcement said the plant's first stage will be built in
northern England by summer 1990.
   It said Fujitsu will produce one-megabit and four-megabit
dynamic random access memory chips and application specific
integrated circuits beginning in late 1990.
   A Fujitsu official, who spoke on condition of anonymity,
declined to discuss the production capacity of the plant, which is
to be expanded by 1994.
   The official said 300 workers will be hired initially for the
plant, with an increase to 1,500 by 1994.
   Fujitsu also has a semiconductor manufacturing plant in the
United States, in Oregon.
   The company has been assembling semiconductors in Dublin,
Ireland, since 1980.
</TEXT>
