<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market headed higher today, adding to
Tuesday's moderate gains.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 8.98 to 2,320.56 in
the first half hour of trading.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declines by about 7 to 5 in
nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with
533 up, 378 down and 544 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 23.60 million shares as of 10
a.m. on Wall Street.
   Analysts said hopes seemed to be building up that the market
would get some favorable news on inflation when the government
reports Friday on the producer price index of finished goods for
March.
   Wall Street estimates call for the index to show a rise of about
0.5 percent, down from 1 percent in both January and February.
   That would come as at least a tentative signal that the Federal
Reserve was seeing some results in its efforts to keep inflation in
check.
   On the other hand, if progress remains slow in the
anti-inflation campaign, brokers say fears are likely to mount that
the Fed might wind up pushing the economy into a recession with its
credit-tightening.
   Gainers among the blue chips included International Business
Machines, up | at 111}; Philip Morris, up { at 119{; DuPont, up |
at 104, and International Paper, up ] at 48.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks rose
.36 to 167.94. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was up .46 at 333.60.
   On Tuesday the Dow Jones industrial average rose 9.71 to
2,311.58.
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by about 5 to 3 on the
NYSE, with 873 issues up, 503 down and 559 unchanged.
   Big Board volume totaled 146.83 million shares, against 123.99
million in the previous session.
