<FILEID>AP-NR-04-12-89 1144EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   04-12 0312</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0324</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Advance On Bullish USDA Report</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures traded modestly higher
today on the Chicago Board of Trade following an Agriculture
Department report that indicated a higher-than-expected rate of
grain usage.
   In the report, released after the close of trading on Tuesday,
the USDA issued new year-end stockpile estimates for wheat, corn
and soybeans. All the numbers fell below expectations.
   The USDA put the U.S. corn stockpile at the beginning of the new
corn marketing year this coming Sept. 1 at 1.83 billion bushels.
   The agency pegged the U.S. wheat stockpile on June 1 at 549
million bushels and estimated the soybean carryover on Sept. 1, the
beginning of the soybean marketing year, at 145 million bushels.
   A 2-day-old dockworkers strike in Brazil is lending additional
support to the soybean market. Brazil is the world's second-largest
soybean producer after the United States.
   In early trading, wheat was 2 cents to 4{ cents higher with the
contract for delivery in May at $4.03 a bushel; corn was 1 cent to
2 cents higher with May at $2.66{ a bushel; oats were 1\ cents to
1} cents higher with May at $1.85 a bushel; soybeans were 2{ cents
to 4} cents higher with May at $7.25\ a bushel.
   Cattle futures were mixed while pork futures were moderately
higher in early trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .12 cent lower to .35 cent higher with April at
77.20 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .15 cent lower to .45 cent
higher with April at 77.10 cents a pound; live hogs were .30 cent
to .53 cent higher with April at 39.95 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .20 cent to .48 cent higher with May at 33.65 cents a
pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled mostly lower on Tuesday.
</TEXT>
