<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890412-0258 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-12-89 1200EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-S&amp;Ls 1stLd-Writethru   04-12 0850</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-S&amp;Ls, 1st Ld-Writethru,0873</SECOND>
<HEAD>EDS: Top 14 grafs new with House action, picking up 6th pvs, one
Senate. Cuts last 6 grafs pvs to tighten.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A House banking panel today amended President
Bush's savings and loan plan to encourage institutions to
concentrate on housing lending, but even supporters of the change
acknowledged it was worded in a way that could allow S&amp;Ls greater
freedom.
   The amendment, sponsored by Rep. Frank Annunzio, D-Ill., the
chairman of the House Banking subcommittee on financial
institutions, requires S&amp;Ls to concentrate 80 percent of their
lending on housing, up from the current requirement of 60 percent.
   But, it very broadly defines the types of lending that would be
used to meet the 80 percent standard to include consumer, small
businesses and education loans. It also would not penalize any
institution for its existing mix of investments, even if that did
not meet the requirement.
   ``One can have the advantage of wanting to sound pro-housing and
still know that one supports greater latitude,'' said Rep. John
LaFalce, D-N.Y., who supported the amendment.
   Annunzio said his measure ``will build homes and help revitalize
our inner cities.''
   The 26-18 vote approving it came as the subcommittee began its
third day of drafting S&amp;L legislation and the Senate Banking
Committee opened its bill-writing session.
   Tresury Secretary Nicholas Brady, in a letter today to Chairman
Don Riegle, D-Mich., called the Senate committee's recommended
changes on regulating the industry ``on balance meritorious'' but
said the administration still objects to his plan to put $50
billion of taxpayer cost in the bailout on the federal budget.
   Meanwhile, the House lawmakers are rejecting Bush's effort to
make the savings and loan industry meet the same capital
requirements as banks in return for bailing out the thrift industry.
   By a 27-16 vote, the panel adopted changes, advocated by Rep.
Stan Parris, R-Va., that would make it easier for S&amp;Ls, through
subsidiaries, to invest in such risky areas as commercial real
estate development and junk bonds.
   Rep. Jim Leach, R-Iowa, in opposing the amendment, said, ``It's
all about whether we want to support risk takers with government
guarantees.''
   On Tuesday, the subcommittee rebuffed, 24-23, Bush's insistence
on doubling the required capital base of S&amp;Ls from 3 percen to 6
percent, the same level that commercial banks have to meet.
   But then in several votes against Annunzio, it endorsed
elimination of several ``smoke and mirror'' accounting practices
that allow S&amp;L owners to meet the present capital standards with
little or no investment of their own.
   The Senate committee, before today's session, had reached a
bipartisan consensus behind closed doors ``on nearly all issues,''
according to its chairman, Sen. Don Riegle, D-Mich.
   One Senate committee member, speaking on the condition of
anonymity, predicted its version will be much tougher than whatever
emerges from the House in regulating S&amp;Ls in the future.
   But Riegle conceded in a letter to Treasury Secretary Nicholas
Brady that financing the taxpayer portion of the bailout ``remains
unresolved.'' And committee sources, speaking on the condition of
anonymity, predicted a party-line fight on the issue.
   Bush wants to raise the $50 billion immediate taxpayer share of
the bailout through 30-year bonds to be issued by a new
quasi-governmental corporation as a way to prevent the costs from
showing up on the federal deficit this year and next.
   Riegle, with support from congressional auditors and
``acquiescence'' of Senate Budget Chairman James Sasser, D-Tenn.,
wants to put the bulk of the costs in the fiscal 1989 budget,
saying it would save taxpayers $4.5 billion in lower interest costs
over three decades.
   In his letter dated Monday to Brady, Riegle said he was aware of
the treasury secretary's threat earlier this month that Bush would
veto the bill if the bailout costs are included in the 1989 or 1990
budget deficits.
   ``We have made substantial movement toward the administration's
direction on the regulatory and structural aspects but have yet to
see any flexibility from you on the funding dimension,'' he
complained.
   In the House, Rep. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., has drafted an
amendment similar to Riegle's financing scheme. But Schumer said he
is waiting for the ``appropriate time'' to introduce it, presumably
after the Senate committee has a showdown vote on the issue.
   Seven Republicans on the House panel joined 17 Democrats in the
24-23 vote Tuesday rejecting Bush's proposal to make S&amp;L owners
have $6 instead of $3 in capital for every $100 they lend out.
   Eleven Democrats sided with 12 Republicans in a failed effort to
reject the adopted alternative scheme introduced by Annunzio and
Parris.
   The Annunzio-Parris measure maintains the current 3 percent
capital floor but for the first time requires that half that amount
_ $1.50 on every $100 in loans _ be real cash investment by S&amp;L
owners that can be recovered if the thrift fails.
   Annunzio cited Federal Home Loan Bank Board estimates that 1,100
S&amp;Ls would falter under Bush's capital standards and claimed his
measure is tougher in some ways because it requires owners to put
their own money at risk.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890412-0259 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-12-89 1218EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-MinimumWage 2ndLd-Writethru   04-12 0753</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Minimum Wage, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0773</SECOND>
<HEAD>Minimum Wage Debate Continues, Amendment Process Moving Slowly</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 9 grafs with unrelated amendment tacked on to minimum
wage bill; pickup graf 4 pvs, Polls have.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate today added to legislation to
increase the minimum wage an unrelated amendment increasing by
roughly $1,000 the amount of outside income Social Security
recipients are allowed to earn before facing benefit cutbacks.
   The amendment, passed 86-11, was one of more than a dozen up for
consideration today before a final vote on the minimum-wage bill,
which calls for raising the hourly base wage from its current $3.35
to $4.55 by October 1991.
   The slow pace of the debate on amendments threatened to push the
final vote back until Thursday.
   Passage of the amendment offered by Sen. William L. Armstrong,
R-Colo., also brought the Senate bill far out of line with a
House-passed bill, meaning that after final Senate passage a
conference committee would be needed to draft a compromise.
   The current outside earnings limit is $8,880 for Social Security
recipients 65 years of age or older. After crossing that limit
recipients lose $1 of benefits for every $2 in earned income.
   The amendment would increase the limit for most of those
affected to $9,960. It would apply to Social Security recipients
between the ages of 65 and 70. The earnings limit expires after age
70.
   Most of the senators who spoke against the amendment said they
supported its goal but questioned the appropriateness of adding it
to the minimum-wage bill. They also said that benefits to thousands
of Social Security recipients likely would have to be cut to pay
for the proposal.
   The amendment is not related to the mininum wage but Senate
rules do not prohibit tacking on other proposals to legislation
being considered by the full body.
   An impasse between President Bush and the Democratic
congressional leadership that threatens prospects for a higher
minimum wage has both sides trying to convince the public the other
side is to blame.
   Bush has said he will veto the Democratic plan, a development
that could lead to a ninth consecutive year without an increase in
the minimum wage despite the first White House support this decade
for some boost.
   Polls have shown the public overwhelmingly supports an increase,
a fact not lost during the partisan wrangling.
   ``This legislation will be a test of whether we indeed are
seeking a kinder, gentler nation,'' Senate Majority Leader George
Mitchell said Tuesday, criticizing Bush for refusing to budge from
his proposal, which would raise the minimum wage from $3.35 an hour
to $4.25 an hour by January 1992.
   Mitchell said Bush's ``kinder, gentler'' campaign rhetoric is at
odds with his opposition to the Democratic bill, particularly when
the president is backing expanded tax breaks for capital gains
enjoyed largely by the nation's wealthy.
   ``How can anyone justify wanting to give $30,000-a-year tax cuts
to the richest Americans and at the same time oppose 30 cents an
hour more for the poorest Americans?'' said Mitchell, D-Maine.
``That's not right. It's wrong. It's unfair.''
   Mitchell spoke just before the Senate rejected Bush's proposal,
58-41, largely along party lines, and instead amended a bill by
Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., to bring it more in line with the
House bill. That revision was approved, 61-39.
   The administration fired back quickly, with Labor Secretary
Elizabeth Dole raising the prospect that the partisan squabbling
would result in no increase in the minimum wage this year.
   ``Democrats have no one to blame but themselves,'' Mrs. Dole
said. ``The Democrats decided they'd rather fight than win.
Unfortunately, the people who really lose are the ones who can
least afford it.''
   In addition to favoring a smaller increase in the general
minimum wage, Bush has insisted on letting employers pay new
workers a sub-minimum ``training wage.'' Democrats, who long
opposed a sub-minimum, agreed this year to include one in their
proposal in hopes of making it more acceptable to the
administration.
   The Kennedy bill, as amended, contains a provision allowing
employers to pay new workers a sub-minimum wage for up to 60 days;
Bush has insisted on a six-month training wage.
   Republicans, however, are confident a veto can be upheld and are
in no mood for a compromise on the overall dispute.
   ``There isn't going to be a compromise,'' said Senate Republican
leader Bob Dole of Kansas. ``It's going to be $4.25 an hour and a
six-month training wage, period.''
</TEXT>
