<FILEID>AP-NR-04-12-89 1241EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Apollo-Hewlett-Packard     04-12 0412</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Apollo-Hewlett-Packard,0427</SECOND>
<HEAD>HP To By Apollo Computer In Grab For Workstation Market</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PALO ALTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hewlett-Packard Co. announced today it
will buy Apollo Computer Inc., a pioneer in the engineering
workstation market, for $476 million in cash.
   The purchase of Apollo by Hewlett-Packard, a manufacturer of
computers and scientific equipment, continues its push into the
$3.8 billion workstation market.
   Under the agreement, Hewlett-Packard will offer $13.25 per share
for Apollo's estimated 36 million shares of common stock
outstanding and will begin its tender offer within five business
days.
   The companies' board of directors unanimously approved the
definitive agreement that will merge two players in the engineering
workstation market, the fastest-growing area of the computer
industry.
   Workstations are single-user computers that resemble personal
computers but are usually faster and have larger screens with
better graphics. They were originally used mostly by scientists and
engineers.
   But the use of workstations, which range in price from $5,000 to
$100,000, has spread to other professions such as financial
analysis.
   Apollo, a Fortune 500 company founded in 1980 and based in
Chelmsford, Mass., pioneered engineering workstations but fell
behind Sun Microsystems Inc. in the rapidly growing market. The
company squeezed out a profit of $2.1 million last year on sales of
$654 million, although it lost money in its second and third
quarters.
   After the second-quarter loss, which surprised analysts, Roland
D. Pampel resigned as president to become president of Bull HN
Information Systems Inc.
   Apollo's stock had risen earlier this year on speculation that
it might be taken over, possibly by Bull HN Information. But the
stock drifted back as the speculation faded. Apollo closed
unchanged at $8.12{ a share Tuesday in over-the-counter trading.
   Palo Alto-based Hewlett-Packard entered its 50th year of
business in 1989 following a financially rosy 1988 when it reported
a 27 percent jump in net income, a 34 percent rise in earnings per
share and revenue of $9.8 billion.
   ``HP and Apollo together represent an ideal blending of product
strengths and business strategies,'' said John A. Young,
Hewlett-Packard president and chief executive officer. ``Both
companies are recognized for technical innovation and high-quality
computer products, and for a commitment to the industry's move
toward cooperative-computing environments based on open industry
standards.''
   The acquisition is agreement is subject to regulatory approval
and the expiration of waiting periods.
   ``Apollo is extremely pleased to join forces with one of the
industry's outstanding organizations,'' said Thomas A. Vanderslice,
Apollo's chairman and chief executive officer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
