<FIRST>a f BC-LoewenbraeuExports Adv15-16   04-12 0542</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Loewenbraeu Exports, Adv 15-16,0560</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv15</HEAD>
<HEAD>$adv16</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release weekend editions April 15-16</HEAD>
<HEAD>Famous Munich Beer Maker May Restart Direct Exports of Renowned Brew</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN COSTELLOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MUNICH, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Loewenbraeu company of Munich,
one of West Germany's best-known beer-makers with origins that date
to the 14th century, is considering direct exports to the United
States after watching falling sales of its licensed brew in America.
   But Loewenbraeu general manager and director Peter Wiedemann
emphasizes direct export is just one option under consideration,
and praises the cooperation with licensing partner Miller Brewing
Co. of Milwaukee.
   ``We have an excellent business and personal relationship with
Miller,'' Wiedemann emphasized in an interview with The Associated
Press. But he said that in an effort to raise flagging sales,
``among the various options that we have, there could also possibly
be the resumption of direct exports.''
   He confirmed published reports that annual sales of the licensed
Loewenbraeu on the American market, which began under a pact made
in the early 1970s, has dropped by nearly a third since then.
   Fritz Kuhn, a Loewenbraeu spokesman, said the licensed product
is brewed in Miller-run U.S. breweries. Direct exports means
Loewenbraeu would ship its beer made in West Germany to the United
States.
   The remarks by Wiedemann and Kuhn appeared to surprise officials
at Miller, a leading American brewer, which has a contract with
Loewenbraeu that runs through 1992.
   ``Quite frankly, I'm really puzzled by what they said,'' said
Beverly Jurkowski, a Miller spokeswoman reached by telephone. ``The
very nature of that contract would prevent some of those other
options from taking place.''
   She said Miller and Loewenbraeu officials conferred in February,
a meeting she said the West German company found highly encouraging.
   The Lowenbraeu general manager suggested that in the future,
both companies might collaborate on direct exports of Loewenbraeu
to the United States. He declined to be more specific.
   Loewenbraeu already has formed a company in Boston, Loewenbraeu
Marketing Corp., to study the possibility of direct exports and to
look into other possibilities in the United States, Wiedemann said.
   ``Because our sales in the United States are down, we must
undertake decisive strategy changes,'' the Loewenbraeu executive
said.
   He acknowledged that the higher price for export beer is one
consideration weighed by officials of the 606-year-old brewery.
   The general manager noted Loewenbraeu is considering the
purchase of a brewing facility on West Germany's northern coast,
near seaports and much closer to the United States than the current
facilities deep in southern Bavaria.
   ``That way we don't just have North America as a possible
market, we also have a substantial export business in the whole
world,'' Wiedemann said.
   He added: ``The beer we would brew there, if in fact we buy a
brewery, would be made according to the same recipe as we have here
in Munich.''
   The northern facility also could figure into Loewenbraeu's plans
to become a dominant brand within this country of 61.3 million
people.
   ``Among the approximately 1,150 breweries now in Germany, there
is none with a market share of more than 5 percent. There are so
many suppliers, and there is no truly national brand,'' he said.
   End adv for weekend editions April 15-16
</TEXT>
</DOC>
