<DOCNO> AP890412-0267 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-12-89 1800EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Earns-FannieMae     04-12 0194</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Earns-Fannie Mae,0200</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fannie Mae Reports First Quarter Net Income</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal National Mortgage Association, the
largest investor in home mortgages, on Wednesday reported a 65
percent rise in its first quarter income over a year ago.
   For the January-March period, the government-sponsored,
privately owned corporation known as Fannie Mae, said it earned
$165.2 million, or $1.98 a share. That compared with net income of
$100.9 million, or $1.27 a share, last year.
   David O. Maxwell, Fannie Mae's chairman and chief executive
officer, said earnings rose despite higher interest rates and the
$8 million cost to phase out the company's Software Systems
division.
   He said that as a result of a declining inventory of foreclosed
properties, the company last quarter reduced its provision for
losses to $80 million, down from $85 million in the fourth quarter.
   Roger E. Birk, the company's president and chief operating
officer, said that contributing to the improved performance last
quarter were an increase in the spread between the yield on the
company's investment portfolio and the cost of its outstanding
debt, the lower loss provision, and continued growth in guaranty
fee income from mortgage-backed securities.
</TEXT>
