<FILEID>AP-NR-04-12-89 1522EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   04-12 0235</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0245</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wheat Futures Surge On Soviet Rumors, Bullish USDA Report</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most grain and soybean futures prices closed
higher Wednesday on the Chicago Board of Trade amid rumors of new
Soviet buying interest in the wheat market.
   But oat futures retreated, reflecting the abundance of foreign
oats available on the U.S. market.
   Crop futures were buoyed early in the session by an Agriculture
Department report indicating the nation's grain stockpiles were
declining more rapidly than most analysts had believed.
   Rumors surfaced at midday that the Soviet Union was eyeing new
purchases of U.S. wheat, which would be a significant development
because the Soviets have already purchased all the U.S. wheat
earmarked for sale to them this year at subsidized prices.
   The moderate decline in oat futures was overdue, said Jay Homan,
an independent oat trader in Chicago.
   ``We've needed to divorce ourselves from the strength of the
other grain markets,'' he said. ``There's a scarcity of American
oats but an abundance of foreign oats.''
   At the close, wheat was 2{ cents to 7{ cents higher with the
contract for delivery in May at $4.03{ a bushel; corn was 2\ cents
to 3{ cents higher with May at $2.67} a bushel; oats were 1} cents
to 4{ cents lower with May at $1.79 a bushel; soybeans were 2 cents
to 6{ cents higher with May at $7.27 a bushel.
</TEXT>
