<DOCNO> AP890412-0270 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-12-89 1523EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f BC-Earns-Banks     04-12 0204</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Banks,0215</SECOND>
<HEAD>J.P. Morgan Announces Drop In Quarterly Income</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   J.P. Morgan &amp; Co., the nation's fourth largest
bank holding company, on Wednesday reported a 36 percent drop in
its first quarter profit over a year ago.
   The company said it netted $180 million, or 96 cents a share,
for the three months ended March 30, compared with earnings of $280
million, or $1.52 per share, in the 1988 period.
   The first quarter of 1988 included a gain of $43 million related
to a federal tax refund.
   Chairman Lewis T. Preston attributed the decline largely to the
rise in worldwide interest rates over the past year, which he said
limited opportunities in areas such currency and securities trading.
   Most effected was net interest income, which tumbled to $299
million in the first quarter from $438 million a year ago.
   Total non-interest income also declined, to $394 million from
$435 million, while non-interest expenses eased to $436 million
from $511 million.
   Morgan allowed less for credit losses during first quarter, $10
million against $50 million a year ago. It said total allowances
from such losses, including loans to Third World countries, was
$1.49 billion, during the quarter, down from $1.57 billion.
</TEXT>
