<DOCNO> AP890412-0271 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-12-89 2007EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Raytheon     04-12 0257</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Raytheon,0268</SECOND>
<HEAD>Raytheon Profits Rise 6.6 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LEXINGTON, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Raytheon Co., the defense contractor and
appliance maker, said Wednesday its earnings rose 6.6 percent in
the first three months of 1989.
   The Lexington-based company said its revenues increased 6.4
percent as strong sales of defense electronics, major appliances
and other products offset a drop in aircraft purchases by the
government.
   Because of stock repurchases, Raytheon said its earnings per
share were up 8.9 percent.
   Raytheon reported net income for the quarter of $120.8 million,
or $1.83 per share, on sales of $2.07 billion. That compares with
net income of $113.3 million, or $1.68 per share, on sales of $1.95
billion in the first quarter of 1988.
   Chairman Thomas L. Phillips said all five of the company's
business sectors were profitable during the quarter. Those sectors
are electronics, aircraft, energy services, appliances and other
products.
   Although aircraft sales were down, Raytheon said the sector's
earnings were up as its Beech division, which makes both military
and civilian planes, improved its profit margins.
   Raytheon said its electronics sector, which accounted for 51
percent of revenues last year, was led by the Missile Systems
Division, which produces Hawk, Sparrow, Sidewinder and other
sophisticated missiles.
   The appliance sector, including Amana refrigerators, Caloric
ranges and Speed Queen washers, had growth in sales but a decline
in profits as competition squeezed margins, the company said.
   Raytheon has 76,100 employees worldwide, including 30,700 in
Massachusetts, second only to Digital Equipment Corp., the
Maynard-based computer manufacturer with 35,000 workers in the
state.
</TEXT>
