<FIRST>r f AM-Fairchild-Carlyle     04-12 0271</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fairchild-Carlyle,0285</SECOND>
<HEAD>Carlyle Sweetens Offer for Fairchild Again</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Carlyle Group continued its pursuit of
Fairchild Industries Inc. Wednesday, sweetening its offer for the
aerospace electronics company to $243.7 million.
   It was the second time Carlyle has raised its offer for
Fairchild, which has rejected the investment partnership's previous
bids.
   Carlyle said it would pay $17 for each of Fairchild's14.3
million outstanding shares, up from $16.30 per share, or a total of
$233.7 million.
   Fairchild Secretary John Jackson said the bid was being
evaluated.
   Fairchild stock was up $1.50 in late New York Stock Exchange
trading Wednesday to $15.12{ a share.
   Carlyle, which owns about 14.8 percent of Fairchild stock,
originally offered $15.50 per share, or $222.2 million, for the
firm.
   Stephen Norris, a managing director of Carlyle, has said that
taking Fairchild private would be in the best interests of the firm.
   Carlyle has no intention of breaking up the company, Norris has
stated.
   If completed, the takeover would be the biggest acquisition to
date by Carlyle, which was founded less than two years ago. It has
aggressively pursued a series of friendly takeovers, and last year
bought Oakite Products Inc., a New Jersey chemical company, in
partnership with a French bank.
   One of the principals in Carlyle is former Defense Secretary
Frank Carlucci, who has been involved in the negotiations by former
baseball commissioner Peter Ueberroth to buy Eastern Airlines.
   A Fairchild unit, Vol-San-Chatsworth, was accused recently of
non-compliance with required testing procedures. The FBI has said
it was investigating Vol-Shan for what it called possible
falsification of quality control records at the California plant.
</TEXT>
