<FILEID>AP-NR-04-12-89 2118EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Westinghouse     04-12 0209</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Westinghouse,0220</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sales, Income Set Records</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Westinghouse Electric Corp. said Wednesday its
first-quarter profits rose 5 percent as its sales at a similar pace.
   Westinghouse said it earned $189 million, or $1.30 per share, up
from $180.5 million, or $1.25 per share, in the first three months
of 1988.
   Sales were up 5.5 percent to nearly $2.9 billion from $2.75
billion.
   The results included a $261.5 million charge as the cost of
restructuring its manufacturing operations. The charge offset gains
from the sale of the Westinghouse elevator business and the
formation of a joint venture in electricity transmission and
distribution.
   Westinghouse, the nation's leading builder of nuclear power
plants, said its energy and utility division made key contributions
to an 11 percent increase in operating profits.
   The division's gains came primarily on sales of nuclear fuel,
energy systems and transmission and distribution business.
   Operating profits rose from $253.4 million a year earlier to
$281.2 million.
   ``The earnings improvement for the quarter, combined with a
strong rate of orders and a solid backlog of $11 billion, are
positive signs for the continuing progress of the corporation,''
Chairman John C. Marous said in a printed statement.
   Westinghouse also has broadcasting, financial services,
industrial, electronics and commercial businesses.
</TEXT>
