<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     04-12 0454</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Mixed, Gold Rise</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON-BC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar ended mixed against major currencies
in U.S. trading Wednesday after increasing slightly abroad.
   Gold prices rose. Republic National Bank of New York quoted a
bid of $387 for a troy ounce of gold, up $2.10 from Tuesday's late
bid.
   Trading activity was kept in check by speculation about possible
central bank intervention and reluctance on the part of dealers to
take major new positions ahead of U.S. government reports on retail
sales Thursday and merchandise trade and producer prices Friday.
   A dealer at a major Japanese bank in London said traders ``are
ultra-cautious and reluctant to test the central bank's resolve
until the release of the data later this week,'' Political
difficulties for the governments in Japan and West Germany caused
some dealers to sell yen and marks, which helped strengthen the
dollar marginally.
   The dollar began its trading day in Tokyo with a rise of 0.23
Japanese yen to a closing level of 132.85 yen. Later, in London, it
was trading higher at 132.95 yen and in New York it finished at
133.025, up from 132.705 Tuesday.
   In London, the dollar gained against the British pound. It cost
$1.6925 to buy one pound compared with $1.6995 late Tuesday. By the
time trading was done for the day in New York, the pound fetched
$1.69215 vs. $1.6910 Tuesday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with Tuesday's
late rates, included: 1.88275 West German marks, down from 1.88525;
1.66475 Swiss francs, up from 1.66375; 6.3615 French francs, down
from 6.3655; 1,380.50 Italian lire, down from 1,381.375; and,
1.18955 Canadian dollars, up from 1.18945.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Tuesday:
1.8857 West German marks, up from 1.8825; 1.6645 Swiss francs, up
from 1.6582; 6.3690 French francs, up from 6.3535; 2.1270 Dutch
guilders, up from 2.1225; 1,381.00 Italian lire, up from 1,379.25;
1.1887 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1888.
   Gold bullion prices strengthened in trading at home and abroad.
   In New York, a troy ounce of gold for current delivery ended at
$388.20 a troy ounce on the Commodity Exchange, up from Tuesday's
$385.80.
   Gold rose in London to a late bid price of $387.25 a troy ounce,
compared with late Tuesday's $385.25.
   In Zurich, gold was higher, closing at a bid $387.30 compared
with $385.00 late Tuesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $1.29 to close at a bid $385.08.
   Silver bullion prices rose on the London market where the metal
was trading at a late bid price of $5.89 a troy ounce, compared
with Tuesday's $5.84.
   Silver for April delivery rose on New York's Comex, settling at
$5.868 a troy ounce, up from $5.834 on Tuesday.
</TEXT>
