<FILEID>AP-NR-04-12-89 1844EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-SmithKline-Beecham Bjt   04-12 0711</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SmithKline-Beecham, Bjt,0739</SECOND>
<HEAD>SmithKline, Beecham Plan To Merge Into World's Second-Largest Drug
Company</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ERICH SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   SmithKline Beckman Corp. and Britain's
Beecham Group PLC announced Wednesday they would merge and form the
world's second-largest pharmaceutical company, but a Wall Street
analyst warned that either firm could find itself a takeover target
before the transaction is completed.
   SmithKline and Beecham, who confirmed earlier this month they
were negotiating on a merger, said they would exchange stock and
establish a pharmaceutical and health care giant with estimated
sales of $6.7 billion.
   The new company, to be named SmithKline Beecham, would rank
second in worldwide pharmaceutical sales behind Merck &amp; Co., second
in over-the-counter medicines behind American Home Products Corp.
and fourth in animal health.
   The firm will have a research and development budget of more
than $500 million per year, SmithKline Chairman Henry Wendt said at
a news conference.
   ``We will have one of the best and largest research and
development organizations in the world, drawing on the scientific
skills and traditions of the United States and Britain,'' he said.
   Under the merger agreement, SmithKline shareholders would
receive five ``B'' shares of stock in the new company for each of
their old shares, and Beecham shareholders would receive slightly
less than one ``A'' share for each of their old shares.
   The new shares would have equal voting rights in the affairs of
SmithKline Beecham but dividends paid to each ``A'' share would be
about five times the dividends paid to each ``B'' share.
   SmithKline currently has some 133 million shares outstanding and
Beecham has about 768 million shares outstanding.
   Two SmithKline subsidiaries, Allergan, an eye- and skin-care
business, and 84 percent of Beckman Instruments, which makes
diagnostic and laboratory equipment, would be spun off to
SmithKline shareholders, the companies said in a joint statement.
SmithKline last fall sold 16 percent of Beckman through a public
stock offering.
   Beecham plans to sell off its cosmetics and fragrance divisions,
plus other non-pharmaceutical businesses, officials said.
   SmithKline shareholders would receive a one-time cash dividend
of $5.50 per share. They also would get about half a share of
Allergan and about 0.18 shares of SmithKline stock for each
SmithKline share, according to a news release.
   The merger would be subject to governmental approval and a vote
by shareholders of both companies.
   SmithKline stock fell $2 in New York Stock Exchange composite
trading Wednesday, closing at $62.75 a share.
   A financial analyst specializing in pharmaceutical companies
said the merger announcement could draw new bids for either company
before stockholders vote four months from now.
   ``To quote Yogi Berra, `It isn't over till it's over,''' said
Ron Nordmann of PaineWebber Group Inc. in New York. ``I think
that's why they attempted to announce this deal in all due haste.''
   Other companies mentioned as possible suitors for SmithKline are
Hoffman-La Roche &amp; Co., Nestle SA, Imperial Chemical Industries and
Du Pont Co.
   Wendt said SmithKline had received no other offers.
   ``There have been no feelers, no nudges, no cloakroom
conversations,'' he said when pressed on the question.
   But Normann said the announcement could change the situation.
   ``Think how short the concept of this merger has been in the
public domain,'' he said. ``And its such a large deal _ $11 to $13
billion, depending on what you think about the pieces. ...
   ``Now, X, Y, Z, who ever that might be, knows exactly what the
terms are that they have to top.''
   Wendt, 55, chairman and chief executive officer of SmithKline,
would become chairman of SmithKline Beecham, and Robert Bauman,
chairman of Beecham, would become chief executive officer of the
new company.
   The two companies executed agreements Wednesday to co-promote
several products, including SmithKline's popular ulcer drug
Tagamet. Beecham was granted a license to sell the drug under its
own brand name.
   Beecham, which makes Tums antacid pills, is particulary
interested in developing an over-the-counter version of Tagamet,
Bauman said.
   ``Building on the `Tums' franchise, an over-the-counter
formulation of `Tagamet' has the potential to become a global
brand,'' he said in a statement released by SmithKline.
   SmithKline reported total sales of $4.7 billion in 1988, while
Beecham's sales exceeded $4 billion.
   The new company would be based in London with offices in
Philadelphia.
</TEXT>
