<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     04-12 0239</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0249</SECOND>
<HEAD>Energy Prices Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gasoline futures prices surged higher in
moderate trading Wednesday, fueled by rising consumer demand.
   Strength in the gasoline pits helped push crude prices up, while
heating oil had a weaker day.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, unleaded gasoline for May
delivery rose 1.11 cents to 70.11 cents a gallon. Most other
contract months were higher.
   The May contract for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark
grade of U.S. crude, edged up 1 penny to close the day at $20.64 a
barrel. June and July showed no gains or losses while other months
rose between 2 cents and 10 cents a barrel.
   Heating oil for May delivery declined .03 cent to 53.20 cents a
gallon with other contract months mixed.
   Analysts said world demand for gasoline is continuing strong in
the wake of the Alaskan oil spill nearly three weeks ago.
   ``A lot of strength is coming out of Europe,'' said Jim Fiedler,
analyst with E.D.&amp;F. Man International Futures Inc. ``Europe had a
mild winter and people have been driving more.''
   In addition, new anti-pollution regulations in Europe also are
affecting demand, analysts said.
   Contributing to the weakness in crude prices was a weekly report
by the American Petroleum Institute showing a 500,000-barrel
increase in crude inventories for the week ending April 7. Market
participants had expected a sharp downturn in inventories because
of the Alaskan spill, traders said.
</TEXT>
