<DOCNO> AP890412-0281 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-12-89 1845EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     04-12 0707</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0733</SECOND>
<HEAD>Palladium Cracks $170, A 5{-Year High, On Fusion Reports</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Palladium futures prices surged to their highest level in nearly
5{ years Wednesday on New York's Mercantile Exchange amid optimism
that recent nuclear fusion experiments could spur demand for the
metal as an ingredient in the power plants of tomorrow.
   Other precious-metal futures prices also advanced.
   On other markets, cocoa futures plunged; gasoline prices rose
but other energy futures were mixed; grains and soybeans were
mostly higher; and livestock and meat futures were mixed.
   Palladium settled $4.40 to $5.15 higher with the contract for
delivery in June at $173.65 a troy ounce. The move marked
palladium's first foray above $170 since December 1983, when the
metal reached nearly $180 a troy ounce.
   Palladium prices have risen in 10 of the 13 trading sessions
since March 23, when two chemists announced they had achieved
nuclear fusion at room temperature using palladium as a catalyst in
an experiment at the University of Utah.
   Fusion is the joining together of hydrogen atoms to produce
enormous amounts of energy. It is the process that powers the sun
and stars, and scientists seeking a cheap energy source have long
sought to harness it.
   Last week, palladium for June delivery went as high as $169 an
ounce only to collapse on Friday amid skepticism about the Utah
findings.
   But on Monday, researchers at Texas A&amp;M and Georgia Tech
announced they had replicated at least part of the University of
Utah results, bringing new buyers into the usually quiet palladium
market.
   Some of the buying interest in palladium spilled over into the
platinum market Wednesday.
   ``The rally in palladium created a psychological environment
which was conducive to rallies in the other precious metals,'' said
George Anagnos, an analyst with Thomson McKinnon Securities Inc. in
New York.
   But analysts said the moderate rise in gold and silver futures
was more likely a response to inflation jitters and signs that the
dollar's recent strength has peaked.
   Platinum settled $3.30 to $3.80 higher on the New York Merc with
May at $531.80 a troy ounce. On New York's Commodity Exchange, gold
settled $2.20 to $2.40 higher with June at $392.10 a troy ounce;
silver was 3.2 cents to 4.2 cents higher with May at $5.895 a troy
ounce.
   Cocoa futures plummeted on New York's Coffee, Sugar &amp; Cocoa
Exchange on rumors that the Ivory Coast, the world's largest cocoa
producer, had sold an unknown quantity of cocoa through the Swiss
trade house Intercafco, which denied any such deal.
   Cocoa settled $30 to $56 lower with May at $1,272 per metric ton.
   Unleaded gasoline futures rose sharply for the fourth straight
day on supply concerns. The crude- and heating-oil market were
quiet.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled unchanged to 6 cents
higher with May at $20.64 a barrel; heating oil was unchanged to 5
cents lower with May at 53.20 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was
.20 cent lower to 1.11 cents higher with May at 70.11 cents a
gallon.
   Most grain and soybean futures prices rose on the Chicago Board
of Trade amid rumors of new Soviet buying interest in the wheat
market.
   But oat futures retreated, reflecting the abundance of foreign
oats available on the U.S. market.
   Wheat settled 2 cents to 6} cents higher with May at $4.03 a
bushel; corn was 2\ cents to 3{ cents higher with May at $2.67} a
bushel; oats were 1} cents to 4{ cents lower with May at $1.79 a
bushel; soybeans were 2 cents to 7 cents higher with May at $7.27{
a bushel.
   On the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, weak cash markets and
profit-taking weighed on the cattle futures while pork futures
advanced on ideas that farmers soon will be busy with spring
planting and will be marketing fewer hogs.
   Live cattle settled .87 cent lower to .60 cent higher with April
at 76.45 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .12 cent to .93 cent
lower with April at 76.40 cents a pound; live hogs were .12 cent to
.38 cent higher with April at 39.95 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .20 cent lower to .28 cent higher with May at 33.30
cents a pound.
</TEXT>
