<FILEID>AP-NR-04-12-89 2300EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Mexico-Banks     04-12 0341</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Mexico-Banks,0358</SECOND>
<HEAD>IMF Loan Could Bolster Mexico's Standing In Talks With Commercial
Banks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mexico's latest $3.65 billion loan from the
International Monetary Fund will likely improve its standing in
upcoming debt restructuring talks with commercial bank creditors,
bank executives said Wednesday.
   Negotiations between the country and a 13-member bank committee
are set to begin April 19 in New York.
   At that time, Mexico will formally propose a reduction in the
value of its foreign debt, a cut in servicing and additional
lending over several years, according to Mexican Treasury Secretary
Pedro Aspe.
   He said Mexico will offer banks the option of exchanging old
debt for Mexican bonds that discount debt principal and reduce
interest rates.
   Mexico, struggling to overcome the burden of payments to
commercial banks and governments on its $107 billion foreign debt,
is the developing world's second-largest debtor behind Brazil,
which owes $121 billion.
   The three-year agreement reached with the IMF on Tuesday is the
first from the international lending community since Treasury
Secretary Nicholas Brady outlined a debt-reduction plan last month
that he hoped would help ease payment terms on the developing
world's $1.32 trillion foreign debt.
   William R. Rhodes, a Citicorp vice president, said the IMF pact
``is a positive signal as it forms an important part of Mexico's
economic program.''
   ``It will help facilitate negotiations with the bank advisory
group'' next week, he said in a statement.
   The $3.65 billion IMF loan will be used to bolster the country's
foreign exchange reserves and spur economic development.
   Aspe said the agreement ``is a fundamental change from the
past,'' since the IMF recognizes Mexico's need to set its growth
priorities first and schedule debt servicing accordingly.
   Many bankers agreed that the pact amounted to an endorsement of
Mexico's economic policies, which included tough inflation-fighting
programs.
   ``Mexico is a country that has made significant progress. It
deserves whatever kind of special treatment might be meted out,''
said Lloyd Atkinson, chief economist for the Bank of Montreal and
an advisor to the bank creditors committee.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890412-0283 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-12-89 2309EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Citibank-Discrimination     04-12 0315</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Citibank-Discrimination,0326</SECOND>
<HEAD>Settlement of Citibank Case Reached</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Justice Department announced Wednesday
that it settled allegations that Citibank New York discriminated
against foreign-born job applicants.
   The issue was raised by the Center for Immigrants' Rights, which
brought the charges on behalf of a job applicant who wished to
remain anonymous, said Lawrence Siskind of the department's Office
of Special Counsel.
   The center alleged that Citibank was requiring that foreign-born
applicants for bank tellers show ``green cards,'' known formally as
alien registration cards, even though they already had provided
adequate documentation to satisfy the requirements of the
Immigration Reform and Control Act of 1986.
   That act, among other things, required employers to ensure that
they did not hire illegal aliens, and threatened them with fines if
they failed to do so.
   ``In the case of Citibank, it was discriminating against
foreign-born employees by forcing them to produce documents that it
wasn't forcing its other employees to produce,'' Siskind said.
   The INS deems drivers licenses, school identity cards with
photographs, voter registration cards and draft cards, among other
documents, as sufficient to establish identity.
   Although the allegation against Citibank focused on just one
individual, Siskind said, ``We did learn that they had been doing
it as a policy. They had instructed their personnel people to do
that, but as soon as we began our investigation and informed them
of the law, they agreed to stop the policy.''
   The investigation began Jan. 27 and was settled Monday, he said.
   In the settlement, Citibank agreed to accept any and all
documents allowed by the INS to satisfy the requirement that the
person is eligible for employment and agreed to treat all
applicants and employees the same. It will not pay any fine to the
government or any back pay to the affected individual, who was
subsequently hired, Siskind said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
