<FIRST>r f AM-AndersenExecs     04-12 0427</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Andersen Execs,0442</SECOND>
<HEAD>Big Eight Accounting Firm Names Heads of Restructured Business Units</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Arthur Andersen &amp; Co.'s new chief executive
announced the heads of the accounting giant's restructured
operations Wednesday and said he was eager to pursue more business
after a tumultuous year.
   Lawrence A. Weinbach, confirmed last week to head the firm, said
the restructuring has created a consulting unit that will operate
independently and on an equal basis with its accounting, audit and
tax business unit.
   The consulting practice will be headed by George T. Shaheen, 44,
who had headed its North American consulting business. He had
previously been the southeast regional managing partner.
   The accounting, audit and tax practice will be headed by Richard
L. Measelle, 50, who had previously been managing partner for
worldwide accounting and audit practice. He has worked in
Andersen's offices in Detroit and Spain.
   Both will report to Weinbach.
   ``The good news is that we have completed our restructuring,
successfully gaining consensus among our partners worldwide and we
are moving aggressively forward,'' Weinbach said.
   He said 89 percent of the partners voting on the restructuring
approved it.
   Weinbach, 49, a 28-year veteran of firm who worked his way up
through the accounting side, was nominated last month and approved
last week to succeed Duane A. Kullberg as managing partner and
chief executive of Arthur Andersen, a privately-held firm based in
Chicago.
   Kullberg announced in January he was stepping down after nine
years as head of Andersen to help give the firm a new start as it
embarked on a restructuring designed partly to end a rift between
its accounting division and its more rapidly-growing management
information consulting division.
   The consulting business accounted for roughly 40 percent of the
firm's $2.8 billion in revenue last year. Weinbach said revenue
from from consulting rose more than 30 percent last year, while its
revenue from its tax practice was up 20 percent and audit and
accounting revenue rose 14 percent.
   ``This organization is back to work,'' Weinbach said, adding the
firm could once again focus full attention on competing in the
marketplace.
   Under questioning, he said the firm has lost no clients but said
it may not have capitalized on marketplace opportunities.
   During the past year, Andersen has been rocked by the defections
of six consulting partners, who have set up their own consulting
business with assistance from the London-based advertising giant
Saatchi &amp; Saatchi PLC.
   Andersen and Information Consulting Group Inc., the firm formed
by Andersen's former partners, are suing each other, each claiming
business interference.
</TEXT>
