<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Motorola     04-12 0245</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Motorola,0256</SECOND>
<HEAD>Motorola Profit Up Nearly 8 Percent In First Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SCHAUMBURG, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Motorola Inc. reported a 7.9 percent
gain in first-quarter profit Wednesday, citing the continued rapid
growth of its computer chip and cellular telephone businesses.
   Motorola reported a profit of $123 million, or 95 cents a share,
for the three months ending April 1, compared with $114 million, or
88 cents a share, for the same period in 1988.
   Motorola's sales for the first quarter totaled $2.18 billion, up
11 percent from the $1.96 billion in the first quarter of 1988, the
Schaumburg-based company said.
   The company said both the sales and earnings figures were record
highs for a first quarter.
   Motorola said lower profits in its communications group, which
produces two-way radio and paging equipment, were more than offset
by higher profits in its semiconductor and general-systems groups.
   Chairman Robert W. Galvin expressed confidence that the
company's growth would continue.
   ``Significant product introductions, combined with steadily
increasing levels of quality and customer satisfaction, give us the
opportunity to gain greater shares of global markets,'' he said.
   During the quarter the semiconductor unit unveiled its new 68040
microprocessor, the first computer chip to contain more than 1.2
million transistors. The division enjoyed an 11 percent sales
increase during the first quarter.
   The general systems group saw its sales jump 58 percent, due
largely to continued strong orders for Motorola's cellular
telephone equipment and the introduction of several new computer
products.
