<DOCNO> AP890412-0290 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-12-89 2224EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Eastern 5thLd-Writethru   04-12 1181</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern, 5th Ld-Writethru,1218</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ueberroth Deal Collapses; Icahn Still Interested</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS 13th graf pvs to CORRECT Shapiro's first name to David;
picks up 14th graf pvs bg'ng, Texas Air ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Peter V. Ueberroth's proposed $464 million
purchase of strike-bound Eastern Airlines collapsed Wednesday but a
federal bankruptcy judge immediately moved to attract new buyers
for the carrier.
   The former baseball commissioner told a news conference his deal
fell through following an impasse Tuesday night with Eastern's
unions and its parent Texas Air Corp.
   ``We are extremely disappointed this transaction collapsed last
night and is done,'' Ueberroth told a news conference. ``Our
agreement with Texas Air is terminated, it's finished, it's over.''
   His announcement squelched a stunning but short-lived effort to
buy one of the nation's most unprofitable and strife-ridden
airlines, which has been mired in an emotional strike and
bankruptcy proceedings for more than a month.
   Eastern President Phil Bakes said the Miami-based airline's
strategy now was to reorganize as a smaller carrier serving roughly
50 percent to 60 percent of its pre-strike schedule of 1,040
flights a day and employing some 15,000 to 18,000 people, compared
with 31,000 before the strike.
   Bakes refused to answer whether the airline would consider new
buyout offers. He denied that a competing offer had been made by
Trans World Airlines Chairman Carl Icahn, who nevertheless has
indicated he remained interested.
   But shortly after the announcement, U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Burton
R. Lifland ordered the parties involved in the sale to show why he
should not throw the airline open to all bidders _ and include with
it certain assets Texas Air has bought or transferred from Eastern
since acquiring it in 1986.
   The order is based on a petition by an Eastern creditor, Atlanta
attorney Moreton Rolleston Jr., that seeks to block the sale of
Eastern's Northeast shuttle for $365 million to developer Donald
Trump.
   The petition also seeks to require that any purchase of Eastern
be for $615 million, the amount Texas Air paid for it in 1986;
include all of its System One computerized reservation system,
which it sold to Texas Air; and include aircraft it has transferred
to sister carrier Continental Airlines.
   Lifland scheduled a hearing Monday on the matter for all parties
involved in Eastern's bankruptcy case and Ueberroth's attorneys.
   The key issue blocking the sale to Ueberroth was who would run
the airline in an interim period between the completion of a deal
and the airline's emergence from bankruptcy.
   ``We were not able to bridge this hurdle although both of us I
think tried to do that,'' Ueberroth said.
   According to a participant in the talks, who asked not to be
identified, court-appointed examiner David I. Shapiro recommended
Monday that U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Burton R. Lifland name former
Defense Secretary Frank Carlucci trustee.
   Texas Air Chairman Frank Lorenzo objected to the appointment of
any trustee and Lifland refused to name one without explaining why,
the source said.
   Eastern's unions have accused Lorenzo of gross mismanagement and
of stripping Eastern of vital assets since Texas Air bought the
airline in 1986, and have refused to return to work while he was in
charge. The pilots and Machinists already have petitioned Lifland
to appoint a trustee.
   Henry Duffy, president of the Air Line Pilots Association,
issued a statement from Washington saying the union was
disappointed and noting the problems that caused the strike
remained unresolved.
   ``This is but one act in a multi-act play, and the bankruptcy
judge still is running the proceedings,'' Duffy stated.
   ``I'm disappointed to say the least,'' said Wally Haber, a
Machininsts union general chairman in Miami. ``I can tell you right
now, Mr. Lorenzo would have walked away in this deal with a lot
more money than he put into Eastern Airlines. Obviously they've got
some plans to milk some more out of Eastern.''
   At Eastern corporate headquarters, management employees gathered
around television sets and expressed relief.
   ``It looks like we move on to another phase,'' veteran spokesman
James Ashlock said. ``I do think there is a certain release of
anxiety here at the base, where a great many people particularly
the non-contract people were increasingly concerned at the way the
situation had been building.''
   Lifland met earlier Wednesday with attorneys for Eastern, its
unions and the Ueberroth group to try to save the deal, saying it
represented a historic opportunity to salvage one of the nation's
biggest airlines.
   Any deal would have required full agreement from Ueberroth,
Lorenzo, Eastern's three unions and Eastern's creditors.
   Eastern has been flying only a fraction of its schedule since
its Machinists union began a strike March 4 that has been supported
by its flight attendants and pilots unions.
   In a related development Wednesday, a federal judge in Miami
upheld the Eastern's pilots participation in the Machinists strike.
The ruling by U.S. District Judge Edward Davis seriously hurt the
company's effort to get the airline flying again.
   Davis said he saw no evidence that ALPA would have gone on
strike if the Machinists hadn't.
   The company said it would ask the federal appeals court to
reject Davis' opinion, but pilots union attorneys said appellate
courts historically accept such findings of fact by lower court
judges.
   Eastern sought bankruptcy protection March 9 because of a cash
crisis stemming from the walkout and pressure from creditors.
Lorenzo has been trying to peddle the airline since then and has
indicated there have been other overtures.
   Icahn, who has been approached previously by Eastern's
Machinists about making an offer, issued a statement Wednesday
saying he remained interested in Eastern. However, he stated,
``although I might be willing to risk my capital in Eastern, I
would not be willing to pay it over to Texas Air.''
   Icahn was not available to elaborate on the statement, his
secretary said.
   Texas Air also has indicated it received a conditional offer
from Jay Pritzker, head of the Hyatt Hotel chain, after initially
getting Ueberroth's bid.
   Meanwhile, a Manhattan diamond dealer said he has formed a
partnership with an unidentified foreign airline that he said could
raise more than $250 million by the end of the week for a bid.
   Willy Censor, 62, said he had met with officials from Eastern
and U.S. Bankruptcy Court to discuss his proposal for buying the
strike-bound carrier. Eastern attorney David Boies confirmed he met
with Censor but declined to say whether the airline was taking the
bid seriously.
   Ueberroth emerged as the buyer earlier this month and a deal
appeared virtually assured, especially after his group reached
labor agreements with Eastern's striking unions following
negotiations this past weekend.
   But negotiations with Texas Air began to deteriorate Tuesday,
amid sometimes-heated discussions with Shapiro. Lorenzo and
Ueberroth walked out of discussions at bankruptcy court that
evening, hours before their self-imposed midnight deadline for
reaching agreement.
   Under five-year deals reached with Ueberroth on Monday, the
three unions _ the Machinists, ALPA and the flight attendants union
_ would have received 30 percent ownership of the airline in
exchange for about $210 million in concessions.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
